<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NASCAR To Race Today After Rain </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CONCORD, N.C. (AP) -- Instead of the roar of 750-horsepower  
engines, the overwhelming sound at Lowe's Motor Speedway was the 
pitter-patter of raindrops. 
</P>
<P>
	The steady rain, which began to fall during the early morning  
hours Sunday, forced NASCAR officials to postpone the UAW-GM 
Quality 500 until today. 
</P>
<P>
	Officials waited until two hours after the scheduled 1 p.m. EDT  
start to make the call, rescheduling the 500-mile event on the 
1 1/2-mile oval to begin at 11 a.m. today. 
</P>
<P>
	It is the first time in the 40-year history of the suburban  
Charlotte track that the fall race was postponed. The last Winston 
Cup event postponed by rain was in April 1998, in Martinsville, Va. 
</P>
<P>
	``The worst part about rain is the sitting around,'' driver Ward  
Burton said. ``You can only play so many card games, tell so many 
jokes and take so many naps. You can only look up at the sky and 
shake your head so many times. 
</P>
<P>
	``NASCAR has the weather radar on the side of their transporter,  
and people will wear out a path to it. That `nice weather for 
ducks' joke gets pretty old pretty quick, too.'' 
</P>
<P>
	With the rain washing the accumulated rubber off the track  
surface, crew chiefs spent some time worrying about their race 
set-ups. 
</P>
<P>
	``We were practicing in bright sunshine and then we had to set  
the cars up for overcast, if we ran Sunday,'' explained Brian 
Whitesell, crew chief for two-time Winston Cup champion Jeff 
Gordon. ``We're just going to have to figure it out (today).'' 
</P>
<P>
	Most of the drivers were happy NASCAR made the decision to  
postpone the start, rather than try to get it started and have a 
rain-shortened event. 
</P>
<P>
	``In April, all we had to go was one more lap and we win the  
race,'' said Jeremy Mayfield, who finished second to Jeff Burton in 
the rain-shortened race in Darlington, S.C. ``Jeff was sitting 
there all torn up, and he couldn't have gone any further. If we'd 
gotten back to green, he was done too, and we felt we were the best 
car out there.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mayfield was third, behind Burton and his brother, Ward, in the  
Darlington race last month, which was also cut short by rain. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Southern 500, who knows? Jeff was good, but so was Ward  
and so were we,'' Mayfield said. ``The sad part about that is there 
was going to be one heck of a shootout between those three cars at 
the end of that race.'' 
</P>
<P>
	If the 334-lap race did get under way, Bobby Labonte was to be  
on the pole with Rusty Wallace alongside. 
</P>
<P>
	Dale Jarrett, who owns a 251-point margin over Labonte in the  
Winston Cup standings, was to start ninth, while Mark Martin, who 
is third, 25 points behind Labonte, was fourth in the 43-car field. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
