<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dell To Focus on Core PC Business </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LAKE BUENA VISTA, Fla. (AP) -- Dell Computer Corp., the No. 1  
seller of personal computers directly to customers, says it will 
stick to its strengths despite Wall Street pressure to vigorously 
branch into areas such as computer services. 
</P>
<P>
	While Dell's financial results are among the strongest in the  
computer industry, its stock price has fallen 16 percent since 
early this year in part due to investor concerns that tumbling PC 
prices will slow galloping revenues and profits. 
</P>
<P>
	But Dell chief executive Michael Dell said Monday that computer  
services, or helping corporate customers set up and maintain their 
computer networks, will remain an adjunct and not a substitute for 
Dell's main business of selling hardware. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think we can grow in our core business and services will  
enhance that growth,'' he said in a talk before thousands of 
technology managers at the annual Gartner Group computer industry 
gathering here. 
</P>
<P>
	Dell's go-it-slow strategy contrasts with moves by IBM,  
Hewlett-Packard Co. and other major Dell rivals to attack the 
fast-growing services business. 
</P>
<P>
	Those companies are making very little money or losing money in  
the PC business. IBM last week told employees it's cutting up to 10 
percent of its PC work force after the business lost $150 million 
last quarter. Compaq Computer Corp. also is struggling to turn 
around its business. 
</P>
<P>
	But Dell expects further strong financial results from selling  
PCs due to the company's efficient, oft-copied strategy of selling 
directly to users and eliminating wholesalers and retailers. 
</P>
<P>
	Dell underscored its iconoclast strategy last month by signing a  
seven-year agreement for IBM to provide technical support to Dell's 
customers -- the Round Rock, Texas company could have instead built 
its services operation from within. 
</P>
<P>
	``I view it very, very differently'' from our competitors,  
Michael Dell said. ``We are profitable in our core hardware 
business.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Still, some analysts say the company is vulnerable to pricing  
pressures, especially since its product line focuses mainly on 
business PCs and isn't as diverse as other companies that sell, for 
instance, lots more computers to home users. 
</P>
<P>
	Dell is moving aggressively to boost sales to home users,  
though. Last quarter, the company more than doubled its sales to 
these consumers, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	And Dell said that despite the company's gradual approach, its  
services business should eventually grow from about 11 percent of 
total revenues to as much as 50 percent, though he didn't specify 
when. 
</P>
<P>
	Dell's stock price rose 1.4 percent, or 6 1/4 cents to $45.56 1/4, in  
trading on the Nasdaq Stock Market. 




  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
