<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Compaq Launches Telecom Division </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	GENEVA (AP) -- Computer manufacturer Compaq on Monday announced  
it was forming a new division to provide services to 
telecommunications companies. 
</P>
<P>
	The company said Compaq Telecommunications would bring together  
2,000 Compaq employees currently working in other divisions. Half 
of the staff would be in the United States, and the headquarters 
would be near Dallas, in the so-called ``telecom corridor.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Compaq is committed to leadership in telecommunications, and  
the new line of business reflects this,'' said Senior Vice 
President Enrico Pesatori, speaking at the Telecom 99 trade show in 
Geneva. 
</P>
<P>
	``Compaq Telecommunications starts with extensive presence in  
the telecommunications market, and leverages that with the 
company's strong experience in consumer and financie markets,'' 
</P>
<P>
	The company also unveiled its new telecommunications engine --  
the computer which keeps track of telephone calls and bills 
customers. 
</P>
<P>
	The system can handle 15,000 transactions per second as well as  
up to 40,000 customer service operators. 
</P>
<P>
	It has a capacity of 111 terabytes. A byte is a small chunk of  
computer data, and a terabyte -- 1 trillion bytes -- is the 
equivalent of 1 million unabridged dictionaries. 
</P>
<P>
	The system is operating at Compaq's customer service operation  
in Cupertino, Calif. 
</P>
<P>
	``Everyone today recognizes the importance of e-business, but  
it's Compaq that has forged ahead and actually built a full-scale 
working model of how companies can re-engineer themselves to 
actually deliver on the e-business promise,'' said Compaq Chief 
Executive Michael Capellas. 
</P>
<P>
	Capellas said he believed the large-scale hi-tech project fitted  
in perfectly well with the company's traditional business of 
high-volume, cheap computers. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's just an added value that we have. It is a natural fit to  
what we have always had traditional high strength in,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	In July Compaq announced it planned to slash up to 8,000 jobs,  
or 12 percent of its workforce, as it struggles to cut costs amid a 
$184 million loss in the second quarter of 1999 brought on by 
computer price wars and slowing sales. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
