<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Keyes Persues Underdog Quest </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ANNAPOLIS, Md. (AP) -- Discipline was so ingrained in Alan Keyes  
that when he transferred from parochial school to public school, it 
took him the entire freshman year to realize that he didn't have to 
wear a uniform. 
</P>
<P>
	Even today, as he pursues an underdog quest for the White House,  
the discipline that Keyes learned as a boy is apparent. He's a 
candidate who sticks to his message, telling people not what they 
want to hear but what he thinks they should hear. 
</P>
<P>
	Friends and political associates say his passionate conservatism  
is not a recent acquisition and that he is driven to run for 
president by a conviction that his political beliefs are correct 
and that the future of America is in doubt. 
</P>
<P>
	William Kristol, who roomed with Keyes at Harvard, remembers him  
as being a very good student, very smart, intense and already a 
committed political conservative. 
</P>
<P>
	``He'd get intensely interested in something and read about it  
for two or three weeks,'' Kristol said. ``In a way, he was always a 
little more driven than the rest of us.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Marlo Lewis, another college friend, said that intensity carries  
over to Keyes' private life. 
</P>
<P>
	``His mind is always fully engaged and operating at full  
throttle,'' Lewis said. ``Alan doesn't have any time to waste. If 
you're going to have a conversation, it had better be a worthwhile 
one.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Keyes grew up the youngest of five children. His mother was a  
schoolteacher, and his father, an Army sergeant major who served in 
three wars -- World War II, Korea, and Vietnam. They lived a typical 
Army life, moving around the country and to Italy, as his father 
was transferred from base to base. 
</P>
<P>
	Lewis said Keyes' father was a major influence on him. ``He was  
an exemplar of the military code. That partly explains Alan's very 
deep devotion to the United States,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Keyes attended parochial schools, but transferred to a public  
high school in San Antonio. 
</P>
<P>
	``There was somewhat more structure and discipline in the  
Catholic schools,'' he told an interviewer several years ago. ``But 
by the time I got to public high school that discipline was 
ingrained. I wore a white shirt, blue tie and blue pants to school 
every day my freshman year before it dawned on me I no longer 
needed a uniform.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Encouraged by a teacher, Keyes entered -- and won the American  
Legion oratorical competition, the first black to do so. He also 
was elected president of the Legion's Boys Nation, and gave 
resounding speeches in support of the Vietnam War. 
</P>
<P>
	Keyes was recruited by Cornell University, and attended the  
Ithaca, N.Y., school during the height of the Vietnam War and the 
black militant movement. 
</P>
<P>
	His disdain for anti-war protests led to him to become a  
Republican, even though his parents were Democrats. 
</P>
<P>
	Kristol said Keyes was threatened after he spoke out against the  
1969 black militant takeover of Cornell's student center during his 
freshman year. He eventually left the school, spent a year in 
Paris, and then transferred to Harvard, where he received a 
bachelor of arts degree in 1972 and a doctorate in government 
affairs in 1979. 
</P>
<P>
	Keyes can still mesmerize a crowd with his fiery oratory.  
</P>
<P>
	``There can be no doubt that the republic is coming apart,''  
Keyes told a national convention of college Republicans at the 
Watergate complex this summer. ``We have destroyed the spirit and 
soul of this nation, and the body is following.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The crowd waited for the ray of hope, the promise that if Keyes  
is elected, the nation can be turned around. They didn't get it. 
</P>
<P>
	Lewis said when Keyes prepares for a speech, ``the question he  
always puts to himself is not what do they want to hear but what do 
they need to hear.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Keyes, 49, is delivering the same unrelentingly conservative  
message he preached in his first presidential race, in 1996: 
Abortion is at the heart of the moral decay; God is the only answer 
to the nation's problems; any Republican willing to compromise on 
moral issues is worthy only of scorn. 
</P>
<P>
	His opposition to abortion and conviction that America is  
decaying morally because it has turned away from God endear him to 
many members of the Christian right, a mostly white Protestant 
group that might seem an unlikely ally for a black Catholic. 
</P>
<P>
	In private, Keyes is an accomplished singer, guitarist and piano  
player. Lewis says he has a great sense of humor. He told one 
interviewer that he likes to relax watching westerns and action 
films or reruns of ``Star Trek.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He and his wife, Jocelyn, have three children.  
</P>
<P>
	After getting his doctorate from Harvard, Keyes spent 11 years  
with the U.S. State Department. He was vice counsel in Bombay, 
India, when he attracted the attention of Jeane Kirkpatrick by 
coming to her defense when she was criticized at a meeting. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Kirkpatrick became a mentor and later brought Keyes to the  
United Nations as an ambassador to the U.N.'s Economic and Social 
Council when she was its chief delegate. 
</P>
<P>
	Keyes plunged into electoral politics by running for the U.S.  
Senate from Maryland in 1988, when he got 38 percent of the vote 
against incumbent Democrat Paul Sarbanes in the heavily Democratic 
state. 
</P>
<P>
	He spent the next four years as president of Citizens Against  
Government Waste, a national organization devoted to lower taxes 
and less government spending. Tom Schatz, who worked with Keyes and 
replaced him as president, said Keyes ``was the kind of person who 
was clearly in charge,'' but was always willing to listen to other 
people's ideas. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1992, Keyes made his second run for the U.S. Senate from  
Maryland, this time running against Democratic incumbent Barbara 
Mikulski. He got just 29 percent of the vote, and Joyce Terhes, 
then state GOP chairwoman, said his campaign suffered from his 
unwillingness to compromise or take advice. 
</P>
<P>
	Any chance he might have had for an upset ended when he decided  
to pay himself a salary of about $8,000 a month out of campaign 
funds, Ms. Terhes said. 
</P>
<P>
	``I pleaded and cajoled that he not do it. He was completely  
unwilling to compromise on that,'' she said. ``Alan was going to do 
it Alan's way, no question about that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	At a news conference with his wife, daughter and two sons  
standing behind him, Keyes defended the payments as necessary to 
support his family and charged that critics wanted to see his 
children hungry and his family living on the street. 
</P>
<P>
	Keyes was involved in more controversy in 1992 when he declared  
that the Republican senatorial campaign committee was racist 
because it would not sink money into his campaign. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Terhes said Maryland Republicans were embarrassed and upset  
by the allegation that came when they were in Houston preparing for 
the national convention. The committee sent money to other 
candidates because Keyes had no chance of winning, but ``he 
couldn't fathom that,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Since 1992, Keyes has supported his family with fees from  
speaking engagements and a syndicated radio show, which he halted 
in July, according to campaign spokeswoman Becky Fenger. 
</P>
<P>
	When associates talk about Keyes, certain words keep cropping up  
-- brilliant, a compelling orator, unwilling to compromise or take 
advice, focused on negatives and, above all, passionately committed 
to his beliefs. 
</P>
<P>
	Ellen Sauerbrey, Republican national committeewoman from  
Maryland and a supporter of GOP presidential front-runner George W. 
Bush, helped Keyes in both Senate races. 
</P>
<P>
	``Unquestionably, Alan Keyes is one of the most articulate  
people that we have running for president,'' Ms. Sauerbrey said. 
But she said he is so focused on what is wrong with the country 
that he doesn't give voters any sense of what he would do to make 
things better. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think people are looking for the Ronald Reagan promise of  
hope and opportunity rather than the lecture that the country is 
coming to an end,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Kristol, editor of the Weekly Standard, said Keyes could have  
had a successful career at a think tank, as a college professor, as 
a lobbyist, but ``he was never a go-along and get-along kind of 
guy. He always had a sense of mission.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
