<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-11 14:40:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Italy Seeks Antiquities Protection </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Italian authorities are weary of watching  
coveted antiquities disappear into the hands of American 
collectors, and they are asking the State Department for help. 
</P>
<P>
	On their side in the effort to keep these valued vases,  
figurines and pottery pieces at home is an international accord 
designed to reduce the incentive for pillage. But they are up 
against an art collectors' lobby that is attempting to keep any 
restrictions within certain limits. 
</P>
<P>
	The State Department is reviewing the Italian request and will  
convene a public session on Tuesday to hear the interested parties, 
which include archaeologists, museums and dealers. The session is 
being organized by the department's Cultural Property Advisory 
Committee, which will make its recommendations to the president. An 
early decision on recommendations is not expected. 
</P>
<P>
	The Washington Post reported Monday that New York Sens. Daniel  
Patrick Moynihan and Charles Shumer, both Democrats, have 
introduced legislation on behalf of the antiquities market that 
would complicate procedures for imposing restrictions. 
</P>
<P>
	Neither the senators nor their staffs were available for comment  
on Monday, a federal holiday. A State Department official involved 
in the issue declined comment. 
</P>
<P>
	The United States and Italy are parties to a 1970 U.N.  
Educational, Scientific, and Cultural Organization (UNESCO) accord 
on illicit trade in cultural properties. Italy is seeking American 
help because it sees the United States as the primary destination 
for its pillaged artifacts. 
</P>
<P>
	Several sources told the Post that the categories covered by  
Italy's still-secret petition embrace virtually every type of 
high-value artifact produced or found in ancient Italy. 
</P>
<P>
	This would include Attic pottery made in Greece and either  
looted by Romans or purchased by them and buried in their tombs. 
</P>
<P>
	Jerome M. Eisenberg, owner of New York's Royal-Athena Galleries  
and the publisher of the antiquities magazine Minerva, told the 
Post, ``Ancient art always traveled. We're concerned with art theft 
but (the scope of the Italian request) is absurd.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In support of their petition, Italian authorities are likely to  
seize on a 1997 case in which a New Yorker, Michael Steinhardt, 
lost his fourth century B.C. antique gold platter when a judge 
ruled it had been imported illegally into the United States from 
Italy. He paid $1.2 million for the platter in 1991. 
</P>
<P>
	The ruling is believed to have been one of the first in the  
nation to order the return of an archaeological item exported in 
violation of Italy's cultural property laws. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
