<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Hong Kong Sets Date for Stock Sales </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HONG KONG (AP) -- Hong Kong's government will start selling  
shares later this month that were acquired in a controversial stock 
market intervention in 1998 but it did not immediately announce the 
size of the sale. 
</P>
<P>
	The sale announced Monday will last from Oct. 25 to Nov. 4.  
</P>
<P>
	Hong Kong spent the equivalent of $15.1 billion on shares when  
it moved into the market in August 1998, at a time when the Asian 
financial crisis was unfolding and local officials were blaming 
speculators for big price plunges in Hong Kong. 
</P>
<P>
	The government's shareholding has since increased in value to  
about $25.6 billion as the market bounced back. 
</P>
<P>
	Hong Kong officials say they will package the shares into mutual  
funds and sell them, hopefully without harming prices on the Hong 
Kong Stock Exchange. The fund set up to sell the shares is called 
the Exchange Fund Investment Ltd. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
