<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Park's Labor Shortage Problem Fixed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN DIEGO (AP) -- SeaWorld employees in San Diego got a free trip  
on the company tab, but it wasn't to anywhere exotic where they 
could relax. 
</P>
<P>
	The 150 seasonal employees were sent by Anheuser-Busch to one of  
the brewer's other amusement parks, Busch Gardens in Williamsburg, 
Va., to help out during the busy fall season because of a labor 
shortage in that city. 
</P>
<P>
	St. Louis-based Anheuser-Busch, which owns 10 parks nationwide,  
spent about $75,000 to fly gift store clerks, ride attendants and 
fast-food workers 3,000 miles to work at the Virginia park from 
mid-September until the end of October. The company also provided 
housing and transportation for the workers. 
</P>
<P>
	The company sees the trip as an investment in keeping its San  
Diego workers, who would have been laid off when SeaWorld's 
business slowed after Labor Day, and a short-term solution to the 
labor problem in Virginia. 
</P>
<P>
	``We think it will make some of our seasonal employees want to  
come back next year and that's good for us,'' said Pamela Masters, 
SeaWorld's vice president of human resources. 
</P>
<P>
	Williamsburg has an unemployment rate of about 2 percent and  
several tourist attractions, restaurants and hotels. Jobs that pay 
between $5.75 and $12 per hour, like those at Busch Gardens, are 
plentiful, making recruiting difficult, company officials said. 
</P>
<P>
	Masters said the temporary transfer made sense because it  
provided the park skilled workers. 
</P>
<P>
	``They didn't have to go out and recruit, nor did they have to  
train workers once they got there,'' said Masters, who came up with 
the idea. 
</P>
<P>
	Jennifer Wagner, 18, who had never traveled outside Southern  
California before her cross-country trip, said, ``I looked at it as 
a chance to have an experience.'' 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
