<DOCNO> APW19991011.0024 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-11 05:40:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> 24-Yr. Term Sought for Sheinbein </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TEL AVIV, Israel (AP) -- Presenting a plea bargain, prosecutors  
asked an Israeli court today to sentence Maryland teen-ager Samuel 
Sheinbein to 24 years in prison for the brutal slaying of an 
acquaintance in 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutor Hadassah Naor said she didn't ask for the maximum,  
life in prison, because Sheinbein, 18, was a juvenile when he 
committed the crime and because he confessed, saving the state a 
lengthy trial. 
</P>
<P>
	Sheinbein's sentencing was set for Oct. 24. The three-judge  
panel at the Tel Aviv District Court was widely expected to accept 
the plea bargain, though it has the discretion to change it. 
</P>
<P>
	Maryland prosecutors have complained that the punishment is too  
light. If the Tel Aviv District Court approves the plea bargain, 
Sheinbein would be eligible for parole after serving two-thirds of 
his sentence, or 16 years. 
</P>
<P>
	Sheinbein's sentencing will wrap up a case that strained  
Israeli-U.S. relations and prompted Israel to change a law that 
bars the extradition of Israeli citizens to stand trial abroad. 
However, the change came too late to affect the Sheinbein case. 
</P>
<P>
	Sheinbein fled to Israel several days after the September 1997  
killing in Maryland and successfully fought extradition to the 
United States, saying he was an Israeli citizen through his father 
who was born in pre-state Palestine. 
</P>
<P>
	Last month, Sheinbein confessed that he bludgeoned to death his  
victim, Alfredo Tello Jr., cut up the body with an electric saw and 
hid the body parts in a nearby garage. Sheinbein's accomplice, 
Aaron Needle, committed suicide in a U.S. jail on the eve of his 
trial. 
</P>
<P>
	Sheinbein has shown little emotion in his court appearances in  
Israel. He sat in the dock quietly today, his hands cuffed and his 
eyes cast down. His parents sat in the second row and refused to 
speak to reporters. 
</P>
<P>
	Naor told the three judges that after weighing the brutality of  
the crime against Sheinbein's age, she considered 24 years a 
reasonable sentence. 
</P>
<P>
	``The punishment is severe and considerable and nears the  
maximum punishment set by law,'' Naor said. 
</P>
<P>
	Sheinbein's confession also weighed in his favor. Naor said that  
if the case had gone to trial, the prosecution would have had to 
bring about 80 witnesses, many from the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	Sheinbein could have been given a life term, but Naor said such  
a stiff term has never been imposed on a juvenile in a criminal 
case. The average sentence for a juvenile convicted of murder is 15 
to 20 years. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
