<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bears' McNown Ready for First Start </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LAKE FOREST, Ill. (AP) -- Cade McNown's wait is over, his  
apprenticeship at quarterback with the Chicago Bears is moving 
forward. He'll start his first NFL game Sunday, not necessarily 
because he's ready, but because Shane Matthews won't be. 
</P>
<P>
	Matthews, the starter the first five weeks, injured his right  
hamstring early in the fourth quarter of Sunday's stunning 24-22 
win at Minnesota as he was scrambling out of bounds. He will 
undergo an MRI on Tuesday and will definitely miss this Sunday's 
game against the Eagles. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm excited to play but not excited that Shane got hurt. That  
in itself is a terrible thing,'' McNown, the No. 12 pick in April's 
draft, said Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	``The situation now is that I have the opportunity to play a  
lot, and I look forward to it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Matthews, who became a father for the second time Monday when  
his wife Stephanie gave birth to a son, arrived at Halas Hall for 
treatment and then headed to the hospital to be with his family. 
</P>
<P>
	He was having one of his best games Sunday, going 19-of-28 for  
two touchdowns, when he was injured on a play in which he wasn't 
even hit. 
</P>
<P>
	The Bears have been phasing in McNown since the season began,  
giving him one series in each of the first three games. He played 
two series the previous week against the Saints and had been in for 
two more against the Vikings before Matthews got hurt. 
</P>
<P>
	Playing most of the fourth quarter Sunday, he finished 9-of-14  
and helped preserve the victory with a third-down scramble of 13 
yards. He was 6-of-8 for 69 yards after replacing Matthews. 
</P>
<P>
	Coach Dick Jauron said the Bears would not alter their game plan  
because of the quarterback change, but admitted that McNown's 
ability to improvise added another dimension. 
</P>
<P>
	``He built his reputation and really his draft position on  
creating big plays in college,'' Jauron said. ``So you would expect 
more down-the-field throws from him. He is obviously a very mobile 
guy and you'll see him move around.'' 
</P>
<P>
	McNown, with a contract that could pay him $22 million over five  
years, admitted that watching from the sideline has been difficult. 
</P>
<P>
	``At the same time, you understand why they were doing what they  
were doing. You stand by the coach's decision, and I believe in 
their decision, even though I wanted to be out there,'' McNown 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Jauron also could not promise Monday that Matthews would retain  
his job once he returns. It all depends on how well McNown 
performs. 
</P>
<P>
	The Bears shook up the NFC Central, ending a 10-game road losing  
streak against opponents in their division with their win Sunday in 
the Metrodome. At 3-2, Chicago is one win away from matching its 
victory total in each of the last two seasons. 
</P>
<P>
	Defensively, the Bears intercepted three passes, recovered two  
fumbles and had four sacks. 
</P>
<P>
	But there was also a long list of injuries. Besides Matthews,  
place-kicker Jeff Jaeger reaggravated a hip injury and missed three 
field goals and might be out a month. The Bears will bring in 
kickers Cary Blanchard, Jaret Holmes and Chris Boniol for tryouts 
Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Running back James Allen is out with a knee sprain. Wide  
receiver Curtis Conway and linebacker Sean Harris have sprained 
ankles and linebacker Rico McDonald a thigh bruise. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
