<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> FAA Vindicated in Consumer Lawsuit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Federal Aviation Administration had the  
authority to certify a stretched version of a Boeing airplane 
without requiring a full-scale passenger evacuation test, an 
appeals court says. 
</P>
<P>
	A consumer group backed by Ralph Nader, the Aviation Consumer  
Action Project, had challenged the FAA's decision, saying its 
reliance on mathematical analysis and a test on a shorter version 
of the Boeing 777 did not adequately ensure the safety of 
passengers. 
</P>
<P>
	But the U.S. Court of Appeals for the District of Columbia  
Circuit ruled Friday that the FAA was allowed to change its policy 
about conducting evacuations. 
</P>
<P>
	The agency's policy is that airplane builders must show new  
plane models can be evacuated within 90 seconds even if half their 
exits are blocked. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1998, the agency said that in cases in which the capacity of  
a plane is increased by more than 5 percent, manufacturers can meet 
that standard with a full-scale test or by submitting data from 
earlier tests. 
</P>
<P>
	The FAA said it planned to use such data in certifying the  
Boeing 777-300, the longest commercial airplane in the world, and 
stretched versions of the Airbus A330 and A340. 
</P>
<P>
	``Whether this test is met requires a factual determination by  
the FAA, and clearly, as methods of analysis and other 
considerations develop over time, the FAA's response to the test 
can also,'' wrote Judge Laurence H. Silberman on behalf of the 
court. 
</P>
<P>
	He added: ``In 1998, spurred on by injuries to demonstration  
participants, (the FAA) reviewed its policy and concluded that the 
situation had changed such that analysis and testing were now 
sufficient.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Boeing created the 777-300 by stretching its 777-200 with a  
33-foot fuselage section. At 242 feet, 4 inches long, the jet is 11 
feet longer than the biggest Boeing 747. The added length increased 
the aircraft's capacity from 440 passengers to 550. To accommodate 
them, Boeing added two new emergency exits. 
</P>
<P>
	Airbus lengthened its A330/340 aircraft to increase their  
capacity from 361 passengers to 440. The European aircraft maker 
did not add any new emergency exits, deciding instead to increase 
the size of an existing pair of exits. 
</P>
<P>
	The lawsuit, filed in July 1998, focused on the 777-300. The FAA  
certified it on May 4, 1998, based on an evacuation test of just 
the new passenger compartment, as well as an analysis of data 
gleaned during a full-scale passenger evacuation of the 777-200. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
