<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> DuPont Weighs Lycra Plant in Asia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SINGAPORE (AP) -- The U.S. chemical company Dupont Co. is  
considering investing about $260 million in a third Lycra 
manufacturing plant in Asia. 
</P>
<P>
	DuPont-Singapore spokesman Alan Rego said Monday that Singapore,  
Taiwan, China and Malaysia are being considered for the plant. 
Discussions are at a preliminary stage, Rego noted. 
</P>
<P>
	DuPont has already invested about $178 million in two Lycra  
plants in Singapore, opening one just last week. Lycra is a spandex 
fabric used in underwear, swimsuits and athletic apparel. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's clear that we are interested in building another Lycra  
facility in Asia,'' Rego said. ``What isn't so clear is where that 
investment will be.'' 
</P>
<P>
	DuPont Lycra vice president Steven McCracken was quoted in  
Singapore's Straits Times newspaper Monday as saying that Singapore 
``has a very good chance'' of landing the investment. 
</P>
<P>
	Rego said Singapore have the built-in advantage of having two  
Lycra facilities already in operation, which would cut down on the 
cost of building a new facility. 
</P>
<P>
	However, he noted that Singapore ``doesn't have a market'' for  
Lycra, as do Taiwan and China. He said DuPont was also in 
discussions with BASF AG in Malaysia about working jointly on a 
Lycra facility there. 
</P>
<P>
	BASF manufactures tetrahydrofuran, a chemical used in making  
Lycra. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
