<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Space Center Workers Feared Floyd </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) -- As Hurricane Floyd churned toward  
Kennedy Space Center, Roger Gillette and Roberta Wyrick barricaded 
themselves in the launch control center, fearing water more than 
wind. 
</P>
<P>
	The chief test conductors, who stayed behind to help defend NASA  
property against the storm, felt certain the space shuttle hangars 
would hold even though they were not designed to withstand Floyd's 
140-plus-mph wind. A storm surge, however, easily could damage the 
four shuttles and numerous space station components awaiting 
launch. 
</P>
<P>
	Doors to critical buildings were sealed with sandbags, and  
replacement parts for the Hubble Space Telescope and other flight 
equipment were raised off the floor. 
</P>
<P>
	Three of the space shuttles already were propped 6 feet high and  
shrouded by work platforms in the Orbiter Processing Facility. But 
Atlantis was parked on the floor of the Vehicle Assembly Building. 
Workers placed plastic bags around the landing gear, covered the 
main engines and hoped for the best. 
</P>
<P>
	At the same time, truckloads of computers were hauled from  
makeshift offices in trailers into the launch control center, and 
the van used to transport astronauts to the pad was driven into the 
Vehicle Assembly Building. 
</P>
<P>
	Newly arrived booster-rocket segments were transported back out  
in railroad cars all the way to the Florida Panhandle. Radios and 
satellite phones were distributed in case the regular phones went 
dead. Finally, the entrance gates to the space center were closed 
and locked. 
</P>
<P>
	Then the waiting game began for Gillette, Wyrick and the 103  
other space center workers who volunteered to stay behind Sept. 14 
to guard against Floyd, a monster storm. For the first time ever, 
NASA considered pulling everyone out; officials ended up paring 
down the crew to be left behind to the bare minimum. 
</P>
<P>
	The 12,400 other employees had evacuated the day before, leaving  
the space center an eerily quiet, boarded-up ghost town. 
</P>
<P>
	That's when reality began to set in, at least for Gillette.  
</P>
<P>
	``You start talking about what could happen,'' he said in an  
interview last week. ``Sixteen-foot surge. And you're thinking 16 
feet and then you start measuring up the wall where that is exactly 
and you realize, 'Uh-oh, I need to get on the third floor.' '' 
</P>
<P>
	Kennedy Space Center is a mere 9 feet above sea level and smack  
on the coast. 
</P>
<P>
	As the wind picked up and the rain pounded down, Gillette and  
Wyrick nervously flipped between The Weather Channel and local news 
broadcasts. It wasn't until almost midnight that they learned Cape 
Canaveral likely would be spared. 
</P>
<P>
	Hurricane Floyd was moving more toward the north and expected to  
pass some 100 miles offshore, with less severe wind than predicted 
and little if any storm surge. As it turned out, the maximum 
sustained wind at the space center was 66 mph, with gusts up to 91 
mph, well within the limits of NASA's critical buildings. Close to 
3 inches of rain fell. 
</P>
<P>
	At daybreak on Sept. 15, the ride-out crew ventured outside. To  
everyone's relief, damage was minimal. 
</P>
<P>
	Some 30 pieces of sheet metal were ripped off the 525-foot-high  
Vehicle Assembly Building and a glass door blew out of the 
adjoining launch control center. At one of the two launch pads, a 
door leading to electrical equipment was damaged. 
</P>
<P>
	Over at the Orbiter Processing Facility, rain had seeped through  
the ceiling and walls. But workers quickly mopped up the water; 
fortunately, there wasn't much. 
</P>
<P>
	The electricity had gone out now and then, but the mechanics who  
stayed behind to keep the systems running were able to restart 
them. Rising humidity could have damaged the shuttles and space 
station equipment. 
</P>
<P>
	Gillette and Wyrick -- and everyone else who works at Kennedy --  
realize how close they came to having their livelihoods washed 
away. 
</P>
<P>
	``You're not going to move down the coast and be able to launch  
again,'' Wyrick said. ``Where else are you going to do this?'' 
</P>
<P>
	It was the first time since Hurricane Erin in 1995 that the  
space center shut down. Hurricanes Bertha and Fran forced NASA to 
move Atlantis from the launch pad into the hangar in 1996, but no 
evacuation was ordered. None of these compared with Floyd. 
</P>
<P>
	``The thing I worry about the most is that people are going to  
get complacent again,'' said Gillette. ``I don't want one to hit 
just so they can understand what it can do. But I'd like people to 
take a look at what happened at North Carolina. That could be here, 
understand that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	NASA is heeding his words.  
</P>
<P>
	Space agency chief Daniel Goldin has ordered a review of  
building safety and hurricane procedures. Kennedy officials plan to 
bring in outside architects and engineers to evaluate all the 
structures. 
</P>
<P>
	When NASA built its steel-reinforced concrete hangars and launch  
pads in the 1960s and 1970s, it complied with standards set by the 
American Society of Civil Engineers. The structures consequently 
were designed to withstand sustained wind of no more than 105 mph 
to 125 mph. 
</P>
<P>
	After Hurricane Andrew's devastating blow to South Florida in  
1992, the society revised its guidelines to 135 mph. 
</P>
<P>
	Ideas already are kicking around the space center for the next  
time a hurricane strikes. Wyrick, for instance, wonders whether a 
shuttle would be safer atop a mobile launch platform in the Vehicle 
Assembly Building, rather than parked on the floor as Atlantis was. 
</P>
<P>
	As for flying the $8 billion space shuttle fleet to safety atop  
modified 747 jets, forget it, says Jim Comer, a shuttle worker who 
rode out the hurricane in the Orbiter Processing Facility. 
</P>
<P>
	A full day is needed to secure a shuttle on a jet, and that  
doesn't count the time needed to pull out work platforms and button 
up the ship, Comer said. Besides, he noted, with only two modified 
747s and one mating device, there's no way all four shuttles could 
get out in time. 
</P>
<P>
	NASA is considering erecting a structure that could take  
Floyd-force wind, so a small team could stay behind no matter how 
bad the hurricane and fan out as soon as the storm passed. But 
other than starting from scratch, there's little that can be done 
to the Vehicle Assembly Building and other shuttle facilities. 
</P>
<P>
	``You're talking about the storm of the century that would have  
to come through to really wipe that thing out,'' Gillette said. 
``If you try to build it for that storm, it would cost 10 times the 
amount of money and what good would it be?'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Once you get into something like that,'' he added, ``it's best  
effort, safely.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
