<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Saturn Prepares for New Model </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SPRING HILL, Tenn. (AP) -- Saturn plans to shut down its assembly  
lines in early January to gear up for production of its new sport 
utility vehicle, the company says. 
</P>
<P>
	The plant normally is idled over the Thanksgiving weekend and  
for about a week between Christmas and New Year's Day. 
</P>
<P>
	Saturn also will halt production for the first two weeks in  
January so that workers can move machinery and make other changes 
needed to add the SUV production. 
</P>
<P>
	Saturn has not said when production of the SUV will begin or  
when it will be introduced to the public. 
</P>
<P>
	All employes will still report for work during the down time,  
Saturn spokesman Bill Betts said. 
</P>
<P>
	Saturn's unique contract with the United Auto Workers says the  
plant's 7,200 or so assembly-line workers will spend down time 
during supplier strikes or other production halts doing plant 
maintenance, planning, training and other jobs. 
</P>
<P>
	The shutdown will cost Saturn at least 10 days of production.  
The plant currently builds about 1,000 cars per day. 
</P>
<P>
	The new vehicle is aimed at gaining Saturn a piece of the  
booming SUV market, as demand for the Spring Hill-built S-series 
has sagged. 
</P>
<P>
	Sales of the basic S-series Saturns fell by 4.7 percent to about  
221,000 vehicles through September, the end of the 1999 model year. 
</P>
<P>
	Strong sales of the redesigned three-door coupe helped offset  
declines in the sedan and station wagon. 
</P>
<P>
	Since Jan. 1, sales of Spring Hill-built models are off 5.8%.  
</P>
<P>
	But total Saturn sales are only down slightly due to demand for  
the new, larger, 2000-model L-series, built in Wilmington, Del. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. auto industry is reporting a 9.7 percent increase in  
sales so far this year. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
