<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Airborne E-Mail Service Planned </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- Airshow Inc., a provider of flight information  
systems, unveiled plans Monday to offer in-flight e-mail services 
for corporate jet travelers. 
</P>
<P>
	The service would allow customers to send and receive e-mail to  
an ``AirshowMail'' account that can be accessed either through a 
laptop computer or a special ``cabin management system'' provided 
by Airshow. The company made the announcement at the National 
Business Aviation Association convention in Atlanta. 
</P>
<P>
	AirshowMail will be transmitted by radio telephone to planes  
within the continental United States and by satellite 
communications to aircraft traveling internationally. 
</P>
<P>
	To meet narrow bandwidth restrictions and reduce signal  
interference, AirshowMail will compress messages prior to 
transmission. But the company is prepared to ``adapt to higher 
bandwidth technology and faster communication devices as they 
become available,'' said Skip Feher, Airshow's vice president of 
communication services. 
</P>
<P>
	The company will encrypt customers' e-mail to secure privacy  
once messages are forwarded to AirshowMail. Pricing has not yet 
been set, but customers will likely be charged a monthly or annual 
fee. The service is expected to debut in the second quarter of 
2000, the company said. 
</P>
<P>
	Airshow, based in Tustin, Calif., is a subsidiary of Burlington,  
Mass.-based Dynatech Corp. and provides map displays, text-based 
news and other real-time information to some 4,000 corporate 
aircraft. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
