<HEADLINE> Grains, Soybeans Mixed on Light Day / Board of Trade  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Grain and soybean futures finished mixed in slow  
trading Monday on the Chicago Board of Trade. 
</P>
<P>
	Volume was extremely light due to Columbus Day and Canadian  
Thanksgiving Day. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat continued its slide, dipping to an 11-week low early in  
the session amid continued concern over the weak export market. 
</P>
<P>
	Corn inched higher after weekend rains in the southern and  
central sections that were thought to have slowed harvest progress. 
The corn harvest is about 40 percent complete. 
</P>
<P>
	Soybeans benefited from a late rally in soymeal and soyoil.  
</P>
<P>
	Wheat for December delivery fell 1 1/4 cents to $2.53 1/2 a bushel;  
December corn rose 1/4 cent to $1.98 3/4 a bushel; December oats were 
unchanged at $1.08 3/4 a bushel; November soybeans rose 1 3/4 cents to 
$4.93 1/4 a bushel. 
</P>
<P>
	Beef and pork futures fell on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.  
</P>
<P>
	December live cattle fell .07 cent to 69.75 cents a pound;  
October feeder cattle fell .35 cent to 80.90 cents a pound; 
December lean hogs fell .43 cent to 44.87 cents a pound; February 
pork bellies fell 1.83 cents to 62.02 cents a pound. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
