<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Jaguars, Jets Need To Wake Offenses </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J (AP) -- It should have been a prime-time  
shootout between two of the NFL's most dangerous offenses. 
</P>
<P>
	Instead, tonight's rematch of last January's AFC playoff game  
between the Jacksonville Jaguars and New York Jets just might take 
on a defensive bent. That's pretty much the way things have gone 
for both teams recently: decent defense, disappointing offense. 
</P>
<P>
	``Offensively, we need to go back to the drawing board,''  
Jaguars guard Ben Coleman said of an attack that ranks 13th overall 
and 20th in passing. 
</P>
<P>
	``This offense should click better than it has,'' added Keenan  
McCardell, who along with Jimmy Smith forms one of the league's 
best receiving duos. 
</P>
<P>
	Quarterback Mark Brunell hasn't approached his usual Pro  
Bowl-caliber play. While the running game, whether it be with Fred 
Taylor, slowed by a hamstring injury, or James Stewart, has been 
staunch, the Jaguars have only five passing plays for 25 yards or 
more. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are 3-1 and certainly not playing as well as we'd like to  
on the offensive side of the ball,'' said Brunell, who reportedly 
has been feuding with coach Tom Coughlin; both sides deny it. ``But 
we are 3-1 and very pleased with that. Our goals haven't changed, 
but it's time to focus and concentrate on getting better, and I 
think we will do that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	They've gotten a whole lot better on defense under new  
coordinator Dom Capers, the former head coach in Carolina and the 
mastermind of Pittsburgh's strong units in the early 1990s. At 
times, in fact, a defense that rarely had a pass rush or made big 
plays in the past has been downright fearsome. 
</P>
<P>
	Yes, better than the Jaguars offense.  
</P>
<P>
	``Their defense has been impressive, what they have done,'' Jets  
coach Bill Parcells said. ``When they got the lead, they were 
particularly effective. They have an excellent pass rusher in Tony 
Brackens. They have improved their secondary since last year.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Brackens was a one-man wrecking crew at Pittsburgh last weekend,  
with three forced fumbles, recovering one, 2 1/2 sacks and 11 tackles. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was really one of the outstanding performances on defense I  
have seen in a long time,'' Parcells said. 
</P>
<P>
	He saw some fine work from his own defense at Denver on Oct. 3,  
when the Jets got their first victory after three losses. They 
forced six turnovers and never let the Broncos get on track in the 
second half, when the Jets took control. 
</P>
<P>
	That defense might get a boost from regular nose tackle Jason  
Ferguson, expected back from an ankle injury. 
</P>
<P>
	``Just like a loss causes you to second-guess,'' linebacker  
Bryan Cox said, ``a win causes you to exude confidence. You can put 
yourself on a roll, that's what winning does, it adds a certain 
amount of confidence.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Usually, the Jets' confidence rides high when they have the  
ball. But season-ending injuries to quarterback Vinny Testaverde 
and running back-kick returner Leon Johnson and a broken foot 
suffered at the end of the preseason by receiver Wayne Chrebet -- he 
is doubtful to make his return tonight -- ravaged the offense. 
</P>
<P>
	Although Rick Mirer is getting more comfortable at quarterback  
and the running game was solid at Denver, New York doesn't have the 
look of a powerhouse. 
</P>
<P>
	``It would be nicer if we were 3-1 instead of 1-3,'' Mirer said.  
``There'd be a lot more laughs.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
