<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bauer Takes Shots at Forbes, Bush </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MANCHESTER, N.H. (AP) -- Republican presidential hopeful Gary  
Bauer said Monday that rival Steve Forbes should dismiss any 
campaign workers who may have helped spread rumors that Bauer had 
an affair with an aide. 
</P>
<P>
	``If Steve Forbes had character, I think he would fire some  
people,'' Bauer told reporters as he began a three-day bus tour of 
the state. ``(My wife) Carol and I had to go through a miserable 
couple of weeks.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Charlie Jarvis, a former Bauer aide who now is an unpaid  
consultant for the Forbes campaign, said two weeks ago that Bauer 
spent ``hours and hours and hours behind closed doors with a young, 
single woman.'' He made no further specific allegations. Bauer has 
denied allegations by former campaign staffers that he had an 
``inappropriate'' relationship with a female campaign aide. 
</P>
<P>
	Bauer blamed the Forbes campaign for the remarks, which he  
called character assassination, and said such unfounded attacks 
prevent a serious discussion of the issues. Anyone involved in 
spreading the rumors should be fired, Bauer said. 
</P>
<P>
	Forbes spokesman Greg Mueller said no one in the Forbes campaign  
spread the rumors, and that no one would be dismissed. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've had no involvement. Our focus is not Gary Bauer; this is  
a Bush-Forbes race,'' Mueller said. ``Nobody in our campaign is 
going to get fired for something he or she did not do.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bauer said Monday the GOP race is narrowing, with Forbes, Texas  
Gov. George W. Bush and himself as the key players. There now are 
eight Republicans seeking the nomination. 
</P>
<P>
	Bauer, a former aide to President Reagan, also said Bush should  
apologize for remarks he made against Republicans in Congress, and 
that Forbes' flat-tax proposal would benefit only the rich. 
</P>
<P>
	``I watched Governor Bush give a major speech in which he  
attacked the Republican Congress in the same rhetoric that Ted 
Kennedy or Barney Frank or President Clinton would use,'' Bauer 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush recently criticized the House Republicans' plan to alter a  
tax credit for the working poor in order to help balance the 
budget. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
