<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Blazers' Grant Out for Season Opener </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TUALATIN, Ore. (AP) -- Brian Grant can only run at about  
half-speed, and you could barely slide an envelope under his 
sneakers on a jump shot. 
</P>
<P>
	Right now, the Portland Trail Blazers see that as significant  
progress for their power forward. 
</P>
<P>
	Grant, recovering from offseason surgery on his left knee, won't  
play in Tuesday's exhibition game against the Seattle SuperSonics 
in Corvallis. He hopes to be in uniform when the Blazers open the 
regular season at Vancouver on Nov. 2. 
</P>
<P>
	``I can't really tell you if it'll happen or not, but we're  
making very, very good progress from last week,'' Grant said after 
Monday's practice. ``I've started doing more stuff on the court, 
some jogging up and down, a lot more jumpers instead of standing 
still, and moving around. So that's a big step for me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Grant had soreness in his knee throughout the playoffs, which  
ended when the Blazers were swept by the San Antonio Spurs in the 
Western Conference finals. His return was delayed two weeks ago by 
an upper respiratory infection that required hospitalization. 
</P>
<P>
	Grant wants to play, but doesn't want to risk re-injuring the  
knee. His teammates agree. 
</P>
<P>
	``I know it's hard for him being injured because the one thing  
about being injured -- because I've been through it before too -- is 
that you don't feel like you're part of the team,'' point guard 
Damon Stoudamire said. ``When he gets ready, he'll come back. I 
just hope he doesn't try to come back too soon.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Grant said he's bound to be sluggish when he returns.  
</P>
<P>
	``Even when I get back, it won't be like I'll be the Brian that  
you guys saw at the end of the season, where I was really sharp,'' 
he told reporters. ``I'll probably miss a lot of little layups and 
get tired a lot, because I didn't go through this week of 
conditioning like they did. The stuff I do is good, but it's 
nothing like playing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Grant sat out Sunday's scrimmage, played before about 6,000 fans  
at Memorial Coliseum. 
</P>
<P>
	The absence of the 6-foot-9 Grant and 6-11 backup center Kelvin  
Cato, who was traded to Houston along with five other Blazers for 
Scottie Pippen, left the Blazers with a lack of big men, so they 
signed free agent center Joe Kleine last week to a one-year, $1 
million contract. 
</P>
<P>
	The 37-year-old Kleine played well in the scrimmage, scoring 14  
points and grabbing 14 rebounds. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was by no means the best I can do, or the best the team can  
do,'' said Kleine, who had offers from other teams but jumped at 
the chance to back up Arvydas Sabonis with the Blazers. 
</P>
<P>
	``They're a serious contender, and the guys on their team are  
all good guys,'' Kleine said. ``There's just lot of unselfish 
people, and I know from experience that being around those types of 
people make basketball a lot more enjoyable.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Coach Mike Dunleavy said he was impressed by the Blazers' energy  
in the scrimmage but not with their level of conditioning. He said 
none of the starters in Tuesday's exhibition -- Stoudamire, Pippen, 
Sabonis, Steve Smith and Rasheed Wallace -- will play more than 30 
minutes. 
</P>
<P>
	``The most important part is to get conditioning, to get guys  
playing with each other and keep everybody healthy,'' Dunleavy 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Dunleavy said he likely will trim the camp roster of 19 players  
beginning this weekend. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
