<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> 2004 Politics Cloud Calendar Fight </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) -- While some people are complaining that  
it's still too early to worry about next year's election, the 2004 
political season already is casting its shadow on a fight between 
Iowa and New Hampshire over the 2000 voting calendar. 
</P>
<P>
	The quadrennial wrangling over primary and caucus dates is an  
exercise in posturing and bluffing, aimed at getting the attention 
from candidates and the media that comes with holding the nation's 
first tests of presidential candidates' political strength. 
</P>
<P>
	Iowa and New Hampshire traditionally have banded together to  
guard their early position, with Iowa's first-in-the-nation 
caucuses leading off and New Hampshire following eight days later 
with the nation's opening primary. 
</P>
<P>
	Now they're squabbling and could risk losing it all.  
</P>
<P>
	It began when New Hampshire set its primary Feb. 1, the day  
after Iowa's Jan. 31 caucuses. That surprised everyone, because 
most assumed the primary would be Feb. 8. 
</P>
<P>
	For weeks, officials have sought to pressure New Hampshire to  
relent and move to Feb. 8, but they are now giving up on that in a 
delicate minuet that almost certainly will see the Iowa caucuses 
move to Jan. 24. 
</P>
<P>
	New Hampshire Democratic Party Chairwoman Kathy Sullivan will  
make her case before a national party rules committee this week, 
but she said the squabble with Iowa has angered many who are 
looking for an excuse to jumble the lineup of caucuses and 
primaries that launch the presidential nominating season. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm convinced that this will hurt us in the long term,'' she  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Some national party leaders agree.  
</P>
<P>
	``If this flap between New Hampshire and Iowa had not occurred,  
then there would have still been a discussion as to whether or not 
Iowa or New Hampshire should retain their first-in-the-nation 
status,'' said Tom Sansonetti, chairman of the Republican National 
Committee's Rules Committee. 
</P>
<P>
	``But now, as a result of what has happened and from the  
comments I've received in just the last 10 days, I'd say the 
chances for New Hampshire and Iowa losing their first-in-the-nation 
status have increased markedly,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	After a few days of squabbling, officials in both states appear  
to be looking to put the best face on the situation. 
</P>
<P>
	Iowa Gov. Tom Vilsack, who initially refused to consider  
changing dates, relented Monday and said holding the caucuses on 
Jan. 24 would be fine as long as the requisite logistics can be put 
in place. 
</P>
<P>
	``They just need to be sensitive to making sure Iowa puts its  
best foot forward,'' Vilsack said. ``If (Iowa) can do that on Jan. 
31, fine. If it can do that on Jan. 24, fine, whatever they 
decide.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He also said Iowa and New Hampshire officials should have a  
quiet conversation about avoiding such disputes in the future. One 
Iowa Democratic official who spoke on condition of anonymity 
conceded that ``the damage has been done'' and said officials are 
seeking a quick way out of the situation. 
</P>
<P>
	That's because national Democratic Party officials next month  
will begin talking about primary and caucus calendars for the 2004 
campaign. 
</P>
<P>
	Vilsack said it's crucial that Iowa and New Hampshire band  
together and offer assurances that the ongoing bickering will not 
be repeated. 
</P>
<P>
	``If we can get that kind of consensus out of this, then maybe  
Iowa and New Hampshire would be in a stronger position to make the 
case that they should serve as the nation's first primary and first 
caucus,'' Vilsack said. 
</P>
<P>
	There's a fight every four years for the honor to be first, as  
other states seek some of the attention paid to Iowa's leadoff 
caucuses and New Hampshire's initial primary. 
</P>
<P>
	The attention gives a huge boost to both political parties in  
the two states, creates something of a cottage industry with 
millions of dollars being spent by candidates and the media and 
helps polish the image of the two states in the national limelight. 
</P>
<P>
	That's why Vilsack argued that Iowa should worry about the  
immense logistical details involved in switching the date -- 
everything from providing hotel rooms to party-run centers for 
tabulating the votes. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	EDITOR'S NOTE -- Mike Glover has covered presidential campaigns  
in Iowa and other states for The Associated Press since 1984. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
