<DOCNO> APW19991011.0079 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-11 00:10:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> US Gymnasts Barely Make Medal Round </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TIANJIN, China (AP) -- Twice it came down to the very last  
routine. 
</P>
<P>
	Vanessa Atler clinched a place for the United States women's  
team in the World Gymnastics Championships medal round with a 9.762 
in the floor exercises Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	Then, John Roethlisberger appeared to do the same for the men  
with a 9.525 on the high bar Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	His performance was enough to move the Americans ahead of  
Ukraine and Germany into third place, with 1997 silver medalist 
Belarus and defending bronze medalist Russia among the teams yet to 
compete. 
</P>
<P>
	The top six teams advance to the medal round, and a fifth-place  
standing at this point would have been troublesome to the 
Americans. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier Monday, Japan moved into second place in the men's  
standings with 226.382 points, well behind three-time defending 
champion China's 230.546. The Americans had 224.594, Ukraine 
224.322, Germany 224.245, and Romania 223.831. 
</P>
<P>
	Roethlisberger gained the chance for the decisive high-bar  
routine after teammate Blaine Wilson's 9.562 and Chris Young's 
9.550. Sean Townsend managed only 8.762 and Yewki Tomita 8.450. The 
top four scores count toward the team total. 
</P>
<P>
	Wilson was solid all day, scoring 57.048, including a 9.625 on  
the parallel bars, and stood fifth among individuals with 19 of 46 
teams still to compete. 
</P>
<P>
	China's Yang Wei, who had a 9.8 in the vault, led individuals  
with 57.649, while teammate Huang Xu had 57.299, and Bulgaria's 
Jordan Jovtchev and Japan's Yoshihiro Saito were tied at 57.074. 
</P>
<P>
	Roethlisberger, like Wilson a four-time national champion, did  
not compete in all six events. But he also had a 9.650 on the 
pommel horse, a 9.237 on the rings and a 9.212 on the parallel 
bars. 
</P>
<P>
	For the American women, Atler was not even aware of their  
perilous position when she went into her final floor exercise 
routine. 
</P>
<P>
	It was the fifth best score of the qualifying round in that  
event, and enough to lift the Americans into fifth place, behind 
defending champion Romania, Russia, Ukraine and China. They also 
were safely into the top 12 that qualify for next year's Olympics 
in Sydney. 
</P>
<P>
	The Americans encountered problems on the uneven bars, an event  
where falls cost the 17-year-old Atler the national championship 
this year and last. 
</P>
<P>
	This time, she made no mistake, scoring 9.475, while U.S.  
champion Kristen Maloney faltered, falling the wrong way out of a 
handstand. The mistake wasn't apparent to the audience, but she 
scored only 8.975. 
</P>
<P>
	In the same event, Jamie Dantzscher managed only 8.312 as she  
lost her grip on the lower bar at one point. Elise Ray recouped 
vital points with a .600, and later contributed 9.612 in the floor 
exercises. 
</P>
<P>
	Maloney and Atler both scored 9.612 on the balance beam, and  
Maloney had 9.750 on the floor. 
</P>
<P>
	Sunday's competition ``just got all the jitters out,'' said the  
17-year-old Atler, who stood seventh in individual standings with 
38.367. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're all really inexperienced, we were all really nervous,''  
Atler said. ``Now that we've got it done, and we know what it's 
like, we can just go out there and have fun.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Atler said she wasn't aware of the importance of her final floor  
exercise, and Maloney added: ``We didn't really look at the 
scoreboard. We wanted to focus on our routines.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I always get a little nervous, especially being second to the  
last and last on every event. ... But I know I can hit for our 
team,'' Maloney said. 
</P>
<P>
	Since the four best scores from five gymnasts in each event  
count toward the total, Atler's 7.762 on the floor made a 
difference of 0.625 to the U.S. score, which was just 0.313 ahead 
of sixth-place Australia and 0.594 better than non-qualifier Spain. 
</P>
<P>
	The medal round comes Tuesday, and coach Kelly Hill said, ``We  
have time now to work out the glitches and we will be fine.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Joining Atler in the 36 who will compete for the individual  
all-around title were Ray, 12th in qualifying with 37.848, and 
Maloney, 16th with 37.768. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. women's team finished sixth in the last World  
Championships in 1997, down sharply from its 1996 Olympic gold 
medal. 
</P>
<P>
	It is competing without Jennie Thompson, third place finisher in  
the U.S. championships. She reinjured her left ankle in practice 
here, and was replaced by 16-year-old Morgan White. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991011.0080 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-11 12:56:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Cowboys' Irvin Hospitalized </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- Michael Irvin lay motionless on the Veterans  
Stadium turf, his teammates gathered in prayer. 
</P>
<P>
	Irvin was hospitalized overnight with swelling in his spine  
after a scary neck injury in the Dallas Cowboys' 13-10 loss to the 
Philadelphia Eagles on Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	Cowboys trainer Jim Maurer said today that Irvin was expected to  
be released from the hospital this afternoon and would fly back to 
Dallas. His condition will be better known after he visits a spine 
specialist Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Maurer said it's too early to tell when Irvin would play again,  
but ``we're optimistic he'll be back this year.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Irvin will wear a collar-style neck brace for about a week.  
He'll be stiff and sore as he awaits the swelling to go down and 
fluid that has built up to drain. 
</P>
<P>
	Maurer said Irvin did have some limited motor skills immediately  
after the injury, but he could use his hands and feet before 
leaving the field strapped to a stretcher. 
</P>
<P>
	Once word reached the Dallas locker room that Irvin was able to  
move his arms and legs, his teammates expressed their anger at fan 
reaction that was boorish and outrageous even by Philadelphia 
standards. 
</P>
<P>
	Incredibly, many fans cheered while Irvin lay on the artificial  
turf for about 15 minutes late in the first quarter. It was enough 
to anger even a player on the home team. 
</P>
<P>
	``I know our fans pride themselves on being tough, but that  
wasn't tough,'' said Eagles receiver Charles Johnson, whose 28-yard 
TD reception from Doug Pederson was the game-winner with 67 seconds 
left. ``That was just plain ignorant. ... I was embarrassed to 
stand on the sideline.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Some people need to grow up,'' an angry Emmitt Smith said.  
``Some people need to grow up and find some inner peace, because 
there is no peace in watching somebody suffer.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Irvin, a five-time Pro Bowl selection and vocal member of the  
best Dallas teams this decade, caught an 8-yard pass from Troy 
Aikman with 5:16 left in the first. He tried to shake a tackle from 
Bobby Taylor and was hit on the head by safety Tim Hauck as he hit 
the ground. 
</P>
<P>
	As Taylor tackled Irvin, Hauck's shoulder pad collided with the  
side of Irvin's helmet -- a clean hit that twisted Irvin's head 
awkwardly as it hit the ground. 
</P>
<P>
	Irvin was taken to the spinal unit at Thomas Jefferson Hospital,  
where an MRI showed swelling in the spinal cord in two places near 
the base of the skull and a herniated disc. He had movement in his 
feet and hands, team doctor Robert Vandermeer said. 
</P>
<P>
	Irvin hasn't missed a game due to injury since the 1990 season,  
but Vandermeer reacted angrily when asked if Irvin could play next 
week. Vandermeer said he didn't know if the injury was 
career-threatening. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think so, but I don't know,'' Vandermeer said. ``We'll  
have to evaluate him.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Team owner Jerry Jones, who rode in the ambulance with Irvin,  
said it was ``way too speculative'' to say how serious the injury 
was. The hospital barred a reporter from entering, and would 
release no information. 
</P>
<P>
	``I felt that he needed me, because I knew his family would want  
me to be there to give them information,'' Jones said. 
</P>
<P>
	Irvin, who moved his fingers and appeared to be talking as he  
lay on his back, was fitted with a neck brace and loaded onto a 
stretcher as his teammates circled in prayer across the field. 
</P>
<P>
	After the Cowboys' prayer group broke up, Sanders nervously  
circled his fallen teammate while medical staff attended to him. As 
Irvin was loaded into the ambulance, ``He said that he was going to 
be OK and he gave me the old Michael Irvin smile,'' said Sanders, 
disgusted by the cheers from Philadelphia fans. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's ignorance and stupidity, but I expect that,'' Sanders  
said. ``That's one of the sick things about our game, that people 
can actually cheer upon a man's injury.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Vandermeer said the herniated disc probably was an old injury  
that wasn't caused by the collision. 
</P>
<P>
	The catch was the 750th of Irvin's career, tying Charlie Joiner  
for ninth in NFL history. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991011.0081 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-11 12:56:00 </DATE_TIME>
