<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Coffee Up 7 Pct. on Brazil Drought  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Coffee futures jumped 7 percent Monday on New York's Coffee,  
Sugar &AMP; Cocoa Exchange on heightened fears of crop damage from the 
extended drought in parched Brazil. 
</P>
<P>
	In other markets, natural gas futures soared as the cold-weather  
season drew nearer in the northeastern United States, and hog 
futures fell. 
</P>
<P>
	Coffee prices are bouncing back after hitting their lowest level  
since early 1994 on Oct. 1, when investors were anticipating a big 
harvest. 
</P>
<P>
	Now those assumptions have been revised as a dry spell shows no  
signs of ending. Showers occurred in some coffee regions over the 
weekend, but rainfall amounts were less than expected and forecasts 
say central Brazil will remain dry through much of this week. 
</P>
<P>
	The drought, coming at a time when moisture is key to a good  
crop, has increased talk of severe soil deficiency. 
</P>
<P>
	``It seems that quite a lot of traders were reassessing the  
situation and saying, 'Hey, it might be more serious than had been 
believed,''' said Arthur Stevenson, an analyst for Prudential 
Securities in New York. 
</P>
<P>
	``They have had sub-optimal rainfall in Brazil for an awfully  
long time,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	After soaring 9 percent in frantic trading soon after opening,  
reaching the highest level since early September, coffee for 
December delivery rose 5.85 cents for the day to close at 90.95 
cents a pound. 
</P>
<P>
	In light Columbus Day trading on the New York Mercantile  
Exchange, natural gas futures moved higher after forecasts said a 
cold snap could head into northern New England, increasing heating 
fuel consumption. 
</P>
<P>
	Heating oil and other energy futures also were higher.  
</P>
<P>
	Crude futures, reeling from a 16 percent decline last week  
attributed to increased OPEC production, rallied after initially 
extending their slide to $20.55 a gallon. 
</P>
<P>
	A senior U.S. Energy Department official said it was unlikely  
the United States will sell crude oil from the Strategic Petroleum 
Reserve to counter rising heating oil prices, despite President 
Clinton's comment last week that he was considering such a sale. 
</P>
<P>
	Crude oil for November delivery rose 37 cents to $21.27 a  
barrel; November heating oil rose 1.16 cents to 54.88 cents a 
gallon; November unleaded gasoline rose 1.11 cents to 60.26 cents a 
gallon; November natural gas rose 13.3 cents to $2.825 per 1,000 
cubic feet. 
</P>
<P>
	In London, North Sea Brent crude rose 53 cents to $21.23 a  
barrel on the International Petroleum Exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	Hog futures retreated on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange on  
signals that retail demand isn't keeping up with output. 
</P>
<P>
	December lean hogs fell .43 cent to 44.87 cents a pound;  
February pork bellies fell 1.83 cents to 62.02 cents a pound. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991011.0086 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-11 20:00:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Tokyo Stock Prices Advance / Japanese Stocks  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- The dollar fell against the yen Tuesday morning  
amid waning expectations that Japan's central bank will take 
significant action to stem the yen's rise. Tokyo stock prices 
advanced. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar traded at 106.42 yen, 1.04 yen below its level of  
107.46 yen late Friday in Tokyo and below 106.68 yen late in New 
York on Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average rose 42.57 points,  
or 0.24 percent, to 18,104.75 at the end of the morning session 
Tuesday. The index closed down 74.37 points, or 0.41 percent, on 
Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Tokyo financial markets were closed Monday for a national  
holiday. 
</P>
<P>
	In currency trading, the dollar was weaker amid diminishing  
expectations that the Bank of Japan, which is holding a policy 
board meeting Wednesday, will increase the domestic money supply as 
a way to slow the ascent of the yen, which has soared in recent 
months. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar has regained some ground against the Japanese  
currency since last month when finance ministers from major 
countries expressed concern about the yen's strength. 
</P>
<P>
	But the gains have been limited due to market skepticism about  
the ability of the Bank of Japan to take steps to bring the yen 
back down. 
</P>
<P>
	Financial authorities fret that too steep a rise in the yen  
could derail a budding economic recovery here by reducing demand 
for Japanese goods abroad as a stronger currency makes them more 
expensive. Japan is struggling to emerge from its worst economic 
downturn in 50 years. 
</P>
<P>
	In other currencies, the euro was trading at 113.32 yen at late  
morning, below 114.68 yen late Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	In stock trading, the Nikkei average opened slightly stronger  
following gains in high-technology shares on Wall Street and on 
hopes for the government's new economic stimulus package. 
</P>
<P>
	The government's new economic stimulus package, currently being  
hammered out among political leaders, is expected to total more 
than $94.3 billion with about $46.9 billion in direct fiscal 
stimulus. 
</P>
<P>
	On Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial average fell 1.58  
points to close Monday at 10,648.18. Spurred by a rise in the 
semiconductor sector, the technology heavy Nasdaq composite index 
rose 29.48 points to 2,916.05, surpassing its all-time closing high 
of 2,887.06, set Sept. 10. 
</P>
<P>
	The broader Tokyo stock price index of all issues listed on the  
first section rose 12.67 points, or 0.83 percent, to finish the 
morning session at 1,543.50. The TOPIX closed up 5.79 points, or 
0.38 percent, on Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	The yield on the benchmark 10-year Japanese government bond rose  
to 1.7850 percent from Friday's finish of 1.7650 percent. Its price 
fell 0.17 point to 99.26. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991011.0087 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-11 08:40:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> KGB Spy List Reaches Parliament </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ROME (AP) -- Giving in to pressure to make public a list of 261  
Italians who allegedly spied for the KGB, Italy's government turned 
the documents over to a parliamentary commission on Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Although the commission is to work in secrecy, the move is  
considered a first step toward making the documents public. 
</P>
<P>
	Italy's conservative opposition has criticized Premier Massimo  
D'Alema's center-left government for trying to keep the documents 
secret to protect members of the former Communist Party who are now 
in the government. 
</P>
<P>
	The documents -- written by KGB archivist Vasili Mitrokhin, who  
fled to Britain in 1992 -- were allegedly given to Italy by Britain 
in 1996. Italy's premier during that period, European Union 
President Romano Prodi, said he was never informed. 
</P>
<P>
	Last week, promising not to cover up the truth, the government  
turned the documents over to prosecutors in Rome for investigation. 
</P>
<P>
	Former Premier Silvio Berlusconi's conservative forces insist  
the names should be made public immediately. Many center-left 
politicians also back publication of the names. 
</P>
<P>
	The government has promised to do so, but only after prosecutors  
and the parliamentary commission evaluate the credibility of the 
documents. News reports said the documents were not original, but 
copies. 
</P>
<P>
	The documents reportedly include the names of government  
officials, journalists and diplomats. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991011.0088 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-11 00:50:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Red Sox Back In It; Is Pedro Next? </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- There's only one comeback that could top what the  
Boston Red Sox have done this October -- Pedro Martinez taking the 
mound in Game 5. 
</P>
<P>
	Martinez, who pulled himself out of the series opener with a  
strained back muscle, said he wants to pitch in Monday night's 
decisive game at Jacobs Field even if it's just in relief. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've got to wait,'' Martinez said after the Red Sox evened the  
series at 2-2 on Sunday night with a 23-7 thrashing of the 
Cleveland Indians. ``If the results are from one day to the other 
like today, I have no doubts whatsoever that I'll be in there.'' 
</P>
<P>
	On Saturday, Martinez could hardly play a game of catch as he  
tested the sore muscle under his right shoulder blade for the first 
time since leaving after four innings of Game 1. He came away 
discouraged, and it appeared baseball's most dominant pitcher might 
have to call it a season. 
</P>
<P>
	But he said his shoulder improved dramatically on Sunday and  
came away from a pregame workout encouraged he had gotten much 
better. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's still tingling, but you never pitch perfect,'' said  
Martinez, who went 23-4 during the regular season. ``I just hope 
the way I threw for eight minutes today I can throw for eight more 
from the mound.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Red Sox will start Bret Saberhagen in Game 5 against  
Cleveland's Charles Nagy, reprising the matchup of Game 2 pitchers. 
</P>
<P>
	Saberhagen lasted just 2 2-3 innings as Cleveland pounded Boston  
11-1 to take a 2-0 lead in the series. 
</P>
<P>
	``I didn't throw that many innings the last time out,'' he said.  
``So hopefully tomorrow maybe I won't be feeling as good and I'll 
be able to calm down a little bit and stay within myself and make 
some better pitches.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Saberhagen knows that with the season on the line, Martinez  
might try to get the Red Sox to the ALCS. 
</P>
<P>
	``Pedro is very determined to pitch,'' Saberhagen said. ``So I  
would guess he is going to pitch sometime soon.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Red Sox fans hope it's tonight. They began chanting, ``We want  
Pedro, We want Pedro'' in the fifth inning of Sunday night's 
blowout. 
</P>
<P>
	As it happens, the Indians couldn't have a better pitcher  
starting Game 5 than Nagy. 
</P>
<P>
	The right-hander with the self-deprecating sense of humor and  
wicked sinker is 10-1 in his career against Boston with a 3-0 mark 
in the postseason. 
</P>
<P>
	``Charlie is a big-game pitcher,'' reliever Steve Karsay said.  
``I've been saying that all year and now we've got him going in the 
biggest game of the year. 
</P>
<P>
	Nagy's seven solid innings in Game 2 went overlooked when the  
Indians pounded the Red Sox 11-1. Now, his performance will be 
scrutinized pitch by pitch. 
</P>
<P>
	Like Bartolo Colon, shelled in Game 4, Nagy will be pitching on  
three days' rest. He said the short turnaround might have some 
advantages. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm a different type of pitcher than Bartolo,'' he said.  
``He's a power pitcher so when he gets more rest, he's stronger out 
there. Myself, I'm a sinker ball guy. That's what they say, anyway. 
The less rest you have, the better your sinker's going to be. We'll 
see.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
