<HEADLINE> Grains, Soybeans Mixed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Grain and soybean futures were mixed early today  
on the Chicago Board of Trade, with the U.S. and Canadian holidays 
keeping trading to a minimum. 
</P>
<P>
	Volume was expected to be light throughout the day due to  
Columbus Day and Canadian Thanksgiving Day. 
</P>
<P>
	Corn and soybeans were both under pressure from ideal harvesting  
conditions in the Midwest, although rain in the southern and 
central sections over the weekend was thought to have slowed 
progress. The corn harvest is about 40 percent complete. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat continued last week's decline, falling to new contract  
lows. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat for December delivery fell 3/4 cent to $2.54 per bushel;  
December corn fell 1/4 cent to $1.98 1/4 a bushel; December oats rose 3/4 
cent to $1.09 1/2 a bushel; November soybeans rose 1/2 cent to $4.92 a 
bushel. 
</P>
<P>
	Pork futures were sharply lower at the Chicago Mercantile  
Exchange, while beef futures were little changed. 
</P>
<P>
	December live cattle were unchanged at 69.82 cents a pound;  
October feeder cattle fell .15 cent to 81.10 cents a pound; 
December lean hogs fell .97 cent to 45.90 cents a pound; February 
pork bellies fell 1.25 cent to 62.60 cents a pound. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
