<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> More Radioactive Leakage in Japan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- A ventilator at the site of Japan's worst-ever  
nuclear accident spewed small amounts of radioactive particles into 
the air for 12 days before it was turned off, the operator said 
today. 
</P>
<P>
	The ventilator leak at the nuclear fuel reprocessing plant  
northeast of Tokyo was discovered Friday, but the operator waited 
until today to turn off the exhaust fan and seal over the opening, 
officials said. 
</P>
<P>
	``We were discussing how to cope with the situation, because the  
level of radioactivity outside the plant was low,'' said Shinji 
Saeki, an official with operator JCO Co. 
</P>
<P>
	The ventilator had been running since the major accident on  
Sept. 30, in which at least 49 people were exposed to radiation and 
three plant workers were hospitalized. Residents surrounding the 
plant were forced to evacuate. 
</P>
<P>
	Saeki said that radioactive iodine 131, measuring twice the  
safety limit, was detected last week in the opening of the exhaust 
vent. Radioactive iodine can cause thyroid disease. 
</P>
<P>
	A monitor 50 yards away from the plant, however, detected iodine  
131 at just 0.01 the safety level. 
</P>
<P>
	Saeki said the leak did not endanger people living near the  
plant. Today, JCO sealed up the windows and doors of the plant, in 
Tokaimura, 70 miles northeast of Tokyo, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The investigation into the Sept. 30 accident has centered on the  
plant's stunningly lax safety standards. Critics also have blamed 
JCO and authorities for not warning residents sooner of the danger, 
and of failing to adequately protect them. 
</P>
<P>
	Last month's accident occurred when workers at the plant failed  
to follow guidelines for handling radioactive materials and set off 
an uncontrolled atomic reaction. 
</P>
<P>
	JCO has been under intense scrutiny for apparently ordering  
workers to skip crucial security steps to save time, and media have 
speculated that the company's operating license will be revoked. 
</P>
<P>
	The accident, which followed a string of smaller incidents at  
Japanese nuclear facilities, has driven fears about the country's 
atomic safety to new heights. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
