<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 3 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Monday, Oct. 11, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	Gore Counting on Labor Endorsement  
</P>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Al Gore, having already secured the  
endorsement of the Food and Commercial Workers Union, is all but 
assured the nod from the other members of the AFL-CIO, campaign 
directors for the Democratic presidential nominee said. ``The UFCW 
endorsement makes it look very good,'' said campaign chairman Tony 
Coelho. AFL-CIO President John Sweeney, who has made clear his 
desire for the Gore endorsement, also sounded satisfied that the 
votes are all moving his way. The United Auto Workers, Teamsters, 
Electrical Workers, and, perhaps, the Machinists, remained 
uncertain votes, labor and political operatives said. 

</P>
<P>
	Internet Plan Spurs Privacy Fear  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Engineers designing a new way to send  
information across the Internet want to include a unique serial 
number from each personal computer within every parcel of data, an 
idea that privacy advocates fear could lead to tracing of senders' 
identities. Critics warn the move could potentially strip away a 
measure of anonymity enjoyed by computer users who dial into 
Internet providers. The proposal by the Internet Engineering Task 
Force would include the unique serial number for each computer's 
network connection hardware as part of its expanded new Internet 
protocol address. The IETF's top engineers say the ``privacy 
concerns are overrated.'' 

</P>
<P>
	Peacekeepers Deny Killing Policeman  
</P>
<P>
	DILI, East Timor (AP) -- International peacekeepers today blamed  
anti-independence militants for provoking bloodshed on the East 
Timor border that has heightened tensions between the foreign 
forces and the Indonesian military. The peacekeepers denied the 
Indonesian army's claim that a squad of Australian troops killed 
one Indonesian policeman and wounded four in yesterday's clash and 
that the incident happened in Indonesian-controlled West Timor. If 
Indonesian police had been directly involved, it would have been 
the first clash between international troops and Indonesian forces 
since the deployment of the foreign peacekeepers to East Timor on 
Sept. 20. 

</P>
<P>
	NATO Chief Wants Stronger Europe  
</P>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- NATO's incoming leader says strengthening European  
security forces and increasing the number of troops available for 
deployment will be one of the alliance's top priorities. George 
Robertson, who takes over as secretary-general this week, noted 
that the alliance is stretched to the limit after deploying 40,000 
troops in Kosovo. Robertson, 53, currently Britain's defense 
secretary, is scheduled to take over the NATO helm Thursday. He 
replaces Javier Solana, who is ending his four-year term a few 
months early to take up the new European Union post of foreign 
policy coordinator. 

</P>
<P>
	AMA Says Its Union Will Not Strike  
</P>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- The American Medical Association says when it  
launches its new physicians' union later this year, there will be 
no strikes and no recruiting of doctors. The AMA House of Delegates 
voted in June to form a union for doctors because of complaints 
that insurance companies prevent them from prescribing the best 
care, overload them with paperwork and cut their compensation. But 
most of the nation's 650,000 doctors are ineligible to join a union 
because they are self-employed. Federal antitrust laws ban 
collective bargaining by the self-employed. 

</P>
<P>
	Disabled Lobsterman Returns to Sea  
</P>
<P>
	SOUTH BRISTOL, Maine (AP) -- Fourteen months after a highway  
crash killed his cousin and left Danny Reed a quadriplegic, the 
20-year-old Reed has returned to sea as skipper of a 36-foot boat 
designed and equipped to accommodate his disability. Five 
generations of Reed's family gathered for the launching of the new 
craft built around a high-tech helm seat donated by a New York 
businessman, also a longtime lobsterman. Danny began lobster 
fishing when he was 15, but his days at sea appeared to have ended 
on Aug. 29, 1998, when the pickup truck in which he was riding with 
his cousin veered into a ditch and rolled over. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Up 19  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Just before 3 p.m. EDT, the Dow industrials were  
up 19.00 at 10,668.76. Declining issues on the New York Stock 
Exchange led advancers 1,607-1,243. The Nasdaq was up 23.60 to 
2,910.17. 

</P>
<P>
	Cowboys' Irvin Hospitalized  
</P>
<P>
	PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- Dallas Cowboys receiver Michael Irvin is  
expected to be released from the hospital today after undergoing 
observation following a neck injury he sustained in a game against 
Philadelphia yesterday. Irvin was injured in the first quarter when 
he caught a pass, then tried to shake a tackle and was hit on the 
head by safety Tim Hauck as he hit the ground. He was hospitalized 
with swelling in his spine. Cowboys doctors said his condition will 
be better known after he sees a spine specialist. Dallas' trainer 
said it's too early to tell when Irvin would play again, but 
``we're optimistic he'll be back this year.'' 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by VINCENT CINISOMO  
  	   	
</P>
