<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dollar Falls in Thin Trading </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The dollar fell against the yen Monday as  
traders anticipated little action from the Bank of Japan this week 
to stem the yen's rise. The dollar also fell against most other 
major currencies. 
</P>
<P>
	Trading was light as Japanese markets were closed for a national  
holiday and U.S. banks and bond markets were closed in observance 
of Columbus Day. 
</P>
<P>
	In late New York trading, the dollar was quoted at 106.68 yen,  
down from 107.56 yen late Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Hopes are diminishing that the Bank of Japan, which is holding a  
meeting Wednesday, will take strong action such as increasing the 
money supply as a way to slow the ascent of the yen, which has 
soared in recent months. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar has gained back some ground against the yen after  
finance ministers from major countries expressed concerns about the 
yen's rise late last month. But the gains have been limited due to 
market skepticism about the ability of the Bank of Japan to bring 
the yen back down. 
</P>
<P>
	The euro was quoted at $1.0648, up from $1.0622 late Friday.  
</P>
<P>
	The dollar also was quoted at 1.4987 Swiss francs, down from  
1.5022, and 1.4730 Canadian dollars, down from 1.4715. The British 
pound rose to $1.6529 from $1.6520. 
</P>
<P>
	Currencies of the 11 countries participating in the euro are no  
longer traded separately and are tied to the euro by a fixed rate. 
Based on Monday's euro rate, the dollar was worth: 1.8370 German 
marks, down from 1.8412; 6.1610 French francs, down from 6.1752; 
and 1,818.61 Italian lire, down from 1,822.80. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
