<HEADLINE> AP Financial News at 9:10 a.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Monday, Oct. 11, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	Cheaper Internet Devices Predicted  
</P>
<P>
	GENEVA (AP) -- The boom of the Internet will be further fueled by  
newer, cheaper browsing devices appearing on the market as well as 
by industry investments that will greatly expand transmission 
capacity, government and business leaders said yesterday. Wu 
Jichuan, Chinese minister of information industry, told the global 
meeting that China had made great strides in expanding its 
telecommunications networks, but that much work remains to be done 
to give more Chinese access to the Internet and other services. 
Industry leaders at the United Nations-sponsored Telecom 99, the 
biggest gathering yet of information technology industries, noted 
that products such as the new WAP-based mobile phone may be part of 
the solution for China and other developing countries. The cellular 
phone, using the ``Wireless Application Protocol,'' allows the user 
to see information from the World Wide Web in the phone's small 
display window. 

</P>
<P>
	Lucent Plans Mobile Phones in China  
</P>
<P>
	BEIJING (AP) -- China's Konka Group and Lucent Technologies Inc.  
have agreed to develop an advanced mobile phone for the Chinese 
market, the state-run Xinhua News Agency reported. They plan to 
develop a phone ``characterized by high speed data transmission, 
advanced language and image processing technology, and very low 
energy consumption,'' Xinhua said in a report late yesterday. Konka 
is one of China's largest makers of home appliances, specializing 
in color televisions for export, and lists B-shares for foreign 
investors on the Shenzhen stock exchange. 

</P>
<P>
	Colt's To Exit Retail Gun Business  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The Colt's Manufacturing Co., inventor of the  
six-shooter, plans to stop taking orders for most of its retail 
handguns so it can limit its liability in lawsuits, according to 
published reports. The company plans to reduce dramatically the 
number of commercial weapons it makes and focus instead on selling 
mainly to the military, law enforcement agencies and collectors, 
who account for the bulk of its business. Colt's 144-year-old 
retail gun business effectively will be stopped and the company 
will cancel seven product lines, partly because it is having 
trouble paying suppliers, an unnamed senior Colt's executive told 
The New York Times in today's editions. 

</P>
<P>
	Spending on Machine Tools Falls  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Spending on machine tools in August fell 1.5  
percent from the previous month and was down 11 percent from the 
year-ago August, according to a study by two industry groups 
released today. Companies spent an estimated $435 million for 
machine tools in August, the Association for Manufacturing 
Technology and the American Machine Tool Distributors' Association 
said in a joint statement. That fell well short of the $442 million 
for July and the $489 million spent in August 1998. Year to date, 
machine tool consumption is down 35 percent from the same period a 
year ago, totaling $3.6 billion. 

</P>
<P>
	British Airways Orders 12 Airbuses  
</P>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- British Airways said Monday it is paying $412  
million for 12 new 100-seat Airbus A318s to replace some of its 
aging Boeings on short haul routes. British Airways said it has put 
an option on another 12 Airbus A318s. The British carrier said in a 
statement that it chose the Airbus jet, which is powered by Pratt 
and Whitney engines, ``for its superior economics, flexibility and 
commonality with the rest of our short haul fleet.'' 

</P>
<P>
	Russia Makes IMF Loan Payment  
</P>
<P>
	MOSCOW (AP) -- The Russian government made an $83 million payment  
to the International Monetary Fund, the Finance Ministry said in a 
statement today. Russia is the IMF's biggest debtor, with more than 
$15 billion in outstanding loans. The country's latest loan with 
the IMF, an 18-month $4.5 billion arrangement, has been delayed 
following allegations of money laundering in Russia. Russian 
officials have said payments due to the IMF through the end of the 
year would be unaffected by any delay in loan disbursements. The 
latest payment was made Friday, the ministry said. 

</P>
<P>
	DuPont Weighs Lycra Plant in Asia  
</P>
<P>
	SINGAPORE (AP) -- The U.S. chemical company Dupont Co. is  
considering investing about $260 million in a third Lycra 
manufacturing plant in Asia. DuPont-Singapore spokesman Alan Rego 
said today that Singapore, Taiwan, China and Malaysia are being 
considered for the plant. Discussions are at a preliminary stage, 
Rego noted. DuPont has already invested about $178 million in two 
Lycra plants in Singapore, opening one just last week. Lycra is a 
spandex fabric used in underwear, swimsuits and athletic apparel. 

</P>
<P>
	Hong Kong Sets Date for Stock Sales  
</P>
<P>
	HONG KONG (AP) -- Hong Kong's government will start selling  
shares later this month that were acquired in a controversial stock 
market intervention in 1998 but it did not immediately announce the 
size of the sale. The sale announced today will last from Oct. 25 
to Nov. 4. Hong Kong spent the equivalent of $15.1 billion on 
shares when it moved into the market in August 1998, at a time when 
the Asian financial crisis was unfolding and local officials were 
blaming speculators for big price plunges in Hong Kong. 

</P>
<P>
	Asian Stock Markets Close Mixed  
</P>
<P>
	HONG KONG (AP) -- Asian stock markets closed mixed today, with  
the key index in Hong Kong slumping ahead of an announcement of the 
sale of the stock shares the government acquired when it propped up 
the market last year. In Japan, the financial markets were closed 
for a national holiday. Hong Kong's blue-chip Hang Seng Index fell 
119.70 points, or 0.9 percent, closing at 12,992.72. The Jakarta 
market's Composite Index fell 0.7 percent, or 4.177 points, to 
584.060. The Kuala Lumpur Stock Exchange's Composite index rose 
3.55 points, or 0.5 percent, to 747.39. 

</P>
<P>
	Stock Markets Open, Bond Markets Closed  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Government offices and most banks are closed  
today, Monday, Oct. 11, in observance of Columbus Day. Stock 
exchanges are open. But bond markets and commodity trading in 
financial contracts are closed. Financial markets are open in most 
other countries. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Rose 376 Last Week  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks overcame a volatile start to the session  
Friday and closed sharply higher as investors shrugged off worries 
about inflation and turned their focus to positive earnings news 
expected next week. The Dow Jones industrial average gained 112.71 
at 10,649.76. The blue-chip index rose 376.76 this week. Broader 
stock indicators also moved higher. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 rose 
18.38 to 1,336.02, and the Nasdaq composite index gained 25.87 to 
close at 2,886.57. All three indexes had their best weekly gains 
since the week ending July 2, when the Dow climbed 586.68. 

</P>
