<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Deports Saudi Bombing Suspect </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A Saudi dissident who reneged on a deal to  
cooperate with U.S. investigators was deported to Saudi Arabia to 
face charges of helping in an attack that killed 19 U.S. airmen, 
the U.S. and Saudi governments announced Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Hani al-Sayegh left the United States on a U.S. government  
aircraft late Sunday evening from Atlanta, where he had been 
detained for the last two years. Accompanied on the flight by FBI 
and immigration service agents, he arrived in Riyadh, Saudi Arabia, 
on Monday, the Justice Department said. 
</P>
<P>
	In Riyadh, Saudi Interior Minister Prince Nayef told the Saudi  
Press Agency, ``The suspect is now in the hands of Saudi justice 
and he will be interrogated just like any other suspect. He will be 
tried according to Islamic law.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Prince Nayef said his government has ``specific evidence and  
information that confirm the involvement of al-Sayegh in the unjust 
terrorist act in the city of Khobar about three years ago.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Al-Sayegh is suspected by Saudi authorities of driving a car in  
June 1996 that signaled an explosives-filled truck when to pull up 
beside the Khobar Towers complex near Dhahran, Saudi Arabia, where 
U.S. airmen and their families lived. 
</P>
<P>
	Al-Sayegh, 30, says that he was not involved in the bombing and  
that he and his 28-year-old brother, Mohammed, have been tortured 
in Saudi jails. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. government said it does not have evidence it can use in  
U.S. courts to charge al-Sayegh in the attack. 
</P>
<P>
	Last week, U.S. circuit courts here and in Atlanta turned down  
his last-minute appeals to delay deportation. 
</P>
<P>
	He claimed that as a politically active opponent of the Saudi  
monarchy he would be tortured there in violation of the United 
Nations Convention on Torture, which both countries have signed. 
</P>
<P>
	Attorney General Janet Reno said she received assurances from  
the Saudis he would not be tortured and would receive a fair trial. 
U.S. authorities were promised access to him in Saudi Arabia to 
make certain he was not tortured. 
</P>
<P>
	The government told the appellate courts that the deportation  
was a political question to be resolved by Reno and Secretary of 
State Madeleine Albright and was not within court jurisdiction. 
</P>
<P>
	Meantime, al-Sayegh's family was having trouble finding him a  
lawyer in Saudi Arabia. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are still looking,'' his wife, Hakima al-Qatri, said Monday  
by telephone from her home in the eastern Saudi city of Qatif. 
</P>
<P>
	She said al-Sayegh spoke with her and their two children,  
Sukeina, 7, and Mustapha, 5, last week. His daughter asked him to 
bring back a Barbie doll. His son asked for a motorized 
remote-control car, al-Qatri said. 
</P>
<P>
	``He asked me to buy the presents for them and tell them it was  
a gift from their father,'' she said. ``Hani said, `Don't worry 
about me. We'll be together soon. I am innocent, and God will take 
care of things.''' 
</P>
<P>
	Saudi lawyers said al-Sayegh's case is politically sensitive  
and, unless the authorities asked for their services, they do not 
dare get involved. 
</P>
<P>
	Al-Qatri has not seen al-Sayegh since July 1996, when they all  
lived in Iran. That year, al-Sayegh went to Kuwait, while his wife 
and children visited relatives in Saudi Arabia. Al-Sayegh later 
moved from Kuwait to Canada. 
</P>
<P>
	There, he cut a deal with U.S. officials that called for him to  
plead guilty to participating in an unrelated plot against 
Americans in Saudi Arabia that was never carried out. 
</P>
<P>
	In June 1997, Canada expelled al-Sayegh for alleged terrorist  
activity. Reno allowed him into the United States solely for 
prosecution under the deal. 
</P>
<P>
	Upon arrival, he reneged on the deal, claiming he had not  
understood it, knew nothing about the Khobar attack and was out of 
Saudi Arabia when the bombing occurred. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
