<DOCNO> APW19991011.0122 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-11 12:40:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Fed Regulators Eye Bank Mergers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Regulators are weighing changes to deal with  
the huge banks being formed by mergers that could hurt the economy 
if they fail, Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan told bankers 
Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Greenspan said in a speech that ``significant changes are in the  
pipeline'' in banking supervision by U.S. regulators and their 
foreign counterparts. 
</P>
<P>
	The changes point to a ``multitrack approach'' to oversight of  
banks, since they vary significantly in size, business strategy and 
penchant for risk, the central bank chief said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Even among the largest banks, no two institutions have exactly  
the same risk profiles, risk controls or organizational and 
management structure,'' Greenspan said in the speech to the 
American Bankers Association's annual convention in Phoenix. Copies 
of his speech to the banking industry's biggest trade group were 
released in Washington. 
</P>
<P>
	Because banks vary so widely, he said, government oversight  
needs to be ``customized for each (financial) institution: the more 
complex an institution's business activities, the more 
sophisticated must be our approach to prudential oversight.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Greenspan said such flexibility is especially needed in the case  
of ``megabanks'' resulting from mergers which, he said, ``create 
the potential for unusually large systemic risks in the national 
and international economy should they fail.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Regulators such as the Fed must walk a line between exercising  
adequate oversight of big banks and regulating them excessively in 
a way that smothers innovation and competition, he suggested. 
</P>
<P>
	``Such a heavier hand would also blunt the ability of U.S. banks  
to respond to crisis events,'' Greenspan said. ``Increased 
government regulation is inconsistent with a banking system that 
can respond to the kinds of changes that have characterized recent 
years.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Jim McLaughlin, director of regulatory affairs for the bankers'  
group, said afterward the Fed chairman's speech ``has gotten the 
industry thinking.'' 
</P>
<P>
	An outline of the changes being mulled by U.S. and foreign  
regulators was released for public comment in June by an 
international group of bank supervisors based in Basel, 
Switzerland. But Greenspan's speech put the issue in clearer 
perspective, McLaughlin said by telephone from Phoenix. 
</P>
<P>
	He also said U.S. bankers support Greenspan's push for federal  
regulators to consult with the industry on developing new standards 
for banks to disclose details of their assets. 
</P>
<P>
	Big bank mergers have been occurring at a rapid pace in this  
country, with recent multibillion-dollar consolidations including 
those in which banking giant Citicorp merged with brokerage-insurer 
Travelers Group; NationsBank Corp. and BankAmerica Corp. combined; 
and Banc One Corp. and First Chicago joined. 
</P>
<P>
	Critics, including consumer advocates such as Ralph Nader and  
some lawmakers, have asserted that the mergers have increased the 
likelihood of future taxpayer bailouts of big financial 
institutions that fail. 
</P>
<P>
	Beyond responding to the rise of huge banks, Greenspan said,  
``few changes'' are needed to the current system of regulation for 
the vast majority of banks in the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. Comptroller of the Currency John D. Hawke, who oversees  
nationally chartered banks, told the bankers' group that regulators 
see some signs of risk spreading in the banking industry despite 
high earnings and hefty assets. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have been particularly concerned with the high degree of  
reliance some banks are placing on optimistic assumptions about 
future cash flows,'' Hawke, who spoke after Greenspan, was quoted 
as saying by Dow Jones Newswires. 
</P>
<P>
	Last month, the Federal Reserve warned banks and directed its  
examiners to watch for signs that risky bank loans are piling up. 
The central bank took the action a day after Fed Governor Laurence 
Meyer warned that some banks may be counting too much on the 
economic boom continuing. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
