<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Results From Presidential Poll </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Some results from a CNN/USA Today/Gallup poll released Monday on  
the 2000 presidential race. When results don't total 100 percent, 
the remainder either didn't know or refused to answer. 

</P>
<P>
	Which of these candidates would you be most likely to support  
for the Democratic nomination for president in the year 2000? 
</P>
<P>
	--Al Gore, 51 percent  
</P>
<P>
	--Bill Bradley, 39 percent  

</P>
<P>
	Asked of 468 who are Democratic or are leaning Democratic.  

</P>
<P>
	(Gore led Bradley 63 percent to 30 percent in a CNN/USA  
Today/Gallup poll in mid-September.) 
</P>
<P>
	------	 

</P>
<P>
	Which of these candidates would you be most likely to support  
for the Republican nomination for president in the year 2000? 
</P>
<P>
	--George W. Bush, 60 percent  
</P>
<P>
	--Elizabeth Dole, 11 percent  
</P>
<P>
	--John McCain, 8 percent  
</P>
<P>
	--Steve Forbes, 4 percent  
</P>
<P>
	--Gary Bauer, 3 percent  
</P>
<P>
	--Pat Buchanan, 3 percent  
</P>
<P>
	--Alan Keyes, 3 percent  
</P>
<P>
	--Orrin Hatch, 2 percent  

</P>
<P>
	Asked of 413 who say they are Republican or leaning Republican  

</P>
<P>
	(Bush has had roughly this lead over the field since early May  
when he led Dole by a 2-1 margin.) 
</P>
<P>
	------	 

</P>
<P>
	If Al Gore were the Democratic Party's candidate and Texas Gov.  
George W. Bush were the Republican Party's candidate, who would you 
be more likely to vote for? 
</P>
<P>
	--Gore, 40 percent  
</P>
<P>
	--Bush, 56 percent  

</P>
<P>
	If Bill Bradley were the Democratic Party's candidate and Texas  
Gov. George W. Bush were the Republican Party's candidate, who 
would you be more likely to vote for? 
</P>
<P>
	--Bradley, 42 percent  
</P>
<P>
	--Bush, 54 percent  

</P>
<P>
	The telephone poll of 976 adults nationwide was taken Oct. 8-10  
and has an error margin of plus or minus 3 percentage points. The 
error margin on the Democratic and Republican party races is plus 
or minus 5 percentage points. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
