<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Knicks' Sprewell Rejoins Team </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Latrell Sprewell's teammates want an  
explanation, even though the fans seem ready to forgive and forget. 
</P>
<P>
	Sprewell was back on the court Monday for the New York Knicks  
after his unexcused, underexplained absence from the first week of 
training camp, but the scars in the locker room from his seven days 
of selfishness were not yet healed. 
</P>
<P>
	Coach Jeff Van Gundy addressed the team and told them the matter  
merits more discussion, and the rest of the players wondered 
whether Sprewell would stand before them and take the heat. 
</P>
<P>
	``Some discussion should take place out of respect,''  
tri-captain Allan Houston said. ``We want to hear something from 
him, but we're not going to pull teeth. I'm not going to lose sleep 
by him not coming forward, but we would like to hear from him.'' 
</P>
<P>
	What the Knicks heard instead were the roars of some 8,000 fans  
when Sprewell took the court for warmups and threw down a tomahawk 
dunk on his first touch in the layup line. 
</P>
<P>
	A windmill jam came next, followed by two more dunks in a  
36-minute scrimmage and a couple of brief bursts of the lightning 
quickness that makes Sprewell such a dangerous offensive weapon. 
</P>
<P>
	As he sat on the bench next to Van Gundy, Sprewell even turned  
and grinned at a fan who yelled ``You gotta start Spree, Jeff.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But while Sprewell remained nonchalant and remorseless about his  
absence, it remained an issue that could potentially splinter the 
team into pro-Latrell and anti-Latrell factions. That was why Van 
Gundy, acutely aware that the Knicks were a fractured unit last 
season, told his team it should air its grievances now. 
</P>
<P>
	``Latrell should address the team about his explanation, because  
there is no excuse. He knows that,'' Van Gundy said. ``And it 
should generate a discussion of what the team wants this year. 
</P>
<P>
	``Weak teams give in to adversity, so it's much bigger than this  
one thing. On any problem, are we going to confront issues and 
problems? Or are we going to grumble about it on the back of the 
bus within our own little groups?'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sprewell said he had spoken privately with a couple of his  
teammates, a few of whom greeted him with hugs in the locker room. 
</P>
<P>
	One of those who did not find the time to embrace him was Marcus  
Camby, one of Sprewell's better friends on the team last season. 
</P>
<P>
	``We definitely have to sit down and talk so we can hear his  
explanation,'' Camby said. ``There were probably people down there 
(at training camp in Charleston, S.C.) who were (upset) that he 
wasn't there doing two-a-days, but now that he's here don't hold 
your tongue. Everybody had something to say when he wasn't here. 
Now that he's here, let's see if those same people step up.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That will depend on whether Sprewell decides to stand up and  
address the team. He has already explained to the coach, the 
general manager and the media that he missed training camp because 
he decided to drive from Oakland, Calif., to Milwaukee to see his 
newborn son, Billy, and to pick up some things before continuing on 
to New York, where he arrived Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've talked to a couple guys individually, but I really  
haven't decided how to handle this,'' Sprewell said. ``I don't know 
if I want to sit them all down at once and do it. I'm not a guy 
that likes giving speeches, but I'll talk to the guys. For me, it's 
not as big of an issue as people are making it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sprewell shot 6-for-10 in the scrimmage and scored 18 points.  
John Wallace had 20 points, Houston added 17 and Mirsad Turkcan had 
14. The scrimmage was free to the public, with most of the crowd 
was comprised of students enjoying a day off because of the 
Columbus Day holiday. 
</P>
<P>
	As young as the crowd was, it showed how hip it was to recent  
Knicks history by booing newly acquired center Andrew Lang -- the 
player who committed a hard foul on Patrick Ewing in December, 
1997, causing him to break his wrist. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991011.0133 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-11 20:00:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Red Sox, Indians Tied 8-8 in 5th </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CLEVELAND (AP) -- The return of Pedro Martinez, a severe shoulder  
injury to Kenny Lofton and five homers highlighted the first six 
innings as Cleveland and Boston were tied 8-8 in Monday night's 
deciding fifth game of their AL division series. 
</P>
<P>
	Both teams picked up where the Red Sox left off in their 23-7  
win Sunday night, in which Boston had 24 hits. 
</P>
<P>
	The Indians outhomered the Red Sox 3-2 in the first three  
innings as they took an 8-7 lead. Jim Thome hit two homers, giving 
him four in the series. That moved into third place in postseason 
homers with 16, two behind Mickey Mantle and Reggie Jackson. 
</P>
<P>
	Travis Fryman also homered for Cleveland, while Nomar  
Garciaparra hit a two-run homer and Troy O'Leary hit a grand slam 
for Boston. 
</P>
<P>
	The winner moves on to face the New York Yankees in Wednesday's  
opener of the best-of-7 AL championship series at Yankee Stadium. 
</P>
<P>
	Monday's slugfest settled down when Cleveland's Sean DePaula  
entered the game in the top of the fourth and Martinez came in to 
start the bottom of the inning. 
</P>
<P>
	Martinez, baseball's best pitcher this year, hadn't pitched  
since last Wednesday, when he left Cleveland's 3-2 win after four 
innings of Game 1 with a strained muscle beneath his right shoulder 
blade. 
</P>
<P>
	In his first three innings Monday, he struck out four and  
allowed no runs, no hits and two walks. DePaula pitched the fourth, 
fifth and sixth, allowing no runs, no hits. 
</P>
<P>
	Lofton left in the top of the fourth with a dislocated left  
shoulder when he slid head first after first baseman Mike Stanley 
fielded a grounder and flipped to Martinez, covering first base. 
</P>
<P>
	Cleveland's center fielder was called out and lay face down on  
the ground for several minutes before being helped off the field by 
assistant trainer Jim Warfield. Dave Roberts replaced Lofton in the 
top of the fifth. 
</P>
<P>
	Bret Saberhagen and Charles Nagy, both starting on three days'  
rest for the first time this season, didn't last long. 
</P>
<P>
	Saberhagen, the MVP of the 1985 World Series when he pitched a  
complete-game victory for Kansas City in Game 7, left trailing 5-2 
with no outs in the second. Nagy, 3-0 in his postseason career 
against Boston, left with an 8-7 lead with a runner on second and 
no outs in the fourth. 
</P>
<P>
	The Red Sox went ahead 2-0 in the first when Garciaparra's homer  
scored Brian Daubach, who had singled after going 0-for-6 Sunday 
night at Fenway Park. 
</P>
<P>
	The Indians quickly erased the lead with three runs in the  
bottom of the inning. Lofton singled, stole second and scored on 
Omar Vizquel's double. Two outs later, Thome hit a 477-foot homer. 
</P>
<P>
	Cleveland made it 5-2 in the second when a single by Wilfredo  
Cordero and a homer by Fryman chased Saberhagen. 
</P>
<P>
	Then it was Boston's turn as it took a 7-5 lead with five runs  
in the third. A walk to Trot Nixon, a single by Jose Offerman and a 
fielder's-choice grounder by John Valentin produced the first run. 
Daubach doubled and Garciaparra was walked intentionally, loading 
the bases. 
</P>
<P>
	Then O'Leary, 0-for-5 on Sunday and 2-for-17 in the series, hit  
Nagy's first pitch for the second grand slam of the series, 
Boston's first in postseason play. Thome hit one in Cleveland's 
11-1 win in Game 2. 
</P>
<P>
	The Indians regained the lead in the bottom of the third against  
Derek Lowe when Robert Alomar and Manny Ramirez hit back-to-back 
doubles and Thome hit his second homer. Ramirez, whose 165 RBIs 
were the most in the majors since 1938, had been 0-for-17 in the 
series before the double. 
</P>
<P>
	Boston tied the game in the fourth when Darren Lewis' leadoff  
double knocked out Nagy. DePaula then walked Offerman and Lewis 
wandered off second. As he rushed back, catcher Sandy Alomar's 
throw to second went into center field, allowing Lewis to reach 
third. Lewis scored the tying run on Valentin's sacrifice fly. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
