<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Disabled Lobsterman Returns to Sea </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SOUTH BRISTOL, Maine (AP) -- The spinal cord injury that put  
Danny Reed in a wheelchair didn't crush his desire to be a 
lobsterman. 
</P>
<P>
	Fourteen months after a highway crash killed his cousin and left  
Reed a quadriplegic, the 20-year-old Reed has returned to sea as 
skipper of a 36-foot boat designed and equipped to accommodate his 
disability. 
</P>
<P>
	The Shawna Beth, named for Reed's fiancee, was built at the  
Farrin Boat Yard in Walpole and was lowered into the water last 
week at this fishing village. 
</P>
<P>
	Five generations of Reed's family gathered for the launching of  
the gleaming white-and-blue fiberglass craft built around a 
high-tech helm seat donated by a New York businessman, also a 
longtime lobsterman. 
</P>
<P>
	The project was overseen by retired lobsterman Philip Reed, who  
initially had doubts about his grandson's insistence that he would 
return to lobstering. But Danny's unwavering determination won the 
elder Reed over. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's a natural-born lobster fisherman,'' he said. ``This is  
the only thing that's keeping him going. This is giving him 
something to look forward to.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Lobster fishing has been a way of life for Reed's family. Danny  
began hauling traps at age 15. He later went out on his own as 
skipper of his father's boat. 
</P>
<P>
	But his days at sea appeared to have ended on the night of Aug.  
29, 1998, when the pickup truck in which he was riding with his 
cousin, Shane Simmons, 17, veered into a ditch and rolled over as 
the two headed home from a fair. 
</P>
<P>
	Simmons, the driver, was killed, and Reed faced months of  
rehabilitation. 
</P>
<P>
	Reed visited several boatyards before meeting late last year  
with Bruce Farrin, who was impressed with the young fisherman's 
determination. 
</P>
<P>
	``We wound up playing it by ear,'' said Farrin, who had never  
before undertaken such a project. 
</P>
<P>
	The project's key element was the custom-made, motor-driven  
chair that Reed can move in multiple directions: front and back, 
side to side and up and down. 
</P>
<P>
	Based on the limited range of motion in Reed's arms,  
boatbuilders positioned the seat to allow him access to a pod of 
electronic engine controls that enable him to steer the boat and 
operate its throttle. 
</P>
<P>
	Reed also has another set of controls in the arm of the chair.  
And on a calm, sunny day, he can edge his shoulder outside the 
cabin and steer from the control station outdoors. 
</P>
<P>
	A four-point harness is designed to hold him securely in the  
chair, even in choppy seas. 
</P>
<P>
	The seat was built by Stidd Systems Inc., of Greenport, N.Y.,  
which has pioneered the development of ergonomic marine seating for 
the U.S. Navy and U.S. Coast Guard. 
</P>
<P>
	Stidd's president, Walter Gezari, worked with Philip Reed to  
design his grandson's chair -- but soon realized that the $10,000 
cost was beyond the Reed family's budget. He decided to make the 
chair a gift. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm grateful to Danny for having given us the opportunity to  
do something that makes us feel this good,'' said Gezari. 
</P>
<P>
	Two dozen people were on hand Tuesday for the launching of the  
Shawna Beth and the dockside lobster picnic that followed, 
including Reed's 91-year-old great-grandmother, Mildred Reed, and 
his nephew Ethan, a toddler. 
</P>
<P>
	Reed and his father, Danny Sr., plan to fish about seven months  
of the year, between June and December or January, setting up to 
800 traps in the waters of Muscongus Bay. They also plan to take 
the Shawna Beth further out to sea to fish for tuna. 
</P>
<P>
	Shawna Beth Maker cracked a champagne bottle across the bow  
minutes before the boat that bears her name hit the water. The 
couple have set a July 15 wedding date. 
</P>
<P>
	After the boatbuilders finished their last adjustments, Farrin  
and Maker carried Reed out of his wheelchair, over the gunwale and 
into the seat from which he will pilot his new boat. 
</P>
<P>
	``It feels good,'' he said, reaching forward to the controls.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
