<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> 'Double Jeopardy' Tops Box Office / Box Office  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- ``Double Jeopardy'' won the box office battle  
of marital betrayal films. 
</P>
<P>
	The Ashley Judd-Tommy Lee Jones movie about a vengeful woman  
striking back at her double-crossing husband was the No. 1 film for 
the third straight weekend, taking in $13.6 million. 
</P>
<P>
	``Double Jeopardy'' edged ``Random Hearts,'' which debuted in  
second place with $13.1 million. ``Random Hearts'' stars Harrison 
Ford and Kristin Scott Thomas as unlikely lovers thrown together 
after their cheating spouses are killed in a plane crash. 
</P>
<P>
	``Superstar,'' with Molly Shannon in a big-screen story about  
her ``Saturday Night Live'' character Mary Katherine Gallagher, 
opened in fifth place with $9 million. 
</P>
<P>
	``Three Kings,'' the tale of American soldiers on a treasure  
hunt at the end of the Gulf War, dropped one spot to third place 
with $11.7 million in its second weekend. 
</P>
<P>
	Another take on infidelity, the dark family satire ``American  
Beauty,'' remained strong with $9.2 million for fourth place. The 
film went into wider distribution at 1,226 theaters, up about 500, 
and averaged $7,504 a screen, compared with $4,652 in 2,913 
theaters for ``Double Jeopardy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Double Jeopardy,'' which has grossed $65.8 million in 17 days,  
and ``Random Hearts'' competed for the adult date crowd. Both 
movies drew well with men and women and played strongly to 
movie-goers 25 and older. 
</P>
<P>
	With more of an action edge, ``Double Jeopardy'' had the  
advantage over ``Random Hearts,'' a slow-paced melodrama. 
</P>
<P>
	``That thriller aspect is what is bringing people into the  
theaters,'' said Paul Dergarabedian, president of Exhibitor 
Relations Co. Inc., which tracks movie-ticket sales. ``Whereas 
'Random Hearts' had more of a romance angle.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A two-hour, 11-minute character study, ``Random Hearts''  
received generally poor reviews describing it as dull. 
</P>
<P>
	Unusual for Ford, who's known for action-adventure films that  
appeal mainly to men, the movie drew a bigger female audience, said 
Ed Russell, executive vice president for publicity at Sony 
Pictures, which distributed ``Random Hearts.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Harrison Ford has so much appeal with every audience,'' said  
Robert Bucksbaum, a box-office analyst with Reel Source Inc. ``It's 
incredible that he can do so well with romance when his main forte 
is action.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Bruce Willis ghost story ``The Sixth Sense'' remained in the  
top 10 for the 10th straight weekend. The film was No. 6 with $6.1 
million and has grossed $242.7 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Estimated ticket sales for Friday through Sunday at North  
American theaters, according to Exhibitor Relations Co. Inc. Final 
figures to be released today. 
</P>
<P>
	1. ``Double Jeopardy,'' $13.6 million.  
</P>
<P>
	2. ``Random Hearts,'' $13.1 million.  
</P>
<P>
	3. ``Three Kings,'' $11.7 million.  
</P>
<P>
	4. ``American Beauty,'' $9.2 million.  
</P>
<P>
	5. ``Superstar,'' $9 million.  
</P>
<P>
	6. ``The Sixth Sense,'' $6.1 million.  
</P>
<P>
	7. ``Blue Streak, $5.5 million.  
</P>
<P>
	8. ``Drive Me Crazy,'' $3.7 million.  
</P>
<P>
	9. (tie) ``Elmo in Grouchland,'' $2.1 million.  
</P>
<P>
	9. (tie) ``For Love of the Game,'' $2.1 million.  
</P>
</TEXT>
