<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Retired AP Newsman Dies at 73 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	OLYMPIA, Wash. (AP) -- John White, a correspondent for The  
Associated Press in Olympia for 23 years, died Monday at 73. 
</P>
<P>
	White had been diagnosed with lung cancer last summer.  
</P>
<P>
	He reported on the activities of five governors, covered  
countless sessions of the Legislature and directed AP news coverage 
in southwest Washington. 
</P>
<P>
	``He was always asking hard questions and never accepting an  
obtuse answer from any of us,'' Democratic Gov. Gary Locke said. 
``He was constantly keeping everyone off guard and even in his 
early departure from us, he was keeping us off guard.'' 
</P>
<P>
	House Co-Speaker Clyde Ballard, a Republican recalled times when  
White was the only reporter on the House floor for an all-night 
session. 
</P>
<P>
	``I loved it when he would raise his pen up real high so  
everyone could see it, when our debates were blazing and everyone 
was talking so they could be in the AP story, John would make a big 
point of putting his pen down. His point was that he was through 
writing down notes -- and people stopped talking.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A press center near the Capitol that is occupied by The AP and  
other news organizations bears White's name. 
</P>
<P>
	White joined The AP in Boise, Idaho, in 1963. He transferred to  
the Portland, Ore., bureau in 1967 and, later that year, was named 
correspondent in Fresno, Calif. He came to Olympia in 1971, and in 
1973 he was named correspondent of the capital bureau. He retired 
in 1996. 
</P>
<P>
	His wife, Evelyn, said, ``His favorite story of all was the  
eruption of Mount St. Helens'' in 1980. The family plans to spread 
his ashes around the mountain, she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Survivors include his wife and five children.  
</P>
<P>
	No funeral was planned.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
