<HEADLINE> Illinois State's QB Out for Season </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NORMAL, Ill. (AP) -- Illinois State quarterback Kevin Glenn tore  
a ligament in his left knee in Saturday's win over Indiana State 
and will miss the rest of the season. 
</P>
<P>
	Coach Todd Berry said Monday that tore the ACL and the  
5-foot-10, 190-pound junior from Detroit is expected to undergo 
surgery in two or three weeks and be ready for spring practice next 
year. 
</P>
<P>
	Glenn led the Gateway Conference in passing yardage per game,  
total offense and pass efficiency last season. 
</P>
<P>
	This season, he was 110-of-174 (63.2 percent), passing for 1,200  
yards and 10 touchdowns. He was intercepted only twice. 
</P>
<P>
	On Saturday, the Redbirds (5-1, 3-0), whose only loss was to  
Minnesota and who are ranked sixth in the Div. I-AA poll, play at 
independent South Florida (4-2), which is ranked 19th. 
</P>
<P>
	Berry said he will decide after this week's practices whether  
senior Ryan Speilman (8-of-19, 84 yards) or freshman Dusty Burk 
(22-of-33, 174 yards) will start against South Florida. 
</P>
<P>
	``The injury took everybody off guard and took the wind out of  
our sails,'' Berry said. ``This is obviously going to change our 
offense, it has to. When you have a player like Kevin, who makes 
such a dramatic impact, the team becomes bulletproof.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
