<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-11 00:20:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Baffert Wins Jockey Club Gold Cup </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- While it was not surprising that trainer Bob  
Baffert saddled a winner at Belmont Park, most bettors were caught 
off guard when it turned out to be River Keen. 
</P>
<P>
	One race after Baffert's star 3-year-old filly Silverbulletday  
finished second to Beautiful Pleasure as the 4-5 favorite in the 
$500,000 Beldame, River Keene surprised everyone. River Keene, a 
12-1 shot, took the lead on the turn and won the $1 million Jockey 
Club Gold Cup on a track made sloppy by day-long rain. 
</P>
<P>
	Baffert watched both races on television from California, where  
he won the Oak Leaf on Saturday with unbeaten 2-year-old filly 
Chilukki and finished second in the Norfolk Stakes with 2-year-old 
colt Forest Camp at Santa Anita. Another Baffert 2-year-old colt, 
Captain Steve, won the Breeders' Futurity Sunday at Keeneland. 
</P>
<P>
	River Keen, who paid $26 despite winning the Woodward Sept. 18  
at Belmont, was never worse than second in the 1 1/4-mile Gold Cup and 
he won by 3 1/4 lengths over favored Behrens, who lost his second 
straight race after having won four straight stakes. Almutawakel, 
the Dubai World Cup winner and Woodward runner was third, with 
3-year-olds Stephen Got Even fourth and Lemon Drop Kid fifth. 
</P>
<P>
	It was the debut against older horses for Stephen Got Even and  
Lemon Drop Kid, winner of the Belmont Stakes and Travers. 
</P>
<P>
	``You never expect anything like this,'' said owner Hugo  
Reynolds, who claimed the 7-year-old River Keen for $100,000 on 
Dec. 4. ``If you did, everybody would be at the claiming box every 
day.'' 
</P>
<P>
	River Keen, a winner in 2:01 2-5 with Chris Antley, is headed  
for the $4 million Breeders' Cup Classic Nov. 6, as are Behrens and 
Lemon Drop Kid. 
</P>
<P>
	Silverbulletday's second loss in 10 starts this year and third  
in 17 career races came in her debut against older fillies. 
</P>
<P>
	Beautiful Pleasure, ridden by Jorge Chavez, won her second  
straight stakes on a sloppy track. Silverbulletday likes to come 
from off the pace, but she was in trouble quickly when the 
4-year-old Beautiful Pleasure broke on top and opened a 6-length 
lead just past the half-mile pole. 
</P>
<P>
	At the wire, Beautiful Pleasure was 4 3/4 lengths ahead of  
Silverbulletday, with Catinca third. The time for the 1 1/8 miles was 
1:47 1-5. Beautiful Pleasure was worth $6.80, $2.50 and $2.10. 
</P>
<P>
	Silverbulletday and another top 4-year-old filly, Banshee  
Breeze, beaten by Beautiful Pleasure at Saratoga, will get another 
crack at Beautiful Pleasure in the Breeders' Cup Distaff. 
</P>
<P>
	In another Grade I stakes Sunday, Surfside gave up the lead to  
Darling My Darling turning for home, then fought back for head 
victory in the $400,000 Frizette, for 2-year-old fillies, a race 
won by her dam, Flanders, in 1994. Both are contenders for the 
Breeders' Cup Juvenile Fillies. Surfside paid $5.90, $2.80 and 
$2.70. 
</P>
<P>
	Positioning themselves on Saturday as contenders in Breeders'  
Cup races were Greenwood Lake and Val's Prince. 
</P>
<P>
	Greenwood Lake ($15.50), ridden by Jean-Luc Samyn, rallied from  
9 lengths off the lead with a little more than a quarter-mile 
remaining and won the 1 Champagne for 2-year-olds by 2 1-2 lengths 
over Chief Seattle in 1:43 3-5 for 1 1-16 miles on a fast track. 
</P>
<P>
	Val's Prince ($8.10), ridden by Jorge Chavez, won his second  
straight Grade I stakes on the grass with a one-length victory over 
France-based Dream Well in the $600,000 Turf Classic. The winning 
time for the 1 1/2 miles on a firm turf course. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
