<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Suharto Corruption Probe Dropped </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	JAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) -- Indonesia's top legal officer dropped  
a corruption investigation against ex-President Suharto today, a 
move that raised fears of renewed student protests just nine days 
before a new head of state is chosen. 
</P>
<P>
	Ismudjoko, Indonesia's acting attorney general, said his  
investigation uncovered some irregularities but not enough evidence 
to show that Suharto had violated the law to enriched himself. 
</P>
<P>
	``There is not sufficient evidence to continue the  
investigation,'' Ismudjoko, who like many Indonesians uses only one 
name, said after presenting his report to President B.J. Habibie, 
Suharto's hand-picked successor. 
</P>
<P>
	Habibie promised to crack down on corruption after he took power  
16 months ago. He repeatedly denied accusations that he would 
protect his old boss, who ruled Indonesia with an iron fist for 32 
years. 
</P>
<P>
	The decision to let Suharto off the hook could damage Habibie's  
already dim chances of staying in power on Oct. 20, when the 
700-member People's Consultative Assembly chooses the next leader. 
</P>
<P>
	Habibie did not immediately comment on the decision.  
</P>
<P>
	Many assembly members have demanded that the government  
prosecute Suharto, who was forced to quit in May 1998 after a wave 
of student protests and bloody riots. 
</P>
<P>
	Since then, students have regularly clashed with security  
forces. They have demanded that Suharto be tried, and they have 
rejected the attorney general's investigation as a whitewash. 
</P>
<P>
	On Tuesday, Habibie's Golkar Party is to announce whether it  
will continue to back him as its sole candidate for the presidency. 
</P>
<P>
	``Politically, this is a major factor. It could damage Habibie's  
candidacy,'' said Marzuki Darusman, who heads an anti-Habibie 
faction within Golkar. 
</P>
<P>
	Reformers condemned the decision and warned that the world's  
fourth most populous nation should brace itself for more trouble on 
the streets. 
</P>
<P>
	``The people are going to be angry that Suharto has been let  
off,'' said Hendardi, who heads the Indonesian Legal Aid 
Foundation. 
</P>
<P>
	``We expected this. No one in this country is brave enough to  
put Suharto on trial,'' said Tenten Masduki, of Indonesian 
Corruption Watch, an anti-graft group. 
</P>
<P>
	Suharto, 78, has been accused of siphoning millions of dollars  
of public funds through charity foundations during his autocratic 
rule. 
</P>
<P>
	The former president, who was recently treated in a Jakarta  
hospital after suffering a stroke, has denied any wrongdoing. He 
also rejected accusations that his family has stashed away a 
fortune in foreign bank accounts. 
</P>
<P>
	``We knew all along this case would be dropped,'' said Danny  
Kailimang, a member of Suharto's legal team. ``We respect the 
attorney general's office for making a professional decision.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Several Suharto children remain under separate investigations  
for corruption, and his youngest son, Tommy, is currently on trial 
over a multimillion dollar land deal. A verdict is expected as 
early as this week. 
</P>
<P>
	Ismudjoko said he had investigated the finances of seven  
foundations headed by Suharto, but focused on the two largest, 
Supersemar and Dahmais. 
</P>
<P>
	The investigation focused on a scheme set up by Suharto under  
which his foundations received regular, legally required, donations 
from state institutions. 
</P>
<P>
	Investigators found that the foundations had lent the funds to  
various commercial corporations. Although irregular, such 
transactions were not illegal because their profits ultimately were 
returned to the foundations and used for charitable work, Ismudjoko 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	``The law says that as long as the profit is used for social  
interests, it is not wrong for the foundation to lend it to 
commercial interests,'' Ismudjoko said. 
</P>
<P>
	He did not specify what commercial interests had borrowed the  
money. However, opponents of Suharto claim the funds were milked as 
an easy source of credit to fuel the business empires of his six 
superrich children. 
</P>
<P>
	Ismudjoko said the case against Suharto could be reopened if new  
evidence of corruption was unearthed. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
