<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Two N.C. Schools Rely on Trailers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TARBORO, N.C. (AP) -- Students at two elementary schools ruined  
by Hurricane Floyd's floodwaters returned to school today for the 
first time in more than three weeks, stepping into trailers that 
will be their classrooms for at least the next year. 
</P>
<P>
	About 700 students from Pattillo A+ Elementary School and  
Princeville Montessori School, a magnet school, were hugged by 
teachers and then escorted into dozens of trailers at two sites in 
this flood-ravaged community on the Tar River. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's ready,'' said Susie Morris, grandmother of kindergarten  
student Montrizes Morris, as she walked the boy to a temporary 
classroom for Princeville Montessori students. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's his first time going to school. I guess it's like  
starting over,'' she said as she watched the students, many in rain 
slickers because of threatening skies, carry their lunch bags and 
backpacks into their new classrooms. 
</P>
<P>
	At the new Pattillo site, next to Martin Middle School, a sign  
on the chain-link fence read, ``Pattillo A+ Elementary School, 
Learning for All ... Whatever It Takes!'' 
</P>
<P>
	Floyd, which drenched eastern North Carolina in 20 inches of  
rain Sept. 16 and killed at least 49 people, caused the Tar River 
in Tarboro to rise 24 feet above flood stage. 
</P>
<P>
	It inundated the entire community of Princeville, a town of  
1,900 founded by ex-slaves after the Civil War, and submerged much 
of Tarboro as well. 
</P>
<P>
	The rest of Edgecombe County's 8,000 students returned to school  
Oct. 4, but more time was needed to set up the mobile homes as 
classrooms for the two uninhabitable schools, county schools 
spokeswoman Diane LeFiles said. She said the county eventually 
plans to use 60 mobile classrooms, each costing $5,000 to set up. 
</P>
<P>
	``We'd like to have the children back in permanent schools by  
next fall,'' LeFiles said, but added that it could be longer.	   Bill Alexander, the cultural arts teacher at Princeville, today 
stood beside a bright-pink sign, helping direct traffic and showing 
parents where to go. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a big day,'' Alexander said. ``I'm glad to get things  
back to a routine. I think it will be a good thing for the 
community to get all the schools back again.'' 
</P>
<P>
	At Pattillo, teachers in purple knit shirts greeted the fourth-  
and fifth-graders with hugs and led them into the Martin school's 
auditorium for an orientation. Later, they planned to walk them 
across the street to their new classrooms. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
