<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Man Falls Overboard in L. Superior </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	EAGLE HARBOR, Mich. (AP) -- A man was being treated for  
hypothermia after falling overboard from a freighter and swimming 
about 4 1/2 miles to shore in the chilly waters of Lake Superior. 
</P>
<P>
	Upon arriving on shore early Monday, he fell asleep for a while  
and then knocked on a nearby door for help. 
</P>
<P>
	Scott Richards, 28, of Willoughby Hills, Ohio, was in fair and  
stable condition Monday night, a nursing supervisor said. 
</P>
<P>
	At about 8 p.m. Sunday, Richards slipped under a fence while he  
was trying to tighten some loose barrels on the 698-foot S.S. 
Buckeye, an iron ore freighter that was headed to Silver Bay 
Harbor, Minn. He fell about 30 to 50 feet in the 46-degree water, 
which had waves estimated at 6 to 8 feet. 
</P>
<P>
	``Given last night's conditions (Richards) overcame amazing  
odds,'' Mark Dobson, Coast Guard operations duty officer, told The 
Mining Journal of Marquette. 
</P>
<P>
	Crew members last saw him on the ship near Copper Harbor, Mich.  
Ninety miles later, they noticed he was gone when he did not report 
for watch, the Coast Guard said. They called the Coast Guard just 
before midnight. 
</P>
<P>
	A helicopter and two rescue boats were sent to look for  
Richards. 
</P>
<P>
	But he had decided to swim to shore when he realized no one had  
seen him fall. He was not wearing a life jacket. 
</P>
<P>
	When he reached land in Eagle Harbor, he fell asleep for an  
undetermined amount of time, officials said. Richards reached a 
nearby home at about 3:40 a.m., and the resident called the 
sheriff's department. 
</P>
<P>
	Richards was sitting on the man's front steps slumped against  
the railing when Sheriff's Deputy William Luokkanen arrived. 
Richards was alert enough to answer questions, but was ``in and 
out'' of shock, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``He was able to give me his name, the name of the ship and what  
had happened at what time,'' said Luokkanen, who took Richards to 
the hospital. ``This is a story to tell the grandkids about.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
