<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Walks to Garciaparra Set Up Homers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CLEVELAND (AP) -- The Cleveland Indians feared Nomar Garciaparra  
so much they walked him intentionally twice. They should have 
worried about Troy O'Leary. 
</P>
<P>
	O'Leary hit a grand slam and a three-run homer on the first  
pitch after each of those walks Monday night as Boston beat 
Cleveland 12-8 to cap its amazing comeback after losing the first 
two games of the best-of-5 division series. Entering Game 5, 
O'Leary was 2-for-16. 
</P>
<P>
	The Red Sox move on to the AL Championship Series against the  
New York Yankees starting Wednesday night in Yankee Stadium. 
</P>
<P>
	O'Leary's second homer broke an 8-8 tie in the seventh and put  
the Red Sox ahead 11-8. The first had put Boston in front 7-5 in 
the third. 
</P>
<P>
	It was understandable for the Indians to risk pitching to  
O'Leary. He hit .280 with 28 homers, but for the second straight 
season he tailed off sharply down the stretch. 
</P>
<P>
	In fact, he went 0-for-5 Sunday night when Boston pounded out 24  
hits in a 23-7 win at Fenway Park that tied the series. 
</P>
<P>
	He was in the midst of his second straight horrid division  
series. The left fielder was just 1-for-16 last year as Cleveland 
beat Boston 3-1. 
</P>
<P>
	The first inning gave the Indians even more reason to pitch to  
O'Leary rather than Garciaparra. The AL batting champion had given 
Boston a 2-0 lead with a homer, but O'Leary ended the inning by 
striking out. 
</P>
<P>
	In the third, after Brian Daubach's double put runners at second  
and third with one out, Indians manager Mike Hargrove had Charles 
Nagy walk Garciaparra. O'Leary then hit Nagy's next pitch 417 feet 
into the right-center field stands for Boston's first postseason 
grand slam in its history. 
</P>
<P>
	The score was tied 8-8 when Hargrove faced a similar decision in  
the seventh. And, despite O'Leary's grand slam, the manager still 
wanted no part of Garciaparra. 
</P>
<P>
	So after John Valentin walked and moved to second on Daubach's  
grounder to second baseman Roberto Alomar, Paul Shuey deliberately 
threw four balls to Garciaparra. 
</P>
<P>
	Up came O'Leary and out went the ball. It flew into the right  
field seats for the winning homer. 
</P>
<P>
	O'Leary's next at-bat was in the ninth after doubles by Daubach  
and Garciaparra produced the 12th run. Hargrove gave the order: 
walk O'Leary intentionally. 
</P>
<P>
	By then, it was too late.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
