<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-11 17:30:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Nets' Cage Deciding Whether To Play </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. (AP) -- Veteran forward Michael Cage is  
going to get another week to decide whether he wants to play for 
the New Jersey Nets this season, general manager John Nash said 
Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Nash said the reason Cage left training camp last Monday was  
because he wasn't sure whether he wanted to go through another NBA 
season being away from his family. 
</P>
<P>
	The 37-year-old Cage has three children.  
</P>
<P>
	``He's not sure whether he wants to call it a career, either,''  
Nash said. 
</P>
<P>
	Cage did not play last season after being waived by Seattle. The  
14-year veteran played in 79 games with New Jersey in 1997-98, 
averaging 1.3 points and 3.9 rebounds. 
</P>
<P>
	He was traded to Seattle on Jan. 21 in a deal that brought Jim  
McIlvaine to New Jersey. He was signed by the Nets as a free agent 
on Sept. 15. 
</P>
<P>
	Cage was the 14th overall pick in the 1984 draft by the Los  
Angeles Clippers. 
</P>
<P>
	McIlvaine had to leave Monday's practice after developing a  
rapid heartbeat 30 minutes into the workout. He was examined by 
team doctors and later returned to the Nets' practice facility. 
</P>
<P>
	McIlvaine said he has had previous episodes with a rapid  
heartbeat in college and while he played for Washington of the NBA. 
He expects to play Tuesday night when the Nets face the Atlanta 
Hawks in an exhibition game at Albany, N.Y. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
