<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-11 01:10:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 4 a.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Monday, Oct. 11, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	Activists Gather at NGO Conference  
</P>
<P>
	SEOUL, South Korea (AP) -- Activists from more than 100 nations  
gathered today to discuss human rights, land mines, hunger and 
refugees at a conference of nongovernmental organizations. The 
annual meeting was opened by South Korean President Kim Dae-jung, 
whose 1997 election victory marked the first peaceful transfer of 
power to an opposition party in South Korea's 50 years of 
independence.Kim, a longtime democracy activist, was once sentenced 
to death by a military-backed government, but his 1980 sentence was 
commuted after pressure from Washington. 

</P>
<P>
	Suharto Corruption Inquiry Dropped  
</P>
<P>
	JAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) -- Indonesia's top legal officer today  
recommended that the corruption case against ex-President Suharto 
be dropped due to lack of evidence. ``There is not sufficient 
evidence to continue the investigation,'' Ismudjoko, Indonesia's 
acting attorney general, said after presenting his report on the 
Suharto probe to President B.J. Habibie. The findings, and how 
Habibie responds to them, could prove crucial to the president's 
chances of staying in power during next week's presidential 
election by the 700-member parliament. 

</P>
<P>
	Peacekeepers Deny Killing Policeman  
</P>
<P>
	DILI, East Timor (AP) -- International peacekeepers today blamed  
anti-independence militants for starting a firefight on the East 
Timor border that heightened tensions between foreign forces and 
the Indonesian military. The peacekeepers denied claims by the 
Indonesian army that a squad of Australian troops killed an 
Indonesian policeman and wounded two others yesterday and that the 
fighting took place on the Indonesian-controlled West Timor side of 
the border. 

</P>
<P>
	Taiwan Mourns Earthquake Victims  
</P>
<P>
	LINKOU, Taiwan (AP) -- Thousands gathered at a sports arena in  
this Taipei suburb today to mourn the deaths of more than 2,000 
people killed by Taiwan's worst earthquake in decades. On a stage 
dimly lit in blue light, many of the island's top leaders 
one-by-one faced a 40-feet-tall memorial to the dead and bowed 
three times. Rows of military officials in formal uniforms watched 
from the stands along with lawmakers in dark suits and members of 
Buddhist, Taoist and Christian charity organizations. 

</P>
<P>
	Delay of Test Ban Treaty Vote Sought  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Three Cabinet members and the White House's  
national security adviser pleaded the Clinton administration's case 
on the nuclear test ban treaty before the public, saying rejection 
by the Senate could hurt nonproliferation efforts. But one 
Republican senator, Jon Kyl of Arizona, said he looked forward to a 
vote this week that is all but certain to kill the Comprehensive 
Test Ban Treaty and force the government to ``go back to the 
drawing board.'' Kyl contended a defeat would strengthen the United 
States' hand in negotiations with other countries. 

</P>
<P>
	EU Demands Worry Serb Leaders  
</P>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- European Union demands for the  
extradition of President Slobodan Milosevic to face war crimes 
charges is causing Serb opposition leaders to rethink their 
cooperation with the EU. More than two dozen top opposition leaders 
had been invited to Luxembourg today to discuss democracy, possible 
shipments of heating oil to municipalities run by opposition 
parties and other issues. But Zoran Djindjic said he and other 
leaders may not attend because EU officials want them to pledge 
that, if they come to power, they will extradite Milosevic and four 
of his aides to the international war crimes tribunal in The Hague, 
Netherlands. 

</P>
<P>
	Albanian Premier Loses Election  
</P>
<P>
	TIRANA, Albania (AP) -- Albania's prime minister was defeated  
today in a leadership contest for his Socialist Party, a loss that 
threatened a new political crisis in this turbulent Balkan country. 
Following an all-night party conference, Prime Minister Pandeli 
Majko was ousted by former Prime Minister Fatos Nano for the 
leadership post by a vote of 291-261. 

</P>
<P>
	Islanders 4, Avalanche 2  
</P>
<P>
	UNIONDALE, N.Y. (AP)-- Mariusz Czerkawski had a goal and two  
assists and rookie Tim Connolly scored his first NHL goal and added 
an assist yesterday as the New York Islanders won their home 
opener, beating the Colorado Avalanche 4-2. New York, which hadn't 
played for eight days and was playing only its second game, also 
got goals from Mats Lindgren and Claude Lapointe. Felix Potvin 
faced 16 shots in winning his first game of the season. 

</P>
<P>
	Red Sox Defeat Indians 23-7  
</P>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- A night after winning just their second postseason  
game in 20 tries, the Red Sox made it two in a row in record style 
-- shocking the Cleveland Indians 23-7 last night to force a 
deciding fifth game in their first-round AL playoff series. John 
Valentin had two homers, a double and seven RBIs as Boston scored 
the most runs ever in a postseason game. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by VINCENT K. WILLIS  
  	   	
</P>
