<HEADLINE> Compaq Plans N. Texas Telecom Site </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HOUSTON (AP) -- North Texas will be home to a new Compaq Computer  
Corp. unit as part of the company's reorganized telecommunications 
group. 
</P>
<P>
	The new unit will be located in the growing ``Telecom Corridor''  
in the suburbs north of Dallas, possibly in or near Plano, Compaq 
spokesman Alan Hodel said. 
</P>
<P>
	Michael D. Capellas, Compaq president and chief executive, was  
to formally announce the move during a keynote address at Telecom 
99, a major trade show beginning this week in Geneva. 
</P>
<P>
	The move would bring up to 2,000 jobs to the area, Hodel said.  
The positions will be a mixture of new hires and transfers of 
current Compaq telecom employees worldwide. 
</P>
<P>
	Larry S. Schwartz will serve as the new group's general manager.  
</P>
<P>
	Compaq boosted its telecom operations two years ago when it  
bought Tandem Computers Inc. Its systems are used worldwide to run 
large-scale telecom operations and drive networks for automatic 
banking, securities trading and other activities. 
</P>
<P>
	Hodel said that Compaq, whose stock price was halved earlier  
this year amid faltering revenues that resulted in the ouster of 
top management, is relying in part on telecom and other large-scale 
computing customers to get the company back on track. 
</P>
<P>
	Compaq, the world's largest personal computer maker, now derives  
more than half of its revenue from large-scale, non-PC products 
designed to drive networks and other large operations. 




  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
