<HEADLINE> Kroger, Union Reach Tentative Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CINCINNATI (AP) -- A union representing Kroger Co. workers in the  
Cincinnati area reached a tentative contract agreement with the 
nation's largest grocery store chain early today, averting a 
possible strike. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're very happy with the agreement, and we also think it  
keeps the company competitive,'' said John Marrone, spokesman for 
United Food and Commercial Workers Union Local 1099, which 
represents about 8,400 workers at 66 Kroger stores in southeastern 
Indiana, northern Kentucky and the Cincinnati area. 
</P>
<P>
	Marrone said Kroger agreed to pay raises and improved health  
benefits for workers at no extra cost to the employees. He declined 
to discuss specifics of the five-year agreement before union 
members had a chance to review the details. 
</P>
<P>
	Union members must approve the contract with a vote, which could  
happen as soon as Wednesday, Marrone said. Calls to 
Cincinnati-based Kroger went unanswered early today. 
</P>
<P>
	The union's previous contract, which expired at midnight  
Saturday, covered employees in Kroger's grocery and meat sections. 
Drugstore and general merchandise division employees are covered 
under another contract. 
</P>
<P>
	On Sunday, an eastern Ohio River Valley local representing 4,600  
Kroger workers in eastern Ohio, West Virginia and eastern Kentucky 
reached a tentative agreement with the company, Local 347 President 
Sterling Ball said. 
</P>
<P>
	Ball said that main negotiations failed to come up with an  
agreement about wages, profit sharing and other terms. But a 
smaller meeting between officials after talks ended enabled the 
sides to agree on a tentative contract, he said. 




  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
