<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> IMF Head Predicts Non-U.S. Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FRANKFURT, Germany (AP) -- The U.S. economy is likely to slow,  
but Europe and Japan can be expected to offset the trend with an 
increase in economic growth, the head of the International Monetary 
Fund said Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	``The U.S. expansion, which has had such a vital role in  
sustaining the world economy ... can -- and should -- be expected to 
slow, with the slack being taken up by expansion in the other 
industrial countries,'' IMF managing director Michel Camdessus 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Signs of improvement in key industrial countries, including  
Japan and Europe, underline that the worst of the global economic 
and financial crisis is over, he told an audience of business 
leaders and politicians in Frankfurt. 
</P>
<P>
	He also said European countries -- at least some of the smaller  
ones -- were increasingly aware of the need to tackle ``structural 
issues,'' a reference to overregulation, inflexible job markets and 
the high cost of social programs. 
</P>
<P>
	Germany, Europe's biggest economy, seems set for an economic  
rebound, helped by the monetary conditions set by the European 
Central Bank, Camdessus said. The ECB has lowered interest rates 
since taking over monetary policy for 11 European countries on Jan. 
1. 
</P>
<P>
	Camdessus specifically urged Germany to push structural reforms  
and consolidate the government's finances. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
