<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Giants' Fassel Doing Damage Control </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. (AP) -- The act is three years in the  
running and getting old for Jim Fassel. 
</P>
<P>
	Five games into the season, the New York Giants have a 2-3  
record, the defense is playing well enough to win and it's 
frustrated the offense isn't holding up its end of the bargain. 
</P>
<P>
	With the prospects for a winning season diminishing and the  
threat of finger-pointing on the rise following Sunday's 
embarrassing 14-3 loss to the Cardinals in Arizona, Fassel was once 
again engaged in damage control. 
</P>
<P>
	``My message right now to myself and the team is we've got  
eleven games left and we can be anything we want to be,'' Fassel 
said Monday. ``All we have to do is go out and start playing 
football like I think we are capable of playing. And that 
specifically applies to the offense.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Giants' offense has been almost nonexistent this season. It  
struggled in the first four games with Kent Graham at quarterback. 
Kerry Collins was no better on Sunday, when Graham was sidelined 
with a concussion. 
</P>
<P>
	Fassel said he had not decided who would start against Dallas  
next Monday night, noting that he wanted to think things out and to 
keep Dallas guessing as long as possible, as if that meant 
anything. 
</P>
<P>
	Consider this: The Boston Red Sox scored more runs Sunday night  
(23) than the Giants' point total over the past two weeks (19). 
</P>
<P>
	Putting a finger on what's wrong with the offense is tough,  
considering almost everyone in the group was making mistakes 
Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	Tackle Roman Oben gave up three sacks. Collins fumbled once and  
threw an interception. Receiver Ike Hilliard dropped a 20-yard pass 
on the Giants' first play from scrimmage. Fullback Charles Way and 
halfback Gary Brown failed to convert on a couple of 
third-and-short plays, with little help from the offensive line. 
</P>
<P>
	Without naming the guilty party, Fassel also said there was a  
sweep that would have gained at least 15 yards if the receiver 
simply bumped into the Cardinals' defensive end. The receiver 
missed his block. 
</P>
<P>
	``Maybe we're thinking too much and we don't execute the nuts  
and bolts of things,'' Fassel said. ``So I'll get it down to where 
we're confident in what we're doing and there's not a lot of 
indecision.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That will probably mean a shaved-down game plan.  
</P>
<P>
	However, that won't mean lineup changes other than the  
quarterback situation. 
</P>
<P>
	In dealing with the team, Fassel plans to stay positive, to keep  
everyone pulling together and to make some changes in how things 
are presented to the offense. 
</P>
<P>
	``I will remind you of this,'' Fassel said. ``We haven't fallen  
apart in two years of doing this and I don't expect to right now.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Neither do some of the Giants' key veterans. They remember  
winning the NFC East after a 2-3 start two years ago. Last year, 
New York didn't right things until the end of the season, winning 
five of six to finish 8-8. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think it's fallen apart,'' Way said. ``That's  
overdramatizing the situation. I just think it's only three games 
(losses). We still have 11 left and we're by no means out of it. We 
just have to get it going starting Monday night.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Reserve halfback Tiki Barber said the offense will go once the  
mistakes stop. He also doesn't see a rift developing between the 
offense and defense, which has only played one bad game. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've been down that road before,'' Barber said. ``That's an  
immature way to play football and it doesn't do anything but drive 
us apart and make it worse. I don't think we are to that point or 
that we will get to that point.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
