<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Steelers Seem Okay With Close Loss </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PITTSBURGH (AP) -- Apparently, the Pittsburgh Steelers no longer  
measure success in wins and losses. Their new measuring stick is 
yards and feet. 
</P>
<P>
	They have lost three in a row -- the first time that's happened  
so early in a season since 1988 -- eight of 10 and 10 of 14. For a 
team that lost as many as seven games only once from 1992-97, those 
numbers are staggeringly bad. 
</P>
<P>
	Yet the Steelers couldn't have put a more positive spin on  
Sunday's 24-21 loss at Buffalo if they were a political consultant. 
Linebacker Levon Kirkland even suggested they will win their next 
five games, beginning Sunday in Cincinnati. 
</P>
<P>
	Is one good game by quarterback Kordell Stewart -- only his  
second such game in nearly a year -- enough to turn yet another loss 
and a discouraging 2-3 start into a positive, upbeat situation? 
</P>
<P>
	``We are not going to get uptight about anything,'' said running  
back Richard Huntley, who had 16 yards on five carries. ``We're 
coming along and we're going to keep coming along.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Only one problem: former All-Pro running back Jerome Bettis  
isn't along for the ride. He managed 24 yards on 13 carries, his 
worst game for the Steelers except for two brief last-season 
appearances in 1996 when he was hurt. 
</P>
<P>
	If it was an anomaly, it wouldn't be a problem. But it is not an  
anomaly. Bettis, who rushed for 4,281 yards in his first three 
Steelers seasons, has 256 yards in five games -- a 51 yards per game 
average that ranks only 10th in the AFC. 
</P>
<P>
	Bettis had 16 100-yard games the last two seasons, but doesn't  
have one this season. Usually the most talkative and upbeat 
Steelers player, he barely spoke Sunday even when his teammates 
were extolling the virtues of the narrow loss. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's inevitable that when we get the passing game going, we're  
going to run the ball a lot better,'' Bettis said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Steelers did throw better, yet still couldn't run; Stewart  
was 21-of-29 for 216 yards and his first two touchdown passes to a 
wide receiver this season. It was his best game since he threw for 
225 yards in the Thanksgiving Day loss in Detroit that began a 
season-ending five-game losing streak last year. 
</P>
<P>
	``Even though we lost, we made some strides,'' wide receiver  
Hines Ward said. ``It was real encouraging. We went out there and 
drove the ball against one of the best defenses in the NFL. We 
proved we can play with the top teams.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Beating them? That's different. The Steelers haven't beaten a  
winning team in almost 11 months, or since their 30-15 victory over 
Jacksonville on Nov. 15. 
</P>
<P>
	No matter, the message is nearly the same from every player: the  
Steelers are very, very close to being very, very good again. 
</P>
<P>
	Of course, their schedule might have something to do with that.  
In their next six games, they play one-game winner Cincinnati 
twice, one-time winner Atlanta once and winless Cleveland once. 
</P>
<P>
	``People want to put us down, but you had better not, I'm  
telling you,'' Kirkland said. ``We're going to be there at the end. 
There is no sense of panic. We're going to do it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Presumably, he meant making the playoffs, something the Steelers  
have missed only once since Bill Cowher was hired as coach in 1992. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's no lack of confidence here,'' Kirkland said.  
</P>
<P>
	No, just a lack of rushing yardage. The Steelers, who  
traditionally rank near the top in rushing, are an unusually low 
sixth in the AFC and ninth in the NFL. 
</P>
<P>
	``But we are very close,'' tight end Mark Bruener said. ``We  
need to keep pressing.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
