<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-11 04:00:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Tigers Might Make Garner Manager </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- Phil Garner might replace Larry Parrish as  
manager of the Detroit Tigers. 
</P>
<P>
	The Tigers are thought to have interviewed the former Milwaukee  
manager in recent days about the possibility of leading their club 
into a new ballpark next season. 
</P>
<P>
	``I have no comment on that,'' Tigers' general manager Randy  
Smith said Sunday night. ``This is a delicate subject right now.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Garner, fired in August after eight years at Milwaukee, would  
replace Parrish who led the Tigers to a disappointing 69-92 record 
during his first full season as a major league manager. That left 
them a distant third in the AL Central behind the Cleveland Indians 
and Chicago White Sox. 
</P>
<P>
	Garner and Smith are thought to have met either Friday or  
Saturday. If the interview went well, it is possible an 
announcement could come early this week. 
</P>
<P>
	A message left at Garner's home by The Associated Press wasn't  
returned. Parrish, who returned to his home in Haines City, Fla., 
after the season ended, was on a hunting trip. 
</P>
<P>
	``Until a formal announcement is made, I can't comment on  
anything,'' Smith said. ``And I'm not saying there's going to be a 
formal announcement.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Smith met last Monday with Tigers' owner Mike Ilitch and club  
president and CEO John McHale Jr. The three discussed whether they 
would retain Parrish for another season. 
</P>
<P>
	McHale said after that meeting that no timetable had been set  
for a decision. He noted, however, that it was in everyone's best 
interest to have it done as soon as possible. 
</P>
<P>
	``We got together last Monday and agreed we'd say nothing about  
anything until we had something to announce,'' Smith said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Tigers, who got by on a lowly $35 million payroll this  
season, are expected to take a payroll in excess of $50 million 
next season into Comerica Park, a $300 million ballpark under 
construction about a mile from Tiger Stadium. 
</P>
<P>
	To manage that kind of investment, the Tigers might want someone  
with more experience than Parrish -- even if their record is no 
better than the one Parrish fashioned. 
</P>
<P>
	The Brewers fired Garner in the midst of the seventh straight  
losing season in his eight years in Milwaukee. 
</P>
<P>
	Garner, like Parrish, could have been the victim of having to  
work with a small-market payroll. The situation in Milwaukee, like 
Detroit, was made worse by some poor personnel decisions by the 
front office. 
</P>
<P>
	Garner's best season was his first, 1992, before the payroll gap  
between clubs got extreme. That season, he almost guided the 
Brewers past Toronto for the AL East title. Milwaukee now plays in 
the NL Central. 
</P>
<P>
	If the Tigers are determined to dump Parrish and don't hire  
Garner, there are other candidates. They could include Atlanta 
batting coach Don Baylor or Jim Riggleman, fired last Monday by the 
Chicago Cubs. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1993, Riggleman managed the San Diego Padres when Smith  
became the club's GM in mid-season. Riggleman left the Padres after 
that season for the Cubs, where he had two winning seasons in five 
years. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
