<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Rangers 4, Islanders 2 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	UNIONDALE, N.Y. (AP) -- Stephane Quintal scored the tie-breaking  
goal with 2:46 left in regulation as the New York Rangers beat the 
New York Islanders 4-2 on Monday night. 
</P>
<P>
	Quintal broke a 2-2 tie with a slap shot from the right point  
that hit off defenseman Jamie Heward. The Islanders claimed Heward 
was pushed into goaltender Felix Potvin, but referee Bill McCreary 
allowed the goal to stand. 
</P>
<P>
	Theo Fleury added an empty-net goal with 22.8 seconds left as  
the Rangers won their third straight after starting the season 
0-2-1. 
</P>
<P>
	Todd Harvey and Kevin Stevens also scored for the Rangers and  
Kirk McLean stopped 20 shots for his third straight win. 
</P>
<P>
	Brad Isbister and Jamie Heward scored for the Islanders, who  
lost for the sixth straight time to the Rangers. Potvin stopped 33 
shots in a strong performance in the Islanders net. 
</P>
<P>
	The Rangers continued to struggle with their power play. After  
five failed attempts against the Islanders, the Rangers have only 
three power-play goals in 33 opportunities, including 0-for-17 on 
the road. 
</P>
<P>
	The Rangers controlled most of the scoreless first period,  
outshooting the Islanders 15-4. Potvin came up with several big 
saves, including one at 14:17 when he used his stick to stop 
Harvey's hard shot from in close. 
</P>
<P>
	Stevens put the Rangers up 1-0 two minutes into the second  
period when his cross-ice pass hit Islanders rookie Tim Connolly's 
skate and deflected past Potvin. Harvey made it 2-0 at 7:25 when he 
scored on a rebound. 
</P>
<P>
	Isbister scored for the Islanders at 9:42 with a backhander from  
the left circle. The Islanders tied the game at 12:34 of the third 
when Heward put a one-timer past McLean. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991011.0203 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-11 09:40:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  U.S. is 6th in Gymnastics Standings </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TIANJIN, China (AP) -- John Roethlisberger's final high bar  
routine today at the World Gymnastics Championships earned 9.525 
points and seemingly clinched a spot in the medals round for the 
United States. 
</P>
<P>
	The United States stood sixth with 224.594 points, while  
three-time defending champion China was far ahead with its 230.546 
points. 
</P>
<P>
	Russia was second with 227.083, followed by Belarus with  
226.557, Japan with 226.382, South Korea with 225.319 and the 
United States. The top six teams advance to the next round. 
</P>
<P>
	Australia was 11th with 217.645, and was likely to be pushed out  
of the top 12 teams that qualify for next year's Olympics in 
Sydney. But if it makes the top 18, it still can send two men to 
compete for individual medals. The Australian women advanced to 
Tuesday's medal round. 
</P>
<P>
	Three Japanese gymnasts scored below 9 on the high bar,  
including Naoya Tsukahara (8.600), the 1997 individual bronze 
medalist. But the team performed well in the other events, and 
Yoshihiro Saito was solid throughout, moving into a third-place tie 
in the individual standings with 57.074 points, with 19 of 46 teams 
still to compete. 
</P>
<P>
	China's Yang Wei, who scored 9.8 on the vault, led with 57.649.  
Teammate Huang Xu had 57.299, and Bulgaria's Jordan Jovtchev tied 
Saito's 57.074. 
</P>
<P>
	American Blaine Wilson scored just behind Saito and Jovtchev,  
gaining 57.048 points including 9.562 on the high bar that helped 
set the stage for Roethlisberger's decisive routine. 
</P>
<P>
	``I didn't realize it was that close until I got down. I'm glad  
I didn't,'' said the 29-year-old Roethlisberger, who like Wilson is 
a four-time U.S. champion. 
</P>
<P>
	``The first two guys (on the high bar) had a little trouble, and  
that just puts the pressure on,'' he added. 
</P>
<P>
	The American women advanced into the top six with their final  
routine, as Vanessa Atler scored a 9.762 in the floor exercises 
Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	Defending champion Romania led the women's qualifying with  
154.394 points. Also reaching the finals were Russia, 153.576; 
Ukraine, 151.970; China, 151.720; the United States, 151.001, and 
Australia, 150.688. 
</P>
<P>
	Finnish gymnast Jani Tanskanen, the 1997 world champion on the  
high bar, fell from the bar on his shoulder and suffered ligament 
damage that ended his competition. 
</P>
<P>
	Tanskanen first was thought to have suffered a dislocated  
shoulder, but officials of the International Gymnastics Federation 
said later he hoped to return to action at the Glasgow Grand Prix 
on Nov. 5. 
</P>
<P>
	Tanskanen jumped back on the bar and tried to continue after his  
fall, but had to give up. He was given a score of 7.775. 
</P>
<P>
	He also had to abandon his last event, the floor exercises, and  
finished with a total of 42.637 points for four events. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991011.0204 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-11 18:10:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Four Wins Breeders' Cup Stakes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TORONTO (AP) -- A disqualification gave Four on the Floor his  
third win in as many outings as he was moved from second to first 
Monday in the $220,200 Grey Breeders' Cup Stakes at Woodbine, his 
second straight major 2-year-old stakes victory. 
</P>
<P>
	The dark bay son of Academy Award crossed the finish line  
second, 8 1/2 lengths behind odds-on favorite Exciting Story. But 
Exciting Story was disqualified for interfering with Twilight 
Dreams and Prime Time Talkin on the first turn of the 1 1-16-mile 
race. 
</P>
<P>
	As a result, Exciting Story was dropped to fifth, while Four on  
the Floor moved to first, Gallop'n Gold to second, Prime Time 
Talkin to third and Twilight Dreams to fourth. 
</P>
<P>
	Jim McAleney, who has ridden Four on the Floor in his three  
wins, including the Summer Stakes last month, said he was also 
interfered with on the roughly ridden first turn. 
</P>
<P>
	``We were at the tail end of a pretty good domino effect,'' he  
said. ``... It forced my horse out and it cost us a significant 
amount of ground going into that turn. 
</P>
<P>
	``(But) my horse ran very well. He recovered really quickly and  
got himself right back into the race. I was very happy with him. 
... He's still learning but in the long run I think he'll be a very 
good horse.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Exciting Story, who was clocked in 1:45.12, was ridden by  
Patrick Husbands. 
</P>
<P>
	``My horse left there running. The other horse (Gallop'n Gold,  
ridden by Laurie Gulas) came straight across. I had nowhere to go 
and I had four guys on the inside of me,'' he said. ``Unfortunately 
they took my number down.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Four on the Floor is owned by Arthur Preston's Lor Stables. The  
Kentucky-bred collected $87,120 in the Grey, raising his career 
earnings to $191,160. 
</P>
<P>
	He paid $13.20, $5.20 and $3.60. Gallop'n Gold returned $4.70  
and $3.80, while Prime Time Talkin was $4.80 to show. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
