<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Global Crossing To Buy Racal Telecom </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- Telecommunications company Global Crossing Ltd.  
has agreed to buy Racal Telecom, a part of Britain's Racal 
Electronics PLC, for about $1.6 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	The acquisition announced Monday is another big step for  
fast-growing Global Crossing, which owns and operates an advanced 
fiber-optic network in the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	Under terms of the deal, Bermuda-based Global Crossing will pay  
$1.57 billion in cash and assume Racal Telecom lease obligations 
worth $82.5 million. 
</P>
<P>
	The deal still must be approved by Racal shareholders and  
regulatory authorities. 
</P>
<P>
	Based at Bracknell, west of London, Racal Telecom operates  
fiber-optic telecommunications links between 2,000 towns and cities 
in the United Kingdom. It adds to Global Crossing's existing 
British operations and a pan-European network now being developed, 
said Bob Annunziata, chief executive of Global Crossing. 
</P>
<P>
	Annunziata estimated that the acquisition would yield net  
savings of about $450 million a year. No jobs are expected to be 
cut from among Racal Telecom's 1,300 employees, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	In clinching the deal, Global Crossing outbid Energis, a British  
telecommunications firm, which had earlier offered an estimated 
$1.32 billion for Racal Telecom. 
</P>
<P>
	Global Crossing which recently acquired U.S. phone service  
provider Frontier Corp., and it agreed in May to pay $908 million 
for the underwater cable-laying business of Britain's Cable &AMP; 
Wireless PLC. 
</P>
<P>
	Global Crossing offers the Racal business ``a certain critical  
mass'' that is necessary for survival amid the rapid consolidation 
in the telecommunications industry, said Racal spokesman David 
Nicholas. 
</P>
<P>
	Racal shareholders would benefit from a reduction in company  
debt and a large cash payout, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	After selling its telecommunications network, Racal's business  
would consist mostly of defense and industrial electronics and 
transportation services. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
