<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Atlanta's Jones Readies for N.Y. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- Chipper Jones did his part to knock the New York  
Mets out of the playoffs. Now, he's got to do it again. 
</P>
<P>
	Having withstood Jones' four-homer, MVP-like barrage late in the  
season, the Mets are still hanging around. And they wasted little 
time focusing on the Atlanta Braves third baseman as the lightning 
rod for their barbs heading into the NL championship series. 
</P>
<P>
	Specifically, New York manager Bobby Valentine took umbrage at  
Jones telling the Mets fans to ``go put on their Yankees stuff'' 
after the Braves took two of three games at Shea Stadium in final 
week. 
</P>
<P>
	Jones arrived at the Turner Field clubhouse on Monday, wearing a  
stock car racing cap and in no mood to keep this exchange going. 
</P>
<P>
	``Bobby can turn my comments any way he wants,'' the Braves star  
said. ``The last thing I want to do is get in a newspaper war with 
Bobby Valentine.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Contrary to Valentine's assessment, Jones insisted he has  
nothing but respect for the Mets, who lost five of six games to the 
Braves in the final two weeks of the regular season but still made 
the playoffs as a wild card. 
</P>
<P>
	Jones homered four times during a three-game sweep of the Mets  
at Turner Field, then endured the wrath of the New York fans when 
the teams met again the following week at Shea. 
</P>
<P>
	After the Braves sent the Mets to the brink of elimination by  
winning two games, Jones said it was almost as much fun as winning 
the World Series. He seemed to have a grudge against the Mets all 
season, hitting .400 (16-of-40) with seven homers, 16 RBIs and four 
stolen bases. 
</P>
<P>
	New York rebounded to win its final three games, beat Cincinnati  
in a wild-card playoff and upset Arizona in the opening round of 
the playoffs. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think the two best teams in the National League are playing  
each other in the league championship series,'' Jones said. ``Their 
backs were against the wall. A lot of people were counting them 
out. But you've got to give them credit. They came back from the 
dead and here they are.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He said his comments in New York were directed more at the fans  
than the Mets themselves. 
</P>
<P>
	``You always say things in the heat of battle that maybe you  
don't mean,'' Jones said. ``Don't get me wrong. They have my utmost 
respect.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The first two games in the best-of-7 series are at Turner Field.  
When the series shifts to New York for the weekend, Jones is 
prepared for hostile treatment. 
</P>
<P>
	``Nothing the fans say or do is going to take me out of my  
game,'' he said. ``The guys on the field affect what I do. Me and 
the fans can jaw all we want, but it's going to have no affect on 
the series.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Cleanup hitter Brian Jordan, who hits behind Jones in the  
Atlanta order, doesn't think his teammate will change his icy 
demeanor. 
</P>
<P>
	``Chipper has been calm, cool and collected all year long,''  
Jordan said. ``Words are words. You can't change them. You've just 
got to go out there, play your game and let your actions speak. ... 
Believe me, they're going to come at Chipper, and he's going to 
come through for us.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Jones, 27, rebounded from personal turmoil -- he admitted to  
fathering an illegitimate child and wound up divorcing his wife -- 
to have the greatest season of his career. He hit .319 with 45 
homers, 110 RBIs and 25 stolen bases, virtually carrying the Braves 
late in the season when Jordan was rendered powerless by a sore 
hand. 
</P>
<P>
	But good news for the Mets: Jones was only 3-of-13 (.231) in the  
opening-round victory over the Houston Astros and showed a tendency 
to swing at poor pitches. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think they will pitch me just like Houston did,'' Jones  
said. ``I'm not swinging the bat like I was three weeks ago. 
Certainly, the pitching has something to do with that. I've got to 
be patient and hope I hit the mistakes.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
