<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Weight: Genes or Discipline? </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- America's problems with extra weight are not  
so much in our genes as they are in our discipline, researchers 
say. 
</P>
<P>
	Only a little less eating or more activity is all it would take  
to turn around weight problems that kill many Americans early, the 
researchers say. Just the same, we don't do it. 
</P>
<P>
	``Modest changes in what we are eating, and what we are doing  
may go a long way,'' said Dr. William H. Dietz, director of the 
Division of Nutrition and Physical Activity at the federal Centers 
for Disease Control and Prevention. 
</P>
<P>
	Fifty calories a day less food or more exercise works out to 5  
pounds less weight over a year -- and doubling the lost calories 
means doubling the lost weight. 
</P>
<P>
	America's weight problem doesn't look primarily genetic, Dietz  
said. Data show the most graphic gains in weight came from 1980 
through 1994, and ``the genes didn't change substantially,'' he 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	About 55 percent of adults weigh too much. The implication is  
that people got that way by eating more and being active less. 
</P>
<P>
	Weight control looks even more important now that a new study  
links even moderate excess weight to a greater risk of dying early. 
The American Cancer Society report, published Thursday in the New 
England Journal of Medicine, found the risk began to rise with a 
body mass index -- a weight-to-height ratio -- that would fit a 
5-foot-5 woman of 150 pounds, or a 5-foot-10 man of 174 pounds. 
</P>
<P>
	A study in the October edition of the American Journal of Public  
Health looked at the lifetime health and economic benefits if obese 
people lost 10 percent of their weight and kept it off. Their life 
expectancy would increase by 2 to 7 months, and the lifetime 
medical costs of five obesity-related diseases would fall by as 
much as $5,300, said researchers at Harvard Medical School and a 
private firm, Policy Analysis Inc. of Brookline, Mass. 
</P>
<P>
	``Small permanent changes are what we should strive for, rather  
than radical or punitive weight loss programs,'' said the cancer 
society study's lead author, Eugenia E. Calle. 
</P>
<P>
	It could start with as little as a daily 15-minute walk out your  
front door and a 15-minute walk back, she said. It also could 
involve eating more fruits and vegetables, and less high-calorie 
processed foods, she said. 
</P>
<P>
	It remains to be seen if people will do it. The latest figures  
from the CDC's Behavioral Risk Factors Surveillance Survey find no 
meaningful change in the proportion of Americans who meet even the 
minimum levels recommended by CDC, the surgeon general and the 
American College of Sports Medicine. The groups call for 30 minutes 
of moderate activity -- such as brisk walks for at least 10 minutes, 
three times a day -- on most days. 
</P>
<P>
	The 1998 risk factors data show almost 30 percent of Americans  
are inactive, said epidemiologist Carol Macera of CDC's physical 
activity and health branch. 
</P>
<P>
	Community health experts think that, through cars, escalators  
and other labor-saving machinery, America has engineered out its 
ability to get activity in. 
</P>
<P>
	``Since about 1950, we have designed our communities and  
environments to be automobile-driven,'' said CDC health scientist 
Richard E. Killingsworth. The average person takes about 8 to 10 
trips a day to such places as work, school or shopping, and 90 
percent are by car, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	It's not realistic to think Americans will give up their cars,  
but ``if we can replace 2 to 3 auto trips (per day), think of the 
public health benefit we would get,'' Killingsworth said. 
</P>
<P>
	The CDC and other organizations have been trying to encourage  
walking, starting with the young. The National Walk Our Children to 
School Day campaign was aimed at getting parents and children who 
live within one mile of school to start walking instead of being 
driven. 
</P>
<P>
	The effort ``should continue all year long,'' said Jessica  
Shisler, the CDC's project coordinator for the program. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991011.0216 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-11 19:50:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Obituaries in the News  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
                            *Frank Baker    	
</P>
<P>
	DURHAM, N.C. (AP) -- The Rev. Frank Baker, an authority on  
Methodism founder John Wesley, died Monday. He was 89. 
</P>
<P>
	An ordained minister and author of 30 books and more than 200  
articles, Baker retired from Duke University in 1980. 
</P>
<P>
	Duke Divinity School dean L. Gregory Jones called Baker ``the  
leading authority on the history of the Wesleys and early 
Methodism.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Baker was ordained as a Methodist minister in 1937 and served  
pastorates in central and northern England until 1959. He joined 
the Duke Divinity School faculty in 1960 and retired as professor 
emeritus of English church history. 
</P>
<P>
	During his career, Baker was closely associated with a 36-volume  
compilation of John Wesley's writings. The work is being published 
by Abington Press. 
</P>
<P>
	Last month, the Baker Methodist Research Center was established  
at Duke to serve as a focal point for future Wesley scholarship. 

</P>
<P>
                         *E. William Crotty    	
</P>
<P>
	GAINESVILLE, Fla. (AP) -- E. William Crotty, a major Democratic  
fund-raiser who became U.S. Ambassador to the Eastern Caribbean 
last year, died Sunday of pneumonia. He was 68. 
</P>
<P>
	Crotty, a longtime Daytona Beach attorney and civic activist,  
was ambassador to seven nations -- Barbados, Antigua and Barbuda, 
Dominica, St. Lucia, Grenada, St. Kitts and Nevis, and St. Vincent 
and The Grenadines. He was appointed to the post in November and 
was based in Barbados. 
</P>
<P>
	He was former chairman of the Executive Committee of the  
Democratic National Committee Board of Directors and a fervent 
fund-raiser for numerous candidates, including President Clinton 
and Vice President Al Gore. 

</P>
<P>
                           *Milt Jackson    	
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Milt Jackson, a jazz vibraphonist who made the  
instrument sing like the human voice as a longtime member of the 
Modern Jazz Quartet, died Saturday of liver cancer. He was 76. 
</P>
<P>
	Jackson was one of the best improvisers in jazz and an  
outstanding blues player. 
</P>
<P>
	Jackson originally was a singer in a Detroit gospel quartet. In  
the 1940s, he created a new sound by slowing the motor on his 
Deagan Vibraharp's oscillator to a third of the speed of Lionel 
Hampton's. The result was a warm, smoky sound with a vibrato 
approximating his own singing. 
</P>
<P>
	Jackson's style came from Charlie Parker, whose rhythmic traits  
he adopted. He was one of the first bona fide be-bop vibraphone 
musicians, and he became a jewel in Dizzy Gillespie's band. He 
recorded be-bop classics with the band, such as ``A Night in 
Tunisia,'' ``Anthropology'' and ``Two Bass Hit.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In 1951, Jackson teamed with Thelonius Monk, recording ``Criss  
Cross'' and ``Straight, No Chaser,'' among others. 
</P>
<P>
	When a pianist in Gillespie's band, John Lewis, decided to form  
a new group, one going beyond soloists with a rhythm section, 
Jackson signed on. In 1952, the Modern Jazz Quartet was born. 
</P>
<P>
	Through 20 years of albums, mostly for Atlantic records, the  
group became one of the first jazz bands embraced by an audience 
much wider than jazz fans. Members choreographed all aspects of 
their presentation, from walking on stage to playing their subdued 
arrangements. 
</P>
<P>
	The band dissolved in 1974 and reunited temporarily for a few  
tours in the 1980s and early 1990s. 

</P>
<P>
                         *Joseph Krispinsky    	
</P>
<P>
	ALLIANCE, Ohio (AP) -- Monsignor Joseph Krispinsky, a longtime  
religious leader in northeast Ohio, died Thursday. He was 99. 
</P>
<P>
	He was found unconscious at his home Oct. 4 and died from  
pneumonia and complications from a stroke. 
</P>
<P>
	Krispinsky was ordained a priest in 1923.  
</P>
<P>
	He was assistant pastor of churches in Cleveland, Lakewood,  
Warren and Youngstown before becoming pastor of Sacred Heart Church 
in Canton in 1927. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1941, Krispinsky became pastor of SS. Cyril and Methodius  
Church in Warren, where he stayed for 32 years. 

</P>
<P>
                           *Thomas H. Lake    	
</P>
<P>
	INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- Thomas H. Lake, former Eli Lilly and Co.  
president who also led the Lilly Endowment for 15 years, died 
Sunday. He was 80. 
</P>
<P>
	The son of a Saltsburg, Pa., coal miner, Lake received his  
bachelor's degree in pharmacy and chemistry from Temple University 
in 1941. He served in the Army in World War II, rising to the rank 
of major. 
</P>
<P>
	Lake began his career with Lilly in 1946 in sales. He was  
president from 1973-1976 and served on the board of directors from 
1965-1989. 
</P>
<P>
	From 1977-1992, Lake also was chairman of the Lilly Endowment,  
one of the largest private foundations in the nation. He served as 
the foundation's president from 1997-1984. 

</P>
<P>
                          *Betty H. Reiley    	
</P>
<P>
	ATTLEBORO, Mass. (AP) -- Betty H. Reiley, whose father-in-law  
founded the Daily American of Somerset and who served as president 
of its parent company until its sale in October 1997, died Saturday 
of cancer. She was 85. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to her newspaper work, she was also a dietitian and  
worked as a staff member of the former Somerset County Hospital 
before retiring in 1970. 
</P>
<P>
	Her father-in-law, the late Henry Reiley Sr., founded the Daily  
American in 1929. 
</P>
<P>
	The newspaper was sold to Schurz Communications Inc. of South  
Bend, Ind. 
</P>
<P>
	Survivors include two sons; one sister; four grandchildren; two  
great-grandchildren; and nieces and nephews. 

</P>
<P>
                            *John White    	
</P>
<P>
	OLYMPIA, Wash. (AP) -- John White, a correspondent for The  
Associated Press in Olympia for 23 years, died Monday at 73. 
</P>
<P>
	White had been diagnosed with lung cancer last summer.  
</P>
<P>
	White joined The AP in Boise, Idaho, in 1963. He transferred to  
the Portland, Ore., bureau in 1967 and, later that year, was named 
correspondent in Fresno, Calif. He came to Olympia in 1971, and in 
1973 he was named correspondent of the capital bureau. He retired 
in 1996. 
</P>
<P>
	A press center near the Capitol that is occupied by The AP and  
other news organizations bears White's name. 
</P>
<P>
	He is survived by his wife, Evelyn, and five children.  



  	   	
</P>
