<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Alleged Mobster Held for Fraud </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Another son of a one-time Mafia boss is behind  
bars. 
</P>
<P>
	First, John A. ``Junior'' Gotti, son of the former boss of New  
York's Gambino crime family, was sentenced to nearly 6 1/2 years in 
prison for bribery, extortion, gambling and fraud. Then, on Sunday, 
Alphonse ``Allie Boy'' Persico, whose father once ran the Colombo 
crime family, was ordered held without bail on loan-sharking 
charges. 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutors say Persico, 45, was charged after investigators  
found papers showing he was involved in loan-sharking, extortion 
and bank fraud. He allegedly took control of the Colombo family 
several years after his father, Carmine ``The Snake'' Persico, was 
sentenced to 100 years in prison. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. Magistrate Arlene Lindsay ordered that the younger Persico,  
who surrendered early Saturday, be held without bail. He was to be 
taken by federal marshals to Fort Lauderdale, Fla., where goes on 
trial Wednesday on a separate weapons possession charge. 
</P>
<P>
	Assistant U.S. Attorney Jim Walden said a complaint filed  
against Persico was ``a bare-bones sketch of some of the truth that 
will come out at trial. ... It is an overwhelming case against Mr. 
Persico.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Walden said Persico committed crimes that violated the terms of  
his bail in the Florida case. He also told Lindsay that 
investigators had seen Persico with high-ranking members of the 
Colombo family. 
</P>
<P>
	The loan-sharking, racketeering, and bank fraud charges carry a  
maximum of 70 years in prison, Walden said. 
</P>
<P>
	Persico's lawyer, Barry Levin, said his client had done nothing  
illegal, and that prosecutors were out to get him. 
</P>
<P>
	``The search warrant was a pretext to harass him,'' Levin said  
before the arraignment in Brooklyn federal court. ``They stayed in 
the house for 16 hours, tearing the place up and down, and they 
came up with a lot of nothing. ... They just put away Gotti's son, 
now they want to put away Persico's son.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Junior'' Gotti was sentenced Sept. 3.  
</P>
<P>
	Persico was acquitted in 1994 in a racketeering and murder case  
stemming from a reported war for control of the Colombo family. He 
previously served seven years for racketeering. 
</P>
<P>
	Levin said Persico now spends most of his time in Florida and  
runs family businesses including a limousine company, a coffee 
wholesaling operation and several restaurants. 
</P>
<P>
	``He is not involved in any criminal activity,'' Levin said.  
Most of the time, he added, ``You'll find him in a pair of shorts 
and slippers on a boat in Florida.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
