<HEADLINE> Arkansas Halts Inmate Work Program </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LITTLE ROCK, Ark. (AP) -- The state police director ordered that  
inmates working under a minimum-security arrangement at state 
police headquarters and the Governor's Mansion be returned to 
prison Monday, following the escape of a convicted killer. 
</P>
<P>
	Mark Stone, 39, escaped Friday night from barracks at the state  
police headquarters where he worked in an honor system-based 
rehabilitation program. Forty-nine other inmates participated in 
the program. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've asked that they all be taken back,'' state police  
director Tom Mars said. 
</P>
<P>
	Correction Department vans were standing by at late-afternoon to  
take the prisoners away, likely to a minimum-security unit in 
Wrightsville. 
</P>
<P>
	Mars, who became state police commander last winter, said he had  
long been uncomfortable with prisoners working at his headquarters. 
Some trusties had access to places off-limits to troopers; others 
worked on police vehicles or maintained the state police radio 
system. 
</P>
<P>
	The 50 trusties assigned to the agency saved $500,000 a year,  
and Mars said he could not afford to give up the free work -- until 
Stone escaped. 
</P>
<P>
	``I wanted to do this months ago,'' said Mars, who previously  
moved to restrict inmate access to guns stored in the troopers' 
cars. 
</P>
<P>
	Stone, convicted in the 1984 beating death of his girlfriend,  
escaped by walking out of a dayroom off the barracks. He was being 
held there while officers investigated reports of inmate beer 
drinking. Mars said previously that Stone should not have been left 
unattended. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
