<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Drought Will Hurt Farmer's Finances / Farm Scene  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	OLDWICK, N.J. (AP) -- An insurance adjuster visited Fred Clucas  
at his farm here in early September and told him what he already 
knew: His corn field was worthless. He had lost $150,000 in 
potential income. 
</P>
<P>
	A light breeze blew among the tiny ears of corn that never  
matured. Most were shriveled from the summer's intense heat. 
</P>
<P>
	The dried tassels atop the plants should have dropped pollen  
onto the cornsilk below to start the reproductive process, Clucas 
explained, holding one of the tiny ears in his hands. His 
thumbnails dug into the husk. A twist of the wrists easily split 
open the ear. Inside were rows of sunken kernels. 
</P>
<P>
	``It just didn't happen this year,'' said Clucas, 69, as he  
flicked the ear aside. It bounced once on the reddish soil 
moistened by rains that came too late. 
</P>
<P>
	Clucas grows field corn, hay, wheat and oats spread over 500  
acres in Hunterdon County. He's been doing it since 1957, but said 
this was his worst year ever. 
</P>
<P>
	Nevertheless, he considers himself fortunate. Crop insurance  
will let him recoup about $20,000 of the $75,000 he lost out of 
pocket. About one-third of New Jersey corn farmers have such 
policies, he said. And his wheat crop was good, which will help 
offset the loss on the corn. 
</P>
<P>
	Field crops like the ones he grows, which brought New Jersey  
farmers $67 million in cash receipts last year, were the hardest 
hit by the summerlong drought. 
</P>
<P>
	New Jersey farms produced about 9 million bushels of corn for  
grain in 1998. This year's crop is expected to be only one-third 
that amount, and soybean production is expected to be down 25 
percent from last year's total of 3.2 million bushels. 
</P>
<P>
	With normal rainfall next year, Clucas and others are optimistic  
there will be no lasting effect on future crop yields. 
</P>
<P>
	What nature's compensation can't undo, however, are the effects  
of the drought of '99 on farmers' finances. And that may affect 
what gets planted next spring. 
</P>
<P>
	``If money don't come in, one of the problems some of the guys  
will have is to get credit for next year. They're not going to be 
able to get the credit to plant a crop,'' Clucas said. 
</P>
<P>
	Low-interest loans are available, but many farmers say they need  
grants instead because they're already too deeply in debt. 
</P>
<P>
	``You can't borrow yourself out of debt, that's for sure,''  
Clucas said. ``We're hoping to get that grant. That loan don't mean 
much.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Members of Congress have requested about $1.5 billion in federal  
aid for Northeast farmers. Clucas, who is associate director of the 
New Jersey Farm Bureau, said New Jersey farmers alone need about 
$800 million. 
</P>
<P>
	The uncertainty over how much money will be made available has  
raised concerns that some New Jersey farmers may be forced out of 
business. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't see most farmers bailing out,'' said Vic Tolomeo,  
state statistician of the New Jersey Agricultural Statistics 
Service. ``But if there was going to be a reason to go this year, 
it would be the drought.'' 
</P>
<P>
	New Jersey farm acreage has decreased by nearly 20 percent since  
1975, to about 830,000 acres, according to the New Jersey 
Department of Agriculture, as the average size of a farm dropped 
from 120 acres to 88 acres. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
