<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-11 00:20:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Mount Union on 46 Game Win Streak </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TIFFIN, Ohio (AP) -- With a shot at breaking the nation's longest  
college football winning streak, Mount Union coach Larry Kehres 
says he won't change a thing. 
</P>
<P>
	And why would he?  
</P>
<P>
	Mount Union, which has won three straight Division III national  
championships, can break Oklahoma's NCAA record 47-game winning 
streak with a victory over Otterbein this week. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're going to do the same things we always do,'' Kehres said.  
``We're not going to change our weekly routine.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Despite the attention on the tiny school with just 2,000  
students in Alliance in northeast Ohio, Kehres won't let his 
players get too caught up in the excitement. 
</P>
<P>
	He doesn't want them to feel any added pressure.  
</P>
<P>
	``Right now we have a win streak of five, that's this year,''  
Kehres said. ``And that's the primary focus of this '99 team.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Purple Raiders matched Oklahoma's record Saturday with a  
66-0 victory over Heidelberg. They did have a scare the week 
before, needing three overtimes to get by John Carroll 57-51. 
</P>
<P>
	After that game, the players talked about how they needed to  
forget about the streak. 
</P>
<P>
	``If you let it affect you, it tends to make your team play  
tentatively,'' linebacker Jesse Pearson said. ``We realized we 
can't let it affect us.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Kehres, who has the highest winning percentage of any coach in  
college football history, has downplayed the streak all season. 
</P>
<P>
	There have been no pep talks urging the team to keep it alive,  
or banners in the locker room counting down to next week. 
</P>
<P>
	``We talked about not letting the streak overshadow the goals  
our team has set for the season,'' Kehres said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Purple Raiders are 111-6-1 during the 1990s, with the last  
loss coming Dec. 2, 1995, 20-17 to Wisconsin-La Crosse in the 
national semifinals. In each of the past four seasons, they have 
scored at least 500 points, something no other Division III school 
has done. 
</P>
<P>
	Maybe that's why there was no wild celebration after the victory  
over Heidelberg. Both teams and their coaches simply met at 
midfield and exchanged handshakes. 
</P>
<P>
	The game, played on a wet high school football field in front of  
about 2,000 fans, was never in doubt. 
</P>
<P>
	Mount Union didn't show any nervousness despite the hype  
surrounding the streak, opening a 35-0 lead after one quarter and 
scoring twice on defense in the first half. 
</P>
<P>
	Gary Smeck threw four touchdown passes, two to Adam Marino, on  
plays of 7 and 60 yards. Smeck was 9-of-12 for 176 yards. 
</P>
<P>
	Pearson scored on a blocked punt and returned an interception 51  
yards to give the Purple Raiders (5-0, 3-0 Ohio Conference) a 42-0 
lead with 14:17 left in the second quarter. 
</P>
<P>
	Pearson has scored five touchdowns on defense this season.  
</P>
<P>
	Heidelberg (2-3, 2-2) was held to 95 yards offense in the first  
half and didn't get a first down until the second quarter. 
</P>
<P>
	Kehres has a 143-16-3 record -- a .910 mark -- in his 14 seasons  
at Mount Union. 
</P>
<P>
	Before Mount Union began its streak, no one came within 10 games  
of Oklahoma's record in the four decades since it was set under 
coach Bud Wilkinson. The Sooners were unbeaten in 47 consecutive 
games between 1953-57 until losing to Notre Dame 7-0 in 1957. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
