<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Reformers Send Demand List to Pope </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	VATICAN CITY (AP) -- While Europe's bishops debated the direction  
of the Roman Catholic Church in the new millennium, a group of 
European Catholics seeking reforms fashioned their own list of 
demands ranging from married priests to an end to the ban on 
contraception. 
</P>
<P>
	After holding what they called a ``shadow synod,'' they  
delivered the list Monday to the Vatican. 
</P>
<P>
	``The year 2000 is the occasion for initiating bold changes in  
(church) structures and in some papal decisions, which cause so 
much suffering to so many Christians,'' the group said in their 
declaration. 
</P>
<P>
	Some 120 representatives of the movements We Are Church and  
Church on the Move met for four days near Rome, while 179 bishops 
from across Europe were in the second week of a three-week synod. 
</P>
<P>
	Such protests are not new to We Are Church, a movement begun in  
Austria that has garnered millions of signatures in petition drives 
seeking changes in the Catholic Church. 
</P>
<P>
	But this time, they raised their voice in Rome, holding a news  
conference in an office building 500 yards from St. Peter's Square. 
Among their demands was that lay Catholics be involved in 
decision-making, including responsibility for appointing bishops, 
which now rests with the pope. 
</P>
<P>
	At the synod itself, there appeared to be little stress on the  
issues raised by the lay Catholics, according to the printed 
summaries released by the Vatican from the closed-door meetings. 
</P>
<P>
	Many of the speeches touched on broad issues such as problems of  
immigration, relations with the Orthodox church and the difficulty 
of getting the Christian message across in secular European 
societies. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
