<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Suspect Charged in Chicago Killings </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- DNA evidence from a string of unsolved killings  
and rapes in several South Side neighborhoods has led police to one 
possible suspect: a man in a Chicago jail. 
</P>
<P>
	Ronald Macon, 35, has been charged with three counts of  
first-degree murder. The Chicago man has been in jail since August 
awaiting trial on a separate rape charge. 
</P>
<P>
	Police said DNA evidence linked him to three of 13 killings of  
women in and around the poverty-stricken Englewood neighborhood 
since 1993. Police Cmdr. Frank Trigg said Sunday that Macon 
confessed on videotape to the killings. 
</P>
<P>
	Authorities said Macon's arrest was the breakthrough they had  
been hoping for, but their investigation into the other murders 
continue. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is going to continue because the perpetrators are still  
out there,'' Trigg said. ``But we're certainly going to pause and 
acknowledge the significance of this.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Macon's three alleged victims were all killed this year in the  
Englewood and Washington Park neighborhoods. Angelnetta Peeples, 
43, was found in an abandoned building Feb. 20. She had been 
strangled and hit on the head. 
</P>
<P>
	Linda Soloman, 36, who was found April 14 in a stairwell, also  
had been strangled and hit on the head. Rosezina Williams, 50, was 
strangled and her body found in a trash container on June 21. 
</P>
<P>
	Authorities said Macon could face the death penalty if convicted  
on the murder charges. They said they also might charge him with 
rape. 
</P>
<P>
	Macon is being held in lieu of $1.25 million bond on the current  
rape charge. He could be arraigned on the murder charges as early 
as today, Trigg said. 
</P>
<P>
	Until Macon's arrest, police have had little success in their  
investigation into the string of slayings. Few people in the 
neighborhoods knew the women or were willing to talk to police. 
</P>
<P>
	The authorities thought their luck might be changing last month  
when they charged three men with the March 1998 slaying of 
LaCreesha Avery, 27. 
</P>
<P>
	Avery, who was beaten, raped and strangled, was found wrapped in  
one of the suspects' sheets in the same general area where the 
other bodies were found, police said. 
</P>
<P>
	Authorities thought the men might be tied to other unsolved  
murders, but later found that DNA samples from the men showed no 
connection. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991011.0244 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-11 03:40:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> India's Premier Woos Key Ally </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW DELHI, India (AP) -- In a formal step toward assuming office,  
Atal Bihari Vajpayee was named the country's prime minister today 
and his National Democratic Alliance staked its claim to build 
India's next government. 
</P>
<P>
	NDA coordinator George Fernandes told President K.R. Narayanan  
that the alliance has the support of 303 legislators, more than the 
required one half of the 545 members in the Lok Sabha, the lower 
house of parliament. 
</P>
<P>
	``I have pleasure in appointing you as the prime minister,''  
Narayanan, the constitutional figurehead, wrote in a formal letter 
after meeting with Vajpayee in the sandstone presidential palace. 
</P>
<P>
	The letter is a formality required before Vajpayee is sworn in  
as prime minister Wednesday and appoints Cabinet ministers from the 
22-party alliance. The alliance handed the main opposition Congress 
party its worst electoral defeat since independence 52 years ago in 
elections that ended a week ago. 
</P>
<P>
	The NDA includes 274 legislators and pledged outside support of  
the 29-member Telugu Desam party who have so far resisted joining 
the alliance. 
</P>
<P>
	With the wider backing, observers said the new government could  
complete a full five-year term, unlike the four previous minority 
governments that collapsed over the past three years. 
</P>
<P>
	But Vajpayee, who will lead the government for the third time,  
will need to persuade the Telugu Desam to join his government in 
order to ensure its stability. 
</P>
<P>
	Chandrababu Naidu, the Telugu Desam leader, has been  
noncommittal so far, although he gave Vajpayee a letter promising 
support in crucial parliamentary voting. 
</P>
<P>
	Vajpayee wants all his supporters to be part of the government  
in order to minimize chances of losing power on another 
no-confidence motion. 
</P>
<P>
	Vajpayee's government fell in April when a southern politician  
withdrew her party's 18 seats from the coalition and Vajpayee lost 
a confidence motion by one vote. No other group was able to form a 
government and elections were ordered. 
</P>
<P>
	Another southern ally, the Dravida Progressive Front, has said  
its legislators will decide Thursday -- the day after Vajpayee is to 
be sworn in -- whether to join the government. 
</P>
<P>
	On Sunday, NDA lawmakers unanimously elected Vajpayee their  
leader in the Lok Sabha, the lawmaking lower house of parliament. 
</P>
<P>
	In a brief speech, Vajpayee said the government will have to  
take unpopular decisions to boost the economy and plans to push 
through stalled bills on foreign investment, foreign exchange 
transactions and curbing the black market. 
</P>
<P>
	Vajpayee also has said he will seek a consensus among all  
parties on signing the Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty, or CTBT, 
which India has resisted for years. India carried out nuclear tests 
in May last year, provoking Pakistan to do the same. 
</P>
<P>
	The new government is also eager to reopen dialogue with  
Pakistan in order to resolve the dispute over the northern 
territory of Kashmir, claimed by both countries. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
