<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Statuary Hall, Fame's Fading Flame </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Of the thousands of men and women sent to the  
Capitol by the states over the years, exactly 96 are authorized to 
stay for as long as forever turns out to be. Which, given the 
temper of the times, may not be much longer. 
</P>
<P>
	Carved from marble or cast in bronze, the weighty images of  
America's favored sons and daughters have tested the weight limits 
of the Capitol's floors since the first of the lot was installed in 
Statuary Hall in 1870. 
</P>
<P>
	Since reputations can rise and fall like shares on history's  
stock market, the result is a collection in which fame confronts 
obscurity, in which George Washington of Virginia contemplates 
George Washington Glick of Kansas. 
</P>
<P>
	While Washington's place as his nation's No. 1 founder remains  
secure, the decades have been less kind to his namesake, Glick, who 
was elected his state's first Democratic senator in 1882. 
</P>
<P>
	So low has Glick's stock fallen that Kansas has been trying  
since 1971 to replace him with a statue of that far more memorable 
Kansan, Dwight David Eisenhower. 
</P>
<P>
	There is certainly more luster in Eisenhower. The Abilene native  
and Army general led the Allied invasion of Europe and followed 
that up with two terms in the White House. 
</P>
<P>
	Early this year, the Kansas legislature raised the stakes.  
</P>
<P>
	In a request to Congress, it asked not only to replace Glick  
with Ike but to also bring home former Sen. John J. Ingalls, who is 
credited by some with coining the Kansas state motto, ``Ad Astra 
per Aspera'' (To the Stars Through Difficulties.) 
</P>
<P>
	Ingalls has been on duty in the Capitol for 94 years, Glick for  
85. 
</P>
<P>
	Because there are no precedents, there is no procedure in place  
for states to replace their statuary. 
</P>
<P>
	But the Senate and House committees that concern themselves with  
such matters have, in effect, given Kansas their blessing to 
proceed. It is inevitable, they say, that some states may wish to 
revisit decisions made as long as 129 years ago. 
</P>
<P>
	The collection overflows Statuary Hall, the old chamber of the  
House of Representatives. It peppers corridors and anterooms with 
an assemblage of portrait sculpture remarkable for the sheer 
diversity of those portrayed. 
</P>
<P>
	There are rules for admittance: Each state can select two  
citizens of ``national prominence'' for membership. Four states -- 
Nevada, New Mexico, North Dakota and Wyoming -- have yet to make a 
choice on a second statue. The states, often through contributions, 
pay for the statues; Congress does the dusting. 
</P>
<P>
	The first statue arrived in 1870; the latest, that of Apollo 13  
astronaut John Swigert, complete with white space suit and golden 
helmet, just two years ago. 
</P>
<P>
	There is one king, Kamahameha the First of Hawaii; one selfless  
priest, Father Damien, who ran Hawaii's leper colonies even after 
he had contracted the disease himself. There are a quorum of 
lawmakers; a platoon of generals; and Jeannette Rankin of Montana, 
the first woman ever elected to the House, who voted against U.S. 
entry into both world wars. 
</P>
<P>
	The collection has a place for both Confederate President  
Jefferson Davis of Mississippi and for humorist Will Rogers of 
Oklahoma, whose bronze shoes are polished to a golden glow by the 
hands of tourists and, by tradition, members of the Oklahoma 
congressional delegation. 
</P>
<P>
	Among the rest, there's a lawyer with a modern footnote attached  
to his last name. 
</P>
<P>
	The footnote belongs to Uriah Milton Rose, 1834-1913, sent to  
Statuary Hall in 1917 by Arkansas. Rose founded the Rose Law Firm 
in Little Rock, the former legal headquarters of first lady Hillary 
Rodham Clinton. 
</P>
<P>
	Other than his footnote, Uriah Rose may gingerly be added to the  
list of Capitol statues for whom bronze and marble have probably 
proved more lasting than name recognition. 
</P>
<P>
	There are many others whose reputations are, at the least,  
dusty. Many would presumably have their defenders if the floodgates 
open for states to opt for change. But others might well be ushered 
from the posts of honor they have held so long. 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. John Ashcroft, R-Mo., wants term limits for statues as well  
as for living lawmakers. And if Kansas provides the opening wedge, 
he wants to send Harry Truman to Statuary Hall. That would mean 
retirement for one of the two Missourians already there: former 
Sens. Thomas Hart Benton and Francis Preston Blair. 
</P>
<P>
	For Kansas, at least, the light is flashing green.  
</P>
<P>
	``We've been told to go ahead, that no one will try to stop  
us,'' said Joey Rathbone, a spokesman for Rep. Todd Tiahrt, R-Kan. 
</P>
<P>
	The congressman is helping raise the estimated $200,000 or more  
it would take to create an Eisenhower statue and ship George 
Washington Glick back to Kansas. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	EDITOR'S NOTE: Lawrence L. Knutson has reported on Congress, the  
White House and Washington's history for more than 30 years. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
