<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Stocks Move Higher; Dow Up 19.95 / Wall Street Report  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks opened modestly higher today, extending  
last week's rally, as optimism over corporate profits drew 
investors into a quiet market. 
</P>
<P>
	In the first hour of trading on Wall Street, the Dow Jones  
industrial average was up 19.95 at 10,669.71. Last week's gain of 
almost 377 points marked the best performance by the Dow in three 
months. 
</P>
<P>
	Broader stock indicators were mixed. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500  
index was down 2.04 at 1,333.98, and the Nasdaq composite index was 
up 11.38 at 2,897.95. 
</P>
<P>
	This week, earnings reports from a wide range of companies are  
expected to drive market activity. Analysts expect most 
corporations to report strong profit growth for the recently ended 
third quarter, and warn that companies that miss expectations may 
face harsh punishment from investors. 
</P>
<P>
	Today, Knight/Trimark confirmed that prediction, falling 3 23/64  
to 26 5/8 after saying it expects to report third-quarter earnings 
between 17 cents and 19 cents per share. Analysts had expected the 
company, a securities dealer which focuses on making markets for 
Nasdaq stocks, to earn 30 cents per share in the quarter. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, a wide range of cyclical stocks rose, buoying the Dow.  
Cyclical companies tend to rise and fall along with the broader 
economy, and many are expected to show strong earnings growth in 
light of the nation's fierce economic growth. Caterpillar rose 1 
1/16 to 57 11/16, and Alcoa rose 13/16 to 62 7/16. 
</P>
<P>
	Today marks the start of the bull market's 10th year. On Oct.  
11, 1990, the Dow closed at 2365.1, and has risen 350 percent since 
then in the longest bull market in history. 
</P>
<P>
	Declining issues narrowly outnumbered advancers on the New York  
Stock Exchange, where volume came to 86.7 million shares, well 
behind Friday's early pace. Traders anticipated a quiet session as 
the bond market was closed in observance of Columbus Day. Stock 
markets were open for the full trading day. 
</P>
<P>
	The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies rose 0.74 to 428.45.  
</P>
<P>
	Overseas, Japan's stock market was closed for a national  
holiday. In afternoon trading, Germany's DAX index was up 0.1 
percent, Britain's FT-SE 100 was up 0.1 percent, and France's 
CAC-40 was down 0.1 percent. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
