<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NL Playoff Notebook </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- Braves manager Bobby Cox was secretive Monday  
about his lineup for Game 1 of the NL championship series, which 
may indicate Walt Weiss will start at shortstop instead of Jose 
Hernandez. 
</P>
<P>
	Weiss, hero of the opening-round victory over Houston, started  
69 games but served primarily as a backup after Atlanta acquired 
Hernandez from the Chicago Cubs on July 31. 
</P>
<P>
	Hernandez slumped late in the regular season and was only  
1-for-11 (.091) against the Astros, with an error. Weiss hit only 
226 during the season but is a better player defensively, as 
indicated by his game-saving play against the Astros. 
</P>
<P>
	In Game 3, Weiss made a diving stop on a hard grounder up the  
middle by Tony Eusebio, throwing out a runner at the plate with the 
bases loaded in the bottom of the 10th. The Braves won 5-3 in 12 
innings. 
</P>
<P>
	On Monday, Cox was asked about Weiss' role in the upcoming  
series against the New York Mets. 
</P>
<P>
	``I wouldn't want to answer that right now,'' the manager said.  
</P>
<P>
	Later, when asked his plans for Game 1, Cox replied, ``I'll post  
the lineup tomorrow.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *DECISIONS, DECISIONS:* Mets manager Bobby Valentine shuffled  
his rotation for the NLCS, shifting around Al Leiter and Rick Reed. 
</P>
<P>
	In the first round against Arizona, the Mets opened with Masato  
Yoshii, followed by Kenny Rogers, Reed and Leiter. For the NLCS 
against Atlanta, it will be Yoshii, Rogers, Leiter and Reed. 
</P>
<P>
	``My thought is it was more on line,'' Valentine said. ``That's  
the way we started the last series, Yoshii and Kenny Rogers. And we 
did all right. That's been our rotation for the better part of the 
second half. 
</P>
<P>
	``There really wasn't any major determining factor,'' he said.  
``We felt we had a good pitcher either way we went. It would mean a 
really long rest and wait for Kenny, and would mean a little 
extended rest for Rick.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *A NEW SEASON:* The Braves had no problem beating up on the Mets  
during the regular season, winning nine of 12 games. 
</P>
<P>
	Atlanta manager Bobby Cox knows that won't help his team win  
four more times. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a new season,'' Cox said. ``I don't think what you did in  
the past has a lot to do with what's going to happen in the future. 
They're all new ballgames.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Braves won the season series 5-4 against the Padres last  
year before being knocked out in six games in the NL championship 
series. The last time the Mets made it this far, they were knocked 
out by a Dodgers team that lost 10 of 11 in the regular season to 
New York. 
</P>
<P>
	``You really don't care,'' Game 1 starter Greg Maddux said.  
``What matters is how we play this week.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *BULLPEN BATTLE:* The Mets bullpen was the one that got all the  
accolades this season. But the Braves relievers actually outpitched 
their New York counterparts. 
</P>
<P>
	Atlanta's bullpen, led by closer John Rocker, was the second  
best in the majors, going 33-14 with 45 saves and a 3.58 ERA. The 
Mets were third, with a 31-19 record, 49 saves and a 3.67 ERA. 
</P>
<P>
	``Rocker has finished everything off and done a very good job of  
it,'' Maddux said. ``But you can't overlook the guys that have gone 
in there to pitch the seventh and eighth also.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rocker, who saved 38 games, sure isn't overlooking the  
contributions of set-up men Mike Remlinger and Terry Mulholland. 
</P>
<P>
	``Without those two guys, I think we would be kind of where the  
Mets ended up, and maybe scrapping for a wild card,'' Rocker said. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *WHAT RIVALRY?* Inflammatory comments to the contrary, Braves  
manager Bobby Cox insisted there's hardly a bitter rivalry between 
his team and the Mets. 
</P>
<P>
	Maybe that's because Atlanta spent 25 years in the NL West,  
competing regularly against Los Angeles and San Francisco. Despite 
the lack of geographical ties, the remnants of those relationships 
still endure. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Dodgers, of all things, them being on the West Coast and  
us on the East Coast, were the biggest thing we had to a rivalry,'' 
Cox said. ``We were supposed to create one with Florida, and that 
hasn't materialized.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Braves shifted to the East when baseball realigned the  
divisions in 1994, pitting them against teams of closer proximity 
such as the Marlins and Mets. But five years isn't long enough for 
a rivalry to develop. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think we have a rivalry,'' Cox said. ``The rivalry is  
who is in first and who is in second, competing each year.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Game 1 starter Greg Maddux insisted he was oblivious to the  
trash talking. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not sure what's being said. Ever since I had kids, it's no  
more ESPN,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	```Now, we're watching Franklin and stuff like that,'' he added,  
referring to the cartoon turtle. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *MELLOW ROCKER:* Maybe there will come a time when John Rocker  
walks in from the bullpen. For now, he's going to keep on running. 
</P>
<P>
	Rocker has become a fan favorite in Atlanta with his trademark  
sprint from the bullpen and his shenanigans on the mound, which 
involve constantly tugging at his hat, jersey, resin bag and 
whatever else he can get his hands on. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think I can keep up this pace for however many more  
years I've got left in me,'' he said. ``I think if I keep up with 
the frantic pace I go now, I'll probably die young, which might not 
be a bad thing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rocker has talked with other pitchers, such as former-Brave Norm  
Charlton, who displayed similar traits on the mound in their early 
years. 
</P>
<P>
	``When I watched Norm pitch, he was more mellow in the way he  
dealt with things,'' Rocker said. ``I'll calm down or burn out 
trying, I guess.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
