<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Asian Stock Markets Close Mixed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HONG KONG (AP) -- Asian stock markets closed mixed Monday, with  
key market indicators losing ground in Hong Kong, Indonesia, 
Thailand and South Korea while rising in Malaysia, Australia and 
Taiwan. 
</P>
<P>
	In Japan, the financial markets were closed for a national  
holiday. 
</P>
<P>
	Prices fell in Hong Kong in anticipation of the government  
announcement of plans to sell the stock it acquired when it propped 
up the market last year. 
</P>
<P>
	Hong Kong's blue-chip Hang Seng Index fell 119.70 points, or 0.9  
percent, closing at 12,992.72. 
</P>
<P>
	Shortly after the close of trading, officials said the  
government will start selling the shares in an offering from Oct. 
25 to Nov. 4. 
</P>
<P>
	The officials said they will package the shares into mutual  
funds and sell them, hopefully without harming prices on the Hong 
Kong Stock Exchange. The fund set up to sell the shares is called 
the Exchange Fund Investment Ltd. 
</P>
<P>
	The sale would be the government's first attempt to divest  
itself of the shareholdings amassed last August, and which are now 
worth more than $25.64 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	Some investors sold banking and property stocks, which make up  
the bulk of the government shares, in anticipation that the new 
fund will allow investors to buy the shares at a discount to 
current market prices, dealers said. 
</P>
<P>
	Indonesian shares closed lower. The Jakarta market's Composite  
Index fell 0.7 percent, or 4.177 points, to 584.060. 
</P>
<P>
	Thai stock prices closed lower, led by losses in banking stocks.  
The Stock Exchange of Thailand or SET index fell 4.14 points, or 
1.05 percent, to 388.88. 
</P>
<P>
	Share prices also fell in Seoul, pushed down by a fall in  
semiconductor stocks due to a decline in global chip prices. The 
Korea Composite Stock Price Index fell 5.02 points, or 0.5 percent, 
to 834.39. 
</P>
<P>
	Malaysian shares close higher, boosted by a plan to merge  
Malaysian banks. The Kuala Lumpur Stock Exchange's Composite index 
rose 3.55 points, or 0.5 percent, to 747.39. 
</P>
<P>
	Dealers said Malaysian Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad's remarks  
during the weekend that the government wouldn't be too rigid in 
determining the number of banks in the merger fueled speculations 
that it could be increased. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the initial plan, Malaysian 58 financial institutions will  
be fused into six banking groups. 
</P>
<P>
	The Australian stock market also closed higher, boosted by a  
strong performance from blue-chip industrial companies, noticeably 
in the finance and telecommunications sectors. The Sydney's All 
Ordinaries Index rose 29.3 points, or 1.0 percent, to 2,926.4. 
</P>
<P>
	In Taiwan, share prices closed higher, supported by technology  
and financial stocks. The market's key Weighted Stock Price Index 
rose 54.13 points, or 0.7 percent, to 7,607.11. 
</P>
<P>
	Singapore's Straits Times Index rose 7.74 points, or 0.4  
percent, to 2,122.23, the shares in the broader market were mixed. 
</P>
<P>
	New Zealand share prices closed slightly lower. The NZSE-40  
Capital Index slipped 5.29 points, or 0.2 percent, to 2,060.41. 
</P>
<P>
	Philippine shares closed mixed. The Philippine Stock Exchange  
index of 30 selected companies rose 6.34 points, or 0.3 percent, to 
2,070.17. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
