<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Magazine Offers Peek at Diana Book </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SYDNEY, Australia (AP) -- Readers of an Australian magazine got a  
peek today at the memoirs of Princess Diana's lover James Hewitt 
after a British tabloid backed down from serializing his book. 
</P>
<P>
	Britain's Mail on Sunday newspaper last month backed out of a  
$492,000 serialization deal after Diana's brother wrote to the 
editor asking him not to publish details about the late princess. 
</P>
<P>
	But in Australia, Woman's Day published a 16-page insert of  
Hewitt's book ``Love and War,'' which details his five-year affair 
with Diana, Princess of Wales, that began when she was still 
married to Prince Charles in 1986. 
</P>
<P>
	Some excerpts from the book were also printed in Sunday's  
edition of The Daily News in New York. 
</P>
<P>
	While the prospect of publication caused uproar in Britain, it  
barely caused a ripple in Australia. 
</P>
<P>
	In the first of a three-part series, Hewitt, a former Life  
Guards cavalry officer, writes of meeting and falling in love with 
Diana. 
</P>
<P>
	``There she was at the bottom of the stairs, in a long summer  
skirt, with bare feet, her shoes in her hand,'' he writes of their 
first meeting at Buckingham Palace. 
</P>
<P>
	The man who later became her lover talks of palace pillow fights  
with Diana's two children, William and Harry, but labels as 
``disgusting'' rumors he is Prince Harry's father. 
</P>
<P>
	He claims Diana initiated the affair, saying her marriage to  
Prince Charles was all but over. 
</P>
<P>
	Hewitt was labeled a ``love rat'' and ``the most hated man in  
Britain'' by British tabloids after he collaborated on a book by 
journalist Anna Pasternak entitled ``Princess in Love.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hewitt began selling stories about Diana in 1993 soon after she  
broke off the affair. Extracts printed today contain more detail 
about the food the couple ate than their love life. 
</P>
<P>
	Writing of their first night together, Hewitt writes: ``The main  
course was chicken in a lemon and cream sauce, with mashed potatoes 
and mange tout and French beans.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A few paragraphs later he simply adds: ``That evening our affair  
began.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hewitt claims Diana told him her former bodyguard Barry  
Mannakee, who later died, was an earlier lover. 
</P>
<P>
	And he reveals Diana sent him copies of Playboy and Penthouse  
while he was stationed in the Persian Gulf during the 1991 conflict 
with Iraq. 
</P>
<P>
	Woman's Day deputy editor Lorrae Willox did not reveal how much  
the magazine paid for serialization rights. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
