<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Limping Denver Regains A Bit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DENVER (AP) -- With Denver's first victory of the season finally  
in hand, defensive end Neil Smith mocked the inhospitable Oakland 
crowd with a sign that read, ``Look at the score.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He simultaneously sent a message to the doubters who had given  
up the Broncos for dead. 
</P>
<P>
	One week after an anonymous Denver player was quoted as saying,  
``We're finished,'' the Broncos (1-4) can at least claim to be 
breathing after their 16-13 victory over the Raiders on Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's been a sense of desperation around here,'' defensive  
end Harald Hasselbach said Monday. ``Anybody who didn't feel 
desperation, I don't know what locker room they were in, but they 
weren't in ours.'' 
</P>
<P>
	For the first time since winning their second straight Super  
Bowl nine months ago, the Broncos were able to celebrate a victory 
when Tory James intercepted a pass in the game's final minute. 
</P>
<P>
	Offensive lineman Mark Schlereth called the win more satisfying  
than the recent Super Bowl title. Others were more conservative 
when describing the importance of avoiding the first 0-5 start in 
franchise history. 
</P>
<P>
	``When you haven't won in so long, it's a great feeling to get a  
win,'' cornerback Ray Crockett said. ``That was the magnitude of 
it, that you finally got a win.'' 
</P>
<P>
	If Denver regained any championship swagger, it comes with a  
limp. 
</P>
<P>
	All-Pro tight end Shannon Sharpe broke his left collarbone and  
will be out 7-to-9 weeks, joining MVP running back Terrell Davis 
and linebacker John Mobley on the long-term injured list. 
</P>
<P>
	The Broncos also will know more this week about the status of  
quarterback Bubby Brister (strained oblique muscle) and Davis' 
replacement, Derek Loville, (strained hamstring). Neither played 
against Oakland. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was pretty crowded in the training room today,'' Loville  
said. ``We took a few on the chin, but it's OK. It's a long season. 
We've got 11 more games. You never know what could happen.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The schedule does not offer the Broncos much solace as Green Bay  
(3-1) travels to Denver on Sunday, followed by a road game against 
New England (4-1) and a home date with Minnesota (2-3). 
</P>
<P>
	At least Denver is assured of avoiding an 0-8 start -- the  
scenario suggested by one player in an article in Sports 
Illustrated last week. 
</P>
<P>
	``Hopefully we can get on a roll here,'' coach Mike Shanahan  
said. ``Guys are feeling good about themselves. We won a football 
game in a tough situation. It carries over.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Denver's first victory raised new questions about the team's  
ongoing quarterback shuffle. Brian Griese, demoted last week, 
played his best game of the season but will return to the bench if 
Brister is healthy Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's always going to be, `What do you do here?' If you want  
Bubby. If you want Brian,'' Shanahan said. ``Going into that game, 
Bubby had an excellent week of preparation. He was fired up to 
play. If he's healthy, he's going to go. If not, we'll go in a 
different direction.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
