<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Victory Helps Ease Falcon's Pain </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SUWANEE, Ga. (AP) -- The injuries are definitely piling up  
quicker than the victories for the Atlanta Falcons. 
</P>
<P>
	The NFC champions won for the first time this season, beating  
New Orleans 20-17 Sunday, but any euphoria was offset by injuries 
to their top two linebackers. 
</P>
<P>
	Keith Brooking, the first-round draft pick in 1998, will be out  
at least three weeks with a knee injury, while Pro Bowl selection 
Jessie Tuggle is doubtful for Sunday's game against unbeaten St. 
Louis because of a sore thigh. 
</P>
<P>
	The Falcons (1-4) beat the Saints without their best offensive  
players, quarterback Chris Chandler and running back Jamal 
Anderson. 
</P>
<P>
	At least coach Dan Reeves knows his team hasn't forgotten how to  
win. 
</P>
<P>
	``Well, I think your mental outlook is a heck of a lot better,''  
he said Monday. ``You are answering questions about how you won 
rather than answering questions about how you lost. That is huge.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Tuggle, the Falcons' 13-year defensive cornerstone, aggravated a  
left thigh injury against the Saints and missed nearly the entire 
second half. 
</P>
<P>
	Tuggle was capably replaced by rookie linebacker Jeff Kelly, a  
sixth-round draft pick who had played only on special teams this 
year. He had five tackles and a forced fumble. 
</P>
<P>
	The injury to Brooking, the team's leading tackler with 38, is  
more serious. The former Georgia Tech standout tore a ligament in 
his right knee and will miss at least three weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	Ruffin Hamilton, who took over when Brooking went down, played  
well enough to be named defensive player of the game by the 
coaches. 
</P>
<P>
	``Losing two of your best players on defense and having two guys  
to step in like that and fill a void is critical,'' defensive 
coordinator Rich Brooks said. ``If they hadn't played well, we had 
no chance to win the game.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Anderson's season ended in Week 2 with a knee injury and a  
pulled hamstring has caused Chandler to sit out three games and 
part of a fourth. 
</P>
<P>
	Injuries on defense, however, are more prevalent and arguably  
more costly. 
</P>
<P>
	The 34-year-old Tuggle has missed only four games over the last  
10 years -- a 165-game span in which he became a fan favorite with a 
nickname, ``The Hammer,'' that reflected just how hard he hit 
opponents. 
</P>
<P>
	``I remember (linebacker Henri Crockett) saying, `The leader is  
down. We have to step up,''' Kelly said. ``The Saints' offensive 
line was looking around to see where Tuggle was. Everybody told me, 
`They'll be coming right at you.' But I guess I did OK.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Also ailing is left defensive end Lester Archambeau, who  
persevered Sunday with a bad shoulder and neck. Defensive end Chuck 
Smith has endured the entire season with an injured toe. 
</P>
<P>
	Starting defensive tackles Travis Hall (thumb) and Shane Dronett  
(neck) were forced to rotate with backups Shawn Swayda and Pellom 
McDaniels -- much to the dismay of Dronett. 
</P>
<P>
	He grew so incensed with the temporary demotion that he  
initiated a sideline argument in the third quarter with defensive 
line coach Bill Kollar. 
</P>
<P>
	Backup tackle Ed Jasper has the same injury as Brooking but  
could return this week. The Falcons also have Crockett playing with 
an ailing thigh, and Hamilton missed the previous two games with a 
bad hamstring. 
</P>
<P>
	In the secondary, cornerback Michael Booker missed the first  
three games with a partially torn thigh muscle, and rookie safety 
Johndale Carty left Sunday's game with an injured hamstring. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
