<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Wisconsin Coach Delays Knee Surgery </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MADISON, Wis. (AP) -- Doctors have delayed knee replacement  
surgery for Wisconsin football coach Barry Alvarez who now is 
expected to undergo the operation after the Big Ten season. 
</P>
<P>
	The 52-year-old Alvarez went to the Mayo Clinic in Rochester,  
Minn., last week and was expected to have the surgery to replace 
his severely arthritic right knee on Oct. 5. 
</P>
<P>
	However, a tissue infection was discovered in early stages of  
the surgery and the knee replacement was halted. 
</P>
<P>
	The Wisconsin sports information office said Monday that Alvarez  
was cleared for release Tuesday from the Mayo Clinic. Back in 
Madison, he will require nursing care in his home to administer 
antibiotics and help with physical therapy while he works on 
increasing the range of motion and strength in the knee. 
</P>
<P>
	His progress in physical therapy will determine how soon he can  
return to some coaching duties. Plans for the knee replacement 
surgery also are dependent on everything going well with his 
rehabilitation. 
</P>
<P>
	Alvarez said Monday he was mildly frustrated by the delay.  
</P>
<P>
	``You come out of surgery and plan on having a new knee and they  
tell you that you don't because you have an infection,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Alvarez watched on a big-screen television Saturday as his  
17th-ranked Badgers beat Minnesota 20-17 in overtime. He talked to 
his coaches by telephone from his hospital room. 
</P>
<P>
	A nursing supervisor asked him to keep it down a couple times  
during the game, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Sitting in the (press) box is passive enough, let alone in a  
hospital bed,'' he said. ``Then they cut away to a commercial. It 
is very frustrating and very strange.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Alvarez coached the Badgers' previous games against Michigan and  
Ohio State from the press box. 
</P>
<P>
	The knee has caused Alvarez severe pain ever since he re-injured  
it while attending an exhibition game in Madison between the Green 
Bay Packers and the Denver Broncos on Aug. 23. Internal bleeding 
was filling the joint with fluids. 
</P>
<P>
	John Palermo, Wisconsin's assistant head coach and defensive  
line coach, is acting head coach until Alvarez returns. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
