<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Suspect Charged in Chicago Killings </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- DNA evidence from a string of unsolved killings  
and rapes in several South Side neighborhoods has led police to one 
possible suspect: a man in a Chicago jail. 
</P>
<P>
	Ronald Macon, 35, has been charged with three counts of  
first-degree murder. The Chicago man has been in jail since August 
awaiting trial on a separate rape charge. 
</P>
<P>
	Police said DNA evidence linked him to three of 13 killings of  
women in and around the poverty-stricken Englewood neighborhood 
since 1993. Police Cmdr. Frank Trigg said Sunday that Macon 
confessed on videotape to the killings. 
</P>
<P>
	Authorities said Macon's arrest was the breakthrough they had  
been hoping for, but their investigation into the other murders 
continue. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is going to continue because the perpetrators are still  
out there,'' Trigg said. ``But we're certainly going to pause and 
acknowledge the significance of this.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Macon's three alleged victims were all killed this year in the  
Englewood and Washington Park neighborhoods. Angelnetta Peeples, 
43, was found in an abandoned building Feb. 20. She had been 
strangled and hit on the head. 
</P>
<P>
	Linda Soloman, 36, who was found April 14 in a stairwell, also  
had been strangled and hit on the head. Rosezina Williams, 50, was 
strangled and her body found in a trash container on June 21. 
</P>
<P>
	Authorities said Macon could face the death penalty if convicted  
on the murder charges. They said they also might charge him with 
rape. 
</P>
<P>
	Macon is being held in lieu of $1.25 million bond on the current  
rape charge. He could be arraigned on the murder charges as early 
as today, Trigg said. 
</P>
<P>
	Until Macon's arrest, police have had little success in their  
investigation into the string of slayings. Few people in the 
neighborhoods knew the women or were willing to talk to police. 
</P>
<P>
	The authorities thought their luck might be changing last month  
when they charged three men with the March 1998 slaying of 
LaCreesha Avery, 27. 
</P>
<P>
	Avery, who was beaten, raped and strangled, was found wrapped in  
one of the suspects' sheets in the same general area where the 
other bodies were found, police said. 
</P>
<P>
	Authorities thought the men might be tied to other unsolved  
murders, but later found that DNA samples from the men showed no 
connection. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
