<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-11 00:20:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Sprewell To Miss Exhibition Game </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Latrell Sprewell's excuse for missing the first  
week of training camp wasn't a good one. In fact, he really had 
none. He simply decided to blow it off in favor of a cross-country 
drive. 
</P>
<P>
	``To me, it was obvious where I was at,'' Sprewell explained  
Sunday following a week of uncertainty over his whereabouts. 
</P>
<P>
	Sprewell said he ignored the Knicks' phone messages as he drove  
a 36-hour stretch solo in his Mercedes-Benz sedan from Oakland to 
his home in Milwaukee, arriving before dawn Wednesday, and then 
continued on to New York a day later with his brother and a friend. 
</P>
<P>
	The Knicks expected him to arrive at camp in Charleston, S.C.,  
by Wednesday morning. He'll be fined as much as $40,000 and will 
have to sit out the first exhibition game Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Sprewell nonchalantly explained that he drove instead of taking  
a flight because he wanted to pick up some things in Milwaukee and 
he wanted to be sure that his car made it to New York. 
</P>
<P>
	``I really didn't call anybody. I'm not denying I didn't call  
them back; I just didn't,'' he said. ``It's on me. I didn't really 
communicate to anybody. It's like, I'll get there; I'll be there. 
It was not like I'm ditching camp.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sprewell met with coach Jeff Van Gundy and general manager Scott  
Layden for 45 minutes Sunday morning at the team's practice 
facility. Sprewell arrived 20 minutes late. 
</P>
<P>
	Van Gundy and Layden refused to divulge many details of the  
meeting. 
</P>
<P>
	The rest of the Knicks had the day off Sunday. Sprewell will  
join them for his first practice -- it will be the team's 10th -- 
today at Madison Square Garden before the team holds a public 
scrimmage. Sprewell will not play but is not officially suspended 
for the exhibition opener in Uniondale, N.Y., against the 
Philadelphia 76ers. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't know how our team is going to react,'' Van Gundy said.  
``I think Latrell most likely will need to address the situation to 
his teammates, and how the team from the inside handles it will be 
between them.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sprewell said his lateness had nothing to do with his contract  
situation. Entering the final year of a four-year deal that will 
pay him $9 million this season, Sprewell is eligible to sign an 
extension during the season. 
</P>
<P>
	Madison Square Garden president Dave Checketts said over the  
summer that the Knicks were eager to begin discussing an extension, 
although it is unclear now if the Knicks will be a reluctant to 
commit as much as $60 or $70 million to Sprewell in a long-term 
deal. 
</P>
<P>
	Layden said the Knicks remain committed to Sprewell, while  
Sprewell said he'll wait and see what kind of money the Knicks 
offer him. 
</P>
<P>
	``It depends on what the numbers are like,'' Sprewell said.  
``Obviously I want to do what's best for me, so I have to see what 
that entails.'' 
</P>
<P>
	What also remains to be seen is how this episode affects  
Sprewell's relationship with Van Gundy following a season in which 
they didn't see eye to eye on the question of whether Sprewell 
should have been a starter or a sixth man. Van Gundy didn't move 
Sprewell into the starting lineup until the Eastern Conference 
finals against Indiana. 
</P>
<P>
	Sprewell does not want to come off the bench this season,  
although he said that had nothing to do with his absence from camp. 
</P>
<P>
	``I wasn't trying to send a message,'' Sprewell said. ``People  
are going to think what they want to think. I don't see any reason 
why we can't hit the ground running. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm a big part of what we do, but I wasn't the sole reason why  
we got so far last year,'' he said. ``We still have time. It's not 
like the first game is tomorrow or in a week.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
