<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 6 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Monday, Oct. 11, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	Clinton Seeks Test Ban Vote Delay  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton asked the Senate in writing  
on today to put off voting on the nuclear test ban treaty, warning 
that a likely defeat in tomorrow's scheduled vote would ``severely 
harm the national security.'' Republicans called his letter a first 
step toward possibly postponing the vote, but sought further 
assurances the issue wouldn't come up again during this 106th 
Congress. By putting his request in writing, Clinton met one GOP 
demand. His letter was silent on their insistence that he promise 
not to revive it during the 2000 election season, but White House 
officials rejected that request. 

</P>
<P>
	Labor Expected To Back Gore  
</P>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- AFL-CIO President John Sweeney declared war  
today on an ``ugly, anti-poor, anti-working family'' Republican 
congressional majority as all signs pointed to an endorsement of 
Vice President Al Gore by the 13-million-member labor federation. 
The endorsement would almost immediately kick into gear a 
$40-million mobilization meant as much to strengthen Gore as to 
wrest control of Congress from the Republicans and topple GOP 
presidential front-runner George W. Bush. After backroom lobbying 
by Sweeney, the endorsement of Gore appeared secure. 

</P>
<P>
	S.African Co. Offers AIDS Insurance  
</P>
<P>
	JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) -- AIDS and rape are so common in  
South Africa that an insurance company is offering a policy to try 
to protect rape victims from contracting the disease. The policy, 
to be introduced tomorrow by the CGU Insurance Ltd, provides a 
one-month course of anti-retroviral drugs to prevent infection, a 
year's worth of AIDS tests and counseling. The new policy arrives 
as South Africa's two ugliest social problems are dominating the 
attention of the media and public officials. 

</P>
<P>
	Michigan St. Treats Meningitis Case  
</P>
<P>
	EAST LANSING, Mich. (AP) -- Hundreds of Michigan State University  
students lined up today for vaccines against bacterial meningitis 
as another student remained in the hospital battling the infection. 
Adam Busuttil was in critical condition. Meningitis is a swelling 
of the lining surrounding the brain and spinal cord and comes in 
two forms -- the common and not very serious viral meningitis and 
the rare bacterial meningitis, which can be fatal. Busuttil has the 
bacterial form. 

</P>
<P>
	UAW Wraps Up Three Auto Agreements  
</P>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- The United Auto Workers wrapped up three new  
contracts with American automakers that promise some 360,000 
workers more money and security for the next four years. The deals 
with General Motors Corp., Ford Motor Co., and DaimlerChrysler AG 
followed peaceful and quick negotiations that avoided costly 
strikes. The pattern agreement made by the UAW is a four-year 
contract with 3 percent raises each year, a signing bonus of $1,350 
and improvements in pensions and cost-of-living adjustments. The 
automakers won the freedom they sought to reduce costs, including 
shedding workers. 

</P>
<P>
	Buffet Gives Teen Finance Advice  
</P>
<P>
	OMAHA, Neb. (AP) -- Multibillionaire investor Warren Buffett gave  
some valuable advice to a group of Nebraska teens today: Avoid 
credit cards. In a forum on economics, the third-richest man in 
America and chairman of Berkshire Hathaway Inc. also urged the 
students to: develop integrity, establish good habits, learn about 
companies before investing in them and choose professions for love 
of the work, not the money. Doing well in the United States is not 
far removed from being rich, said Buffett, who added with 
self-effacing humor: ``I'll pay more for my suits than you will, 
but as soon as I put it on, it will look cheap on me.'' 

</P>
<P>
	Nasdaq Pushes to Record Close  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The Nasdaq composite index pushed to a record  
high close today as the promise of strong corporate earnings pumped 
up technology stocks. The Nasdaq was up 29.48 at 2,916.05. At the 
close of trading on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial average 
was down 1.58 at 10,648.18. Declining issues on the New York Stock 
Exchange led advancers 1,558-1,391. 

</P>
<P>
	Gordon Wins 7th at UAW-GM Quality 500  
</P>
<P>
	CONCORD, N.C. (AP) -- Jeff Gordon caught and passed Bobby Labonte  
with seven laps to go today, pulling away to win the rain-delayed 
UAW-GM Quality 500 at Lowe's Motor Speedway. It was the series-high 
seventh win this season for Gordon, who moved into a tie for 10th 
on the Winston Cup career list with Rusty Wallace at 49. Despite 
the wins, it hasn't been a vintage year for Gordon, now fourth in 
the season points after winning three of the last four 
championships and finishing second the other year. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by LISI de BOURBON  



  	   	
</P>
