<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-11 11:10:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Justice Foresees Global Disputes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Supreme Court increasingly will be asked  
to look beyond U.S. borders when resolving 21st century disputes, 
Justice Sandra Day O'Connor predicts. 
</P>
<P>
	Calling herself ``just a cowgirl from Arizona,'' O'Connor  
recently told a Navy War College audience in Newport, R.I., ``The 
world is increasingly interdependent and demands that we 
participate in a global community.'' She said America must learn 
``how to live in a world with porous borders,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	O'Connor, who took questions after her speech, said world trade  
treaties, ever-improving communications technology and 
multinational organizations blur the borders between nations and 
give rise to numerous legal questions. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	Justice John Paul Stevens also has been out on the stump talking  
about blurred lines, but in a completely different context. The 
oldest justice is complaining about a recent practice of newly 
confirmed Supreme Court appointees. 
</P>
<P>
	Two oaths -- constitutional and judicial -- are taken before a  
justice takes his or her place on the bench, and Stevens noted 
during a speech at the Gerald R. Ford Museum in Grand Rapids, 
Mich., that for decades both oaths were administered at the Supreme 
Court building. 
</P>
<P>
	``In recent years, some of my colleagues have taken their first  
oath in a televised proceeding conducted at the White House,'' said 
Stevens, 79. ``I ... have refused to attend the last four of those 
televised events.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Why? ``It is, in my judgment, a serious mistake to replace an  
important symbol of the independence of the federal judiciary with 
an event that tends to blur the critical distinction between 
political and judicial service,'' Stevens said. 
</P>
<P>
	Stevens, one of the court's most prolific dissenters,  
acknowledged that ``my colleagues do not share my concern.'' 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	Arizona's Republican senators, Jon Kyl and John McCain, want a  
new federal courthouse being built in Phoenix to bear O'Connor's 
name. 
</P>
<P>
	``Justice O'Connor has been making history throughout her long  
and distinguished career,'' Kyl said in announcing that he and 
McCain were introducing legislation to bring about the honor. ``She 
... should be recognized for that service.'' 
</P>
<P>
	O'Connor, 69, became the first woman on the Supreme Court when  
appointed by President Reagan in 1981. 
</P>
<P>
	Her name already is attached to a high school in Helotes, Texas.  
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	Wanda Martinson, who for 25 years served as No. 1 secretary to  
Justice Harry A. Blackmun, has left the court for a new job. She is 
confidential assistant to Solicitor General Seth Waxman, the 
Clinton administration's chief advocate before the Supreme Court. 
</P>
<P>
	Blackmun died in March at age 90, five years after he retired.  
Martinson has spent recent months cleaning off his offices. 
</P>
<P>
	At a sendoff party for Martinson last week, Chief Justice  
William H. Rehnquist described her early career with painstaking 
detail. ``All this came to me in a dream,'' said Rehnquist, 
laughing, when asked about his research. 
</P>
<P>
	Martinson was given a flag that had flown over the court plaza  
on the 1999-2000 court term's opening day, but Rehnquist mistakenly 
told her it had flown at ``half-staff.'' Catching his error, the 
chief justice said: ``We aren't that sad.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Justices Ruth Bader Ginsburg and Stephen G. Breyer spoke about  
Martinson's kindness to them and their office staffs when they were 
high court rookies. Also on hand were Justices Antonin Scalia and 
David H. Souter and retired Justice Byron R. White. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
