<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Vanguard Releasing After-Tax Figures </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- The Vanguard Group will begin publishing the  
after-tax returns for 47 of its stock and balanced funds, in a move 
the company said will give investors a clearer picture of their 
funds' actual return. 
</P>
<P>
	The nation's second-largest mutual fund firm is the first fund  
company to disclose after-tax returns on a broad range of mutual 
funds. 
</P>
<P>
	``Vanguard has long recognized the importance of discussing tax  
facts in evaluating mutual fund returns,'' said Joel Dickson, 
Vanguard principal and tax specialist. ``We see the actual 
publication of returns as a next logical step in providing 
investors the information they need to assess how their portfolio 
has performed.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The information debuts in Vanguard's U.S. Growth Fund and its  
International Growth Fund's 1999 annual reports being mailed to 
shareholders this week, Dickson said Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	According to Vanguard, taxes have deducted about 2.5 percentage  
points per year off the return of its U.S. stock mutual funds over 
the past 10 years. Investors in the company's largest portfolio, 
Vanguard Index 500 Fund, saw taxes take away 1.2 points per year. 
On the high end, taxes erased 3.5 points per year from the return 
of actively managed Vanguard Windsor Fund. 
</P>
<P>
	Vanguard's step may lead other fund groups to start providing  
similar disclosures, but investors should keep in mind that the 
return information is not customized and will vary from person to 
person, said Geoff Bobroff, a fund consultant in East Greenwich, 
R.I. 
</P>
<P>
	``What they're proposing to do is a great first step in  
providing information to investors about their investments, but 
it's going to have to be somewhat uniformly applied,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The after-tax figures are calculated based on the highest  
individual federal income-tax rates -- currently 39.6 percent for 
dividends and short-term capital gains distributions and 20 percent 
for long-term capital-gains distributions. State and local taxes 
are not included. 
</P>
<P>
	Vanguard will present tables showing pretax and after-tax  
figures over one-, five- and 10-year periods. For comparison, the 
returns use calculations by Morningstar Inc. of after-tax returns 
of similar funds. 
</P>
<P>
	Morningstar calculates that industrywide, mutual funds that are  
set up to minimize taxes lost just 0.22 percentage point of their 
return to taxes in the 12 months ended Sept. 30, while the average 
growth fund lost 1.67 points to taxes. 
</P>
<P>
	Morningstar's data indicated that growth funds' overall  
after-tax performance still was better than tax-managed funds for 
the past 12 months, although tax-managed funds outperformed growth 
funds for both the past three years and the past five years. There 
are relatively few tax-managed funds, however, compared with growth 
funds, and even fewer tax-managed funds existed three and five 
years ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Giving investors more information is a good move but Vanguard  
may be ``preaching to the converted,'' said Daniel P. Wiener, 
editor of The Independent Adviser for Vanguard Investors 
newsletter. 
</P>
<P>
	``If you get the annual report, you're already a shareholder ...  
you're going to have to work a little harder for it if you're not a 
shareholder,'' he said. ``But it's a good first step. They're going 
to get a lot of kudos for this, and they deserve it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The after-tax information will not be available to investors in  
tax-deferred accounts such as IRAs or 401(k)s, Dickson said. 
</P>
<P>
	Vanguard, based in Valley Forge, Pa., serves 14 million clients  
and manages nearly $500 billion, including the retirement 
investments of The Associated Press. 
</P>
<P>
	``Any information that's useful and provides a better  
representation of returns ... is beneficial,'' Dickson said. 
``Although it's difficult to do an exact evaluation, we know what 
isn't correct -- and that's a zero percent tax rate.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
