<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> N.C. Schools Rely on Trailers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TARBORO, N.C. (AP) -- More than 600 children filed into  
classrooms assembled out of trailers Monday, more than three weeks 
after Hurricane Floyd's floodwaters engulfed their schools. 
</P>
<P>
	The youngsters were greeted with hugs and stuffed animals.  
</P>
<P>
	``It's so good to hear the children laughing again,'' Edgecombe  
County schools spokeswoman Diane LeFiles said. 
</P>
<P>
	The children hadn't set foot in a classroom since Sept. 15, the  
day before Floyd swamped North Carolina with more than 20 inches of 
rain. The floodwaters swallowed farms and towns and killed at least 
49 people. 
</P>
<P>
	The 12 other Edgecombe County schools opened last week, but the  
Princeville Montessori School and the Pattillo A+ Elementary School 
were so heavily damaged that dozens of trailers had to be brought 
in to serve as classrooms for at least the rest of the school year. 
</P>
<P>
	School officials have yet to determine whether the two buildings  
can be repaired. 
</P>
<P>
	``My children were so excited that they couldn't sleep last  
night,'' said Janice Davidson, whose twin 8-year-olds attend 
Princeville Montessori. 
</P>
<P>
	Mary Odom, Princeville Montessori's principal, said a crisis  
team was on hand for the youngsters but didn't appear needed. 
``They're young, and they just bounce right back. They were ready 
to get back,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	About half the students at Odom's school are from Princeville, a  
town of 1,900 founded by former slaves. Princeville was inundated 
by the Tar River, and it will probably be next year before 
residents can return home. Many are staying with friends and 
relatives; a few remain in a shelter at a high school. 
</P>
<P>
	At Pattillo, a donated stuffed animal sat on the desk of each  
student. Later in the day, Kathy Valadja of Pittsburgh and her two 
sons brought 930 stuffed animals to Princeville Montessori. 
</P>
<P>
	Her 10-year-old son Alex came up with the idea. He and his  
friends collected the animals and raised more than $1,000 for Floyd 
victims. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
