<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> European stocks close mixed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- European stocks closed mixed Monday, with the  
pharmaceutical industry leading the rise and oil shares falling. 
</P>
<P>
	Shares in SmithKline Beecham jumped 38.5 pence, or 5 percent, to  
813 pence and Glaxo shares rose 70 pence, or 4 percent, to 1,801 
pence. 
</P>
<P>
	The stocks rose after rumors circulated that SmithKline  
Beecham's chief executive Jan Leschly was to retire early, but the 
company denied that he was leaving. Still, the rumors set off 
merger speculation as Leschly was seen as the main obstacle to a 
deal between the pharmaceutical companies, after talks broke down 
last year. 
</P>
<P>
	In the European bourses, oil stocks were among those falling,  
with BP Amoco down 2 pence to 538 pence, Shell dropping 2 pence to 
439 pence. In Paris, Total Fina lost 2.00 euros to close at 112.00 
euros. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dow Jones Stoxx Index of 614 European companies rose 0.78  
points to close at 313.15. The pharmaceutical index was the best 
performer, with a gain of 2.3 percent, followed by the technology 
index, which rose 1.2 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dow Jones Euro Stoxx Index, which tracks 310 companies in  
countries that joined the single currency, closed up 0.53 points at 
327.75. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dow Jones Euro Stoxx 50 Index rose 5.57 points to 3789.89,  
while the DJ Stoxx 50 Index closed up 18.40 points at 3775.51. 
</P>
<P>
	In London, the FTSE 100 index of blue-chip shares rose 0.6  
percent, to close at 6,234.8. In addition to the jump in 
pharmaceutical shares, telecommunications stocks also rose. 
</P>
<P>
	Vodafone AirTouch rose 12.25 pence to 315.25 pence, Orange rose  
68 pence to 1,419 pence, and British Telecommunications rose 23 
pence to 1,018.5 pence. 
</P>
<P>
	However, in the rest of Europe, telecommunications shares fell,  
with Deutsche Telekom down 89 pence at 42.11 euros. Traders 
attributed the decline to uncertainty about the future of the 
company's Global One partnership with Sprint Corp. and France 
Telecom, which itself lost 2.35 euros to close at 86.50 euros. 
</P>
<P>
	Frankfurt's Xetra DAX index fell 0.1 percent to 5,414.40, the  
Paris CAC-40 index rose 0.42 of a point to 4,722.35, Milan's MIBtel 
index fell 0.2 percent to 33,837 and Amsterdam's AEX index fell 0.9 
percent to 559.77. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
