<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 11 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Monday, Oct. 11, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	U.N. Official Fatally Shot in Kosovo  
</P>
<P>
	PRISTINA, Yugoslavia (AP) -- A staffer working for the U.N.  
civilian mission in Kosovo was shot and killed Monday night after 
his first day on the job, U.N. officials said. The staffer was shot 
on the main street of the capital, Pristina, on his way to dinner 
after arriving for duty earlier in the day, spokesman Manoel de 
Almeida e Silva said in New York. Members of the U.N. police force 
in Pristina said the man, apparently a Bulgarian national, was shot 
near the Grand Hotel, where many international workers stay. 

</P>
<P>
	Clinton Pushes Senate for Test Ban Delay  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton formally asked the Senate  
today to delay tomorrow's vote on the nuclear test ban treaty, 
warning that a likely defeat would hurt national security. 
Republicans called his letter a first step toward possibly 
postponing the vote, but sought assurances the issue wouldn't come 
up again during this 106th Congress. By putting his request in 
writing, Clinton met one demand of his Republican opponents. The 
letter was silent on their insistence that Clinton promise not to 
revive it during the 2000 election season, and White House 
officials rejected that request. 

</P>
<P>
	World Population Is Six Billion  
</P>
<P>
	SARAJEVO, Bosnia-Herzegovina (AP) -- The world's six billionth  
person was said to have been born two minutes after midnight 
Tuesday in Sarajevo. The United Nations estimated that the world's 
population would reach six billion Tuesday, and the first child 
born here was to be designated as the symbolic Baby Six Billion. 
Dr. Idris Bukvic, pediatrics chief at Sarajevo's hospital, said 
Fatima Nevic gave birth to the 8-pound, heathy boy after a 
seven-hour labor. Mother and baby were fine, he said. 

</P>
<P>
	U.S. Citizen Wins Nobel for Medicine  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- A scientist at New York's Rockefeller University  
won the Nobel Prize in medicine today for discovering how proteins 
find their rightful places in cells. Dr. Guenter Blobel, 63, a 
German native who became a U.S. citizen in the 1980s, said that by 
showing how cells work when they're healthy, his research might 
help scientists understand what goes wrong in diseases. Blobel 
found that after proteins are created, they reach their various 
workplaces because they carry signals that indicate where to go. 
These signals determine whether a protein ends up in a certain 
compartment of a cell, takes up residence in the cell wall, or is 
expelled from the cell. Mistakes can kill a cell or cause disease. 

</P>
<P>
	Saudi Dissident Deported From U.S.  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A Saudi dissident who reneged on a deal to  
cooperate with U.S. investigators was deported to Saudi Arabia to 
face charges of helping in a 1996 attack that killed 19 U.S. 
airmen, the U.S. and Saudi governments announced today. Hani 
al-Sayegh left the United States on a U.S. government aircraft late 
last night from Atlanta, where he had been detained for the last 
two years. Accompanied on the flight by FBI and immigration service 
agents, he arrived in Riyadh, Saudi Arabia, today, the Justice 
Department said. 

</P>
<P>
	Taliban: Labeled Men Not Terrorists  
</P>
<P>
	KABUL, Afghanistan (AP) -- Afghanistan's reclusive religious  
leader on Monday said that men labeled terrorists by the United 
States are considered ``mujahedeen,'' or holy warriors, by the 
Taliban religious army. Mullah Mohammed Omar also warned Washington 
not to threaten the Taliban or Afghanistan. But he didn't elaborate 
on what actions, if any, the Taliban were prepared to take. 

</P>
<P>
	Tokyo Stock Prices Rise  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Stocks climbed on Tuesday in Japan. The Nikkei rose  
42.57 points to 18,104.75 in morning trading. In New York, the Dow 
Jones industrial average fell 1.58 points to close Monday at 
10,648.18. Spurred by a rise in the semiconductor sector, the 
technology heavy Nasdaq rose 29.48 points to 2,916.05, a new high. 

</P>
<P>
	Indians' Lofton Injures Shoulder  
</P>
<P>
	CLEVELAND (AP) -- Cleveland center fielder Kenny Lofton  
dislocated his left shoulder during tonight's fifth and deciding 
game of the AL division series against Boston. He was admitted to a 
hospital. Lofton was hurt in the fourth inning when he hit a ground 
ball to Boston first baseman Mike Stanley and slid head first in an 
attempt to beat the throw to pitcher Pedro Martinez, covering at 
first. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by KELLY GRUEL  
  	   	
</P>
