<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Italy Seeks Antiquities Protection </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Italian officials are enlisting State  
Department help in their effort to curb the pillaging of coveted 
antiquities by American collectors, dealers and museums. 
</P>
<P>
	An Italian request to impose restrictions on imports of the  
valued vases, figurines and pottery pieces was being taken up today 
at a public session sponsored by the State Department's Cultural 
Property Advisory Committee. 
</P>
<P>
	The committee ultimately will make recommendations to the  
president. An early decision is not expected. 
</P>
<P>
	On the Italian side is a 1970 international convention aimed at  
reducing the incentive for pillage of national treasures. But some 
collectors and their allies believe the Italian request is too 
sweeping. They will try to limit any restrictions. 
</P>
<P>
	That objective would be achieved under legislation introduced by  
New York Sens. Daniel Patrick Moynihan and Charles Schumer, both 
Democrats. 
</P>
<P>
	Several sources told The Washington Post that the categories  
covered by Italy's still-secret petition embrace virtually every 
type of high-value artifact produced or found in ancient Italy. 
</P>
<P>
	This would include Attic pottery made in Greece and either  
looted by Romans or purchased by them and buried in their tombs. 
</P>
<P>
	Jerome M. Eisenberg, owner of New York's Royal-Athena Galleries  
and the publisher of the antiquities magazine Minerva, told the 
Post, ``Ancient art always traveled. We're concerned with art theft 
but (the scope of the Italian request) is absurd.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In support of their petition, Italian authorities are likely to  
focus on a 1997 case in which a New Yorker, Michael Steinhardt, 
lost his 4th century B.C. antique gold platter when a judge ruled 
it had been imported illegally into the United States from Italy. 
He paid $1.2 million for the platter in 1991. 
</P>
<P>
	The ruling is believed to have been one of the first to order  
the return of an archaeological item exported in violation of 
Italy's cultural property laws. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
