<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Chargers' Riley May Start Kramer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN DIEGO (AP) -- Erik Kramer might have earned another start at  
quarterback for the San Diego Chargers. 
</P>
<P>
	And it could be a pretty big one, if that's the way coach Mike  
Riley decides to go. The Chargers play the Seattle Seahawks on 
Sunday, with the winner taking sole possession of first place in 
the AFC West. Both teams are 3-1. 
</P>
<P>
	Kramer wasn't flashy in replacing the injured Jim Harbaugh, but  
the struggling offense did make some progress in Sunday's 20-10 win 
at Detroit. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think that Erik warrants consideration as our starter,''  
said Riley, who added that it might be Wednesday before he 
announces his decision. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'll just say again, I'm really glad to have both of those  
guys here,'' Riley said. ``Even though we're not the most 
productive offense around, those guys are good leaders and give us 
a definite chance to get better offensively.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Kramer was pleased to hear that Riley is giving him strong  
consideration. But when asked if he thought he deserved to start, 
Kramer said, ``That's a platform I'm not going to stand on.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Kramer was 20-of-34 for 208 yards and one interception.  
</P>
<P>
	``As far as hanging in there, taking a lot of hits and still  
completing 20 balls and getting our team into shape on third downs, 
I thought he did an outstanding job,'' Riley said. 
</P>
<P>
	San Diego converted 7 of 15 third downs. A week earlier, it was  
just 1-of-12 in a 21-14 win over Kansas City. 
</P>
<P>
	Although he can handle returning to his backup role, Kramer said  
he'd love to start. 
</P>
<P>
	``At 34, you just never know how many times you're going to be  
out there again. I'm excited to get on the field. I had to overcome 
an injury in the offseason. I look at things maybe differently than 
I used to.'' 
</P>
<P>
	While with the Chicago Bears, Kramer missed the last half of  
1998 after undergoing knee and shoulder surgeries. 
</P>
<P>
	Harbaugh sustained two cracked ribs and a bruised throwing elbow  
in a 21-14 win over Kansas City on Oct. 3. He practiced little last 
week, but on Monday said he felt much better. 
</P>
<P>
	``I want to play, I'd like to play, Erik feels the same way. I'm  
with the program whatever they decide,'' Harbaugh said. 
</P>
<P>
	Running back Natrone Means was held out of Sunday's game to rest  
his sore ankles, and Riley said there's a good chance he'll get a 
full week of practice for the first time since before the Sept. 19 
opener at Cincinnati. 
</P>
<P>
	``If he's good enough to practice on Wednesday, that means that  
this deal was real good for him taking that game off,'' Riley said. 
</P>
<P>
	Means, who agreed with the move, said he felt fine.  
</P>
<P>
	``We're 3-1 and sitting, definitely, in a position nobody  
thought we'd be in,'' he said. ``We have a big game this Sunday and 
I had a week off to rest.'' 
</P>
<P>
	San Diego's hard-hitting defense came up big again on Sunday.  
Linebacker Junior Seau had 12 tackles, two of them sacks, and 
safety Rodney Harrison forced a fumble that cornerback Darryll 
Lewis returned 42 yards for a touchdown. 
</P>
<P>
	Although it's still early, Harrison figures a win over the  
Seahawks can win over any doubters. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's like a playoff game,'' Harrison said. ``It's time for us  
to come in here and make a statement and get the respect of the 
league. The way to get respect is to go out there and get a 
victory.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
