AMEX Mkt Value Index:          790.02  +  8.53
Nasdaq Composite Index        2,916.05  + 29.48
Gold(final) -    $318.80    troy oz., NY Comex spot month Mon.
Silver(final) -   $5.460  troy oz., NY Comex spot month Mon.

</P>
<P>
	Fed Regulators Eye Bank Mergers  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Regulators are weighing changes to deal with  
the huge banks being formed by mergers that could hurt the economy 
if they fail, Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan told bankers 
today. Greenspan said ``significant changes are in the pipeline'' 
in banking supervision by U.S. regulators and their foreign 
counterparts. The changes point to a ``multitrack approach'' to 
oversight of banks, since they vary significantly in size, business 
strategy and penchant for risk, the central bank chief said. ``Even 
among the largest banks, no two institutions have exactly the same 
risk profiles, risk controls or organizational and management 
structure,'' Greenspan told the American Bankers Association's 
annual convention in Phoenix. Copies of his speech were released in 
Washington. 

</P>
<P>
	Dell To Focus on Core PC Business  
</P>
<P>
	LAKE BUENA VISTA, Fla. (AP) -- Dell Computer Corp., the No. 1  
seller of personal computers directly to customers, says it will 
stick to its strengths despite Wall Street pressure to vigorously 
branch into areas such as computer services. While Dell's financial 
results are among the strongest in the computer industry, its stock 
price has fallen 16 percent since early this year in part because 
of investor concerns that tumbling PC prices will slow galloping 
revenues and profits. But Dell chief executive Michael Dell said 
today that computer services, or helping corporate customers set up 
and maintain their computer networks, will remain an adjunct 
activity. Dell shares were at 45 9/16, up 1/16. 

</P>
<P>
	Compaq Launches Telecom Division  
</P>
<P>
	GENEVA (AP) -- Compaq Computer Corp. announced the formation of a  
new telecommunications unit, unveiling a powerful new data system 
as part of the struggling company's bid to lessen its dependence on 
the personal computer market. The announcement by Michael D. 
Capellas, Compaq's new president and chief executive, came during a 
keynote address at Telecom 99, a major trade show this week in 
Switzerland. The company will reorganize its telecom operations 
under a new unit based in the ``Telecom Corridor'' in the north 
Dallas suburb of Plano, Compaq spokesman Alan Hodel said. Compaq 
shares were at 21 7/8, down 1/8. 

</P>
<P>
	Vanguard Reports After-Tax Figures  
</P>
<P>
	PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- In a move aimed at helping investors better  
evaluate the performance of their mutual funds, the Vanguard Group 
is starting to publish the after-tax returns for 47 of its stock 
and balanced funds. The nation's second-largest mutual fund firm is 
the first fund company to disclose after-tax returns on a broad 
range of mutual funds. The information debuts in Vanguard's U.S. 
Growth Fund and its International Growth Fund's 1999 annual reports 
being mailed to shareholders this week, Dickson said today. 

</P>
<P>
	AFL-CIO To Offer New Web Site  
</P>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- The AFL-CIO is creating an Internet gateway  
it hopes will connect its 13 million members online and serve as a 
high-tech organizing device. ``This will be a revolutionary tool 
for communications,'' said Morton Bahr, president of the 
Communications Workers of America. The Web portal site, called 
workingfamilies.com, is scheduled to be up and running by Dec. 1 
and union members will be offered Internet service at no more than 
$14.95 per month. The AFL-CIO also said it will offer members 
discounted computers, with full financing, for as little as $600. 

</P>
<P>
	Lonmin Offers To Buy Ashanti Shares  
</P>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- British mining company Lonmin PLC has offered to  
buy the 68 percent of shares in Ashanti Goldfields Co. that it 
doesn't already own. Ashanti, a gold mining company based in Ghana, 
said today it received the offer. It has been struggling to come up 
with some $270 million to pay its creditors for margin calls on 
futures contracts for the sale of gold. 

</P>
<P>
	Internet Plan Spurs Privacy Fear  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Engineers designing a new way to send  
information across the Internet want to include a unique serial 
number from each personal computer within every parcel of data. 
Privacy advocates fear it could lead to tracing of senders' 
identities. Critics warn that, if adopted, the move could 
potentially strip away a measure of anonymity and security enjoyed 
by tens of millions of home computer users who dial into America 
Online Inc. and other Internet providers over traditional telephone 
lines. 

</P>
<P>
	Airborne E-Mail Service Planned  
</P>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- Airshow Inc., a provider of flight information  
systems, unveiled plans today to offer in-flight e-mail services 
for corporate jet travelers. The service would allow customers to 
send and receive e-mail to an ``AirshowMail'' account that can be 
accessed either through a laptop computer or a special ``cabin 
management system'' provided by Airshow. The company made the 
announcement at the National Business Aviation Association 
convention in Atlanta. 

</P>
<P>
	Saturn Prepares for New Model  
</P>
<P>
	SPRING HILL, Tenn. (AP) -- Saturn plans to shut down its assembly  
lines in early January to gear up for production of its new sport 
utility vehicle, the company says. The plant normally is idled over 
the Thanksgiving weekend and for about a week between Christmas and 
New Year's Day. Saturn also will halt production for the first two 
weeks in January so that workers can move machinery and make other 
changes needed to add the SUV production. There's no word on when 
production of the SUV will begin or when it will be introduced to 
the public. 

</P>
<P>
	Colt May End Consumer Handgun Orders  
</P>
<P>
	WEST HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) -- The Colt's Manufacturing Co.,  
inventor of the six-shooter, plans to stop taking orders for most 
of its retail handguns so it can limit its liability in lawsuits, 
according to a report in Newsweek magazine. Citing unidentified 
industry sources, Newsweek said the gunmaker also will lay off as 
many as 300 of its 700 union workers in Connecticut. While the 
gun-maker informed distributors last week that it would discontinue 
at least three of its product lines, Colt's executives strongly 
disputed the implication that the company was shedding a major 
segment of its business. Colt general counsel told the Hartford 
Courant, however, that layoffs were indeed being considered. 

</P>
