<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Gore Welcomes Labor Endorsement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- As polls show Bill Bradley closing in on Al  
Gore, the vice president's camp welcomed a certain endorsement by 
the AFL-CIO as more than just a symbolic nod. ``It means 
volunteers, organizers, committed supporters'' and a hefty 
on-the-ground advantage, said campaign chairman Tony Coelho. 
</P>
<P>
	Nudged along by President Clinton, the AFL-CIO's political  
committee was preparing for a late afternoon vote that would send 
Gore's endorsement to the labor federation's executive council and, 
finally, to ratification by the more than 700 union delegates 
convened here. 
</P>
<P>
	The AFL-CIO is committed to spending at least $40 million to get  
union members to vote Democratic next year. In crucial 
early-primary states like New Hampshire and New York, where Bradley 
has edged ahead of or tied Gore in the polls, that mass union 
mobilization could tip the scales to the vice president. 
</P>
<P>
	A CNN/Gallup/USA Today poll released Monday showed Gore leading  
Bradley, 51 percent to 39 percent, among likely Democratic primary 
voters nationwide. A similar poll a few weeks ago put Gore further 
ahead, with 63 percent support to Bradley's 30 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The AFL-CIO counts nearly 580,000 union members among New York's  
registered Democrats -- about a third of all New Yorkers who voted 
in 1998. And in Iowa, whose caucuses in January will begin the 
nomination chase, AFL-CIO organizers were credited with the 69 
percent turnout of registered union voters that lifted Democrat Tom 
Vilsack from fourth place to winner of last year's gubernatorial 
race. 
</P>
<P>
	``With the kind of program we're talking about, we're able to  
not just do voter and issue education, but drive up a much bigger 
turnout,'' said AFL-CIO political director Steve Rosenthal. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a machine, though we don't like to use that word,'' said  
Kathy Bowler, director of Gore's campaign in California. 
</P>
<P>
	National campaign manager Donna Brazile showed off the  
collection of business cards pushed on her Monday by union leaders 
eager to help Gore. ``I'm delighted by all the strong support we're 
going to receive,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	An endorsement, said Coelho, will bring Gore immediate  
``volunteers, organizers and not just supporters, but committed 
supporters -- people who have a stake and want to go out and help 
you win because they know what it means.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bradley adviser Anita Dunn said Gore's institutional advantage  
is nothing new and her candidate will continue to campaign among 
workers for grassroots labor support. 
</P>
<P>
	On the campaign trail, Gore mingled with hardhats at a Phoenix  
construction site to try to cast the apparently imminent 
endorsement as a rank-and-file nod. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm very grateful for all the working men and women who have  
helped me in this campaign,'' Gore told workers who greeted him 
with applause and handshakes. 
</P>
<P>
	The endorsement stakes grew so high in the days leading up to  
this biennial convention that Clinton reached out to several labor 
leaders. He telephoned International Brotherhood of Electrical 
Workers chief J.J. Barry, and reached out to United Food and 
Commercial Workers President Doug Dority through a mutual friend. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton's message, Dority said, was that the stakes had been  
``so ginned up that we didn't want (a delay in the endorsement) to 
appear that we were doing something that would hurt'' Gore. 
</P>
<P>
	In testimony to some feeling here that Gore had taken labor for  
granted and not paid attention to where union presidents stood, 
IBEW political director Rick Diegel said Clinton called Barry over 
the weekend to say thanks, apparently unaware that Barry remained 
undecided until Monday morning. 
</P>
<P>
	A disgruntled undercurrent among some delegates and union  
officials feeling bullied by the accelerated endorsement was 
palpable on the convention floor Monday. More than one union 
officer privately griped that the rush to endorse was being 
dictated from the top down by AFL-CIO President John Sweeney. 
</P>
<P>
	Paul Hunt, an airline grounds crewman with the Transportation  
Workers, said the point should be ``to listen to all the issues 
first.'' And, he added, ``This could be a mistake in the long 
run.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Electrical worker Joe Lubitz, from St. Paul, Minn., said, ``I  
want to put my efforts behind someone who can win and I don't know 
enough about Bradley yet.'' 
</P>
<P>
	AFL-CIO officials countered that GOP front-runner George W.  
Bush's runaway popularity in polls and ever-mounting bankroll lent 
urgency to the endorsement, which frees the labor group to begin 
attacking the Texas governor's record. 




  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
